<FIRST>r a AM-SlayingsDeportation     08-25 0345</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Slayings Deportation,0355</SECOND>
<HEAD>Man Wanted in Mexican Slayings Won't Contest Deportation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TUCSON, Ariz. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The man accused in the drug-related torture
slayings of 12 people at his ranch near Agua Prieta, Mexico, will
accept deportation to Mexico, his attorney said Thursday.
   Hector Fragoso Burqueno, accused of murder and other charges in
Mexico, agreed to the deportation Thursday provided his U.S.
citizenship application remains valid, attorney Alfred S. Donau III
said following a hearing before Immigration Judge John McCarrick.
   Donau said the effect of Thursday's deal ``was to preserve
(Fragoso's) right to pursue his citizenship application and at the
same time set a date when he would be voluntarily returning to
Mexico.''
   The Tucson lawyer said Fragoso wouldn't return to Mexico at least
until Oct. 1 because he needs additional time to complete the
application process. However, Donau also said he doesn't expect the
application to be succesful until the charges in Mexico are resolved.
   Fragoso is entitled to citizenship, Donau said, because he is a
U.S. Army veteran.
   Fragoso had sought political asylum but that request was
withdrawn after McCarrick refused to bar reporters from the
courtroom.
   Donau said his witnesses consequently ``refused to testify if
their testimony would be made known to the public at large.''
   Fragoso, who remained in custody, is working to acquire Mexican
legal counsel before facing Mexico's charges of first-degree murder,
concealment of accomplices, criminal association and violation of
burial laws, Donau said.
   Mexican officials have said statements by Jesus Luis Tapia, 29,
who is believed to be involved in the slayings, placed Fragoso at
the ranch where the bodies of the torture victims were found, four
in a septic tank pit and eight others stuffed into a well. Aqua
Prieta is just across the border from Douglas.
   Authorities believe they were killed on March 24 and 25.
   Fragoso was arrested April 20 in a mobile home near Three Points,
a tiny community about 25 miles southwest of Tucson.
   Tapia was turned over to Mexican authorities Aug. 10 after he was
detained and questioned by authorities in Tucson.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
