<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 0155EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Baltic-Notebook     08-25 0728</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Baltic-Notebook,0753</SECOND>
<HEAD>Politics, Lithuanian Style: Carbon Paper and Remembering the Grand
Duke</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also in Friday AMs report.</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   This week's astonishing protest that joined an
estimated 1 million people in a human chain across the Baltic
republics was the latest tactic used by local activists to advance
their demands. Here are some other snapshots from grassroots
political life in one Soviet Baltic republic.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VILNIUS, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democracy Central here is an ornate
four-story building where the fledgling grass-roots political
movement Sajudis uses high- and low-tech to get its message across
in the drive for Lithuania's independence.
   On the third floor, college students duplicate political
statements the old fashioned way _ by typing with carbon paper. The
copying machine is broken. One floor up, the Sajudis Information
Agency uses a new fascimile machine to receive a letter from
Washington signed by members of Congress supporting freedom for the
Baltic republics.
   The offices of Sajudis, just over a year old, have all the
trappings of an upstart citizens group struggling with meager
resources to change the world. There aren't enough phones, chairs or
desks, and the staircase is crumbling, but there is no shortage of
dedication.
   Dozens of helpers stream through the offices. Hundreds of people
stop daily at the newsstand on the ground floor to pick up a copy of
the Sajudis newspaper.
   The very existence of the office is an important political
accomplishment in a country where the government tightly controls
allotment of buildings, phones and copying machines.
   The windows look out on Vilnius' Cathedral Square, where protest
posters demanding ``Occupiers Go Home'' _ a reference to the Soviet
soldiers who have been stationed in the republic since 1940 _ and
``Freedom for Lithuania'' are displayed around a bell tower.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   Although the drive for independence is gradually gaining
official, ambiguously worded support from the Lithuanian Communist
Party, sometimes activists have to settle for symbolism.
   Dozens of streets have been de-Sovietized, or given back the
names they had before the Red Army tanks rolled in in 1940 and made
Lithuania a part of the Soviet Union.
   The street where Sajudis headquarters is located, Lenin Prospect,
was recently renamed for Gediminas, the Grand Duke of Lithuania, who
made Vilnius the capital in 1322.
   A poster on the wall of Sajudis headquarters spells out the word
perestroika, President Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reform drive, in
fading letters. A calendar depicts the currency used when Lithuania
was independent from 1918-1940. Independence activists hope the
republic will soon be able to have its own currency again.
   Graffiti artists are getting into the act. ``Red Army Go Home''
was painted in red in English on a sidewalk near a hotel frequented
by foreigners.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   They are portrayed as bride and groom or as soldiers with blood
dripping from their mouths, and are constant targets of both verbal
and physical abuse.
   Mere mention of Adolf Hitler and Josef Stalin once struck hatred,
loathing or fear into the hearts of millions, but in the Baltics,
the two dictators are now openly ridiculed.
   Attacking Hitler is certainly not new in the Soviet Union, and
Stalin is now officially vilified for ``repressing'' millions of
people and setting up the tight, centrally commanded economy that
Gorbachev is trying to streamline.
   But the open accusation that Stalin was in cahoots with Hitler is
relatively new.
   ``For the first time we pondered and publicly announced that
Stalin and Hitler were branches of the same tree, and their policy
was equally disastrous for our small Lithuania,'' the Vilnius
Communist Party newspaper Vecherniye Novosti (Evening News) said
Wednesday.
   The most dramatic attack on the men who engineered the carving up
of Lithuania, Estonia and Latvia in a secret 1939 agreement was
their burning in effigy Wednesday. Members of the Lithuanian Liberty
League _ a radical group that demands Lithuania secede from the
Soviet Union _ carried a Hitler-Stalin, two-headed soldier through
downtown Vilnius on the anniversary of the secret deal.
   The effigy was carried to an independence rally in a park, where
a speaker said the two dictators ``drank from one glass the blood of
Lithuania.'' To wind up the demonstration, the effigy was burned.
Orange flames quickly engulfed it, sending black smoke and ashes
aloft. The dictators' heads and their blood-smeared mouths were the
last to go up in smoke.
</TEXT>
