<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 0014EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u a AM-TheWho     08-25 0437</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-The Who,0451</SECOND>
<HEAD>Legendary Rock Group Stages Rock Opera `Tommy' One More Time</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN ANTCZAK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNIVERSAL CITY, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Who blasted off nearly a decade
of rust with a thundering performance of their rock opera ``Tommy''
on Thursday night, bringing a graying crowd of baby boomer fans to
their feet.
   Led by a 44-year-old Roger Daltrey, the Who put on a stirring
rendition of their old act, minus the guitar-smashing antics of 20
years ago.
   ``Everyone here is obviously full of love and good feelings,''
said former LSD advocate Timothy Leary, who once coined the phrase
``Turn on, tune in, drop out.''
   Leary joked about his status as a hallucinogenic guru of the
1960s. ``Well, to tell the truth, I've just taken some mushroom,''
Leary quipped as the Who stepped onto stage.
   The sold-out Universal Amphitheater show was the second of only
two complete performances of ``Tommy'' scheduled on the 25-city
reunion tour of the Who's Daltrey, Pete Townshend and John Entwistle.
   A well-dressed crowd of people in the 30s and 40s walked into the
amphitheater reading warning signs that announced sound levels could
cause hearing impairment.
   Only the faintest odor of a rare whiff of marijuana smoke could
be detected.
   The saga of ``the deaf, dumb and blind kid'' who becomes a
fantastic pinball player also featured Elton John, reprising his
1975 movie role as the Pinball Wizard, Steve Winwood as the Hawker,
Phil Collins as Uncle Ernie, Billy Idol as Cousin Kevin, and Patti
Labelle as Gypsy, the Acid Queen.
   The show, benefiting the Nordoff-Robbins Music Therapy
Foundation, was available live on a pay-per-view basis for $19.95
per subscriber on King Biscuit Television, a division of DIR
Broadcasting.
   The tour's first performance of ``Tommy'' was in June at Radio
City Music Hall in New York and featured the band and supporting
musicians.
   Bob Meyrowitz, president of DIR, said the show had a potential
audience of 12.5 million households.
   The New York performance was ``really mind-boggling,'' but the
West Coast staging made the opera ``a much more musical piece,''
Meyrowitz said.
   The Who came together in London in 1964 and were a premiere rock
band through the 1970s. Drummer Keith Moon died in 1978 and the
remaining members of the band retired in 1982 after a concert in
Toronto.
   Who albums between 1965 and 1982 included ``My Generation,''
``Happy Jack,'' ``The Who Sell Out,'' ``On Tour: Magic Bus,''
``Tommy,'' ``Live at Leeds,'' ``Who's Next,'' ``Meaty, Beaty, Big
and Bouncy,'' ``Quadrophenia,'' ``Odds and Sods,'' ``The Who by
Numbers,'' ``Who Are You,'' ``The Kids Are Alright,'' ``Face
Dances,'' and ``It's Hard.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
