<DOCNO> AP890825-0008 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 0311EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Chronology     08-25 0332</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Chronology,0350</SECOND>
<HEAD>Key Events in Poland's Post-War History</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Major events in Poland's post-war history:
   Sept. 1, 1939 _ Germany invades Poland. Soviet Union attacks from
the east 16 days later. Poland spends rest of war under German and
Soviet occupation.
   April 1943 _ Soviet Union breaks relations with exiled Polish
government in London.
   July 22, 1944 _ Soviets install ``Polish Committee of National
Liberation.'' Six months later they recognize this committee as
Polish government.
   June 28, 1945 _ Following Yalta conference, Soviet-dominated
Polish Provisional Government of National Unity formed.
   Sept. 1980 _ Discontent underlying strikes intensified by
revelations of government and Communist Party corruption and
mismanagement. Party leader Edward Gierek ousted.
   Dec. 13, 1981 _ Workers threaten general strike and Gen. Wojciech
Jaruzelski declares martial law, interning thousands of Solidarity
members, including Lech Walesa.
   Oct. 8, 1982 _ Solidarity is banned and official trade union
alliance is created to take its place.
   Nov. 11, 1982 _ Walesa is freed.
   July 22, 1983 _ Jaruzelski lifts martial law but leaves many
restrictive edicts in place.
   1984-1987 _ Amnesty is approved for political prisoners and
eventually all are freed.
   Aug.-Sept. 1988 _ Strikes spread across Poland, creating worst
labor strife in seven years. Strikes end when Walesa asks for time
to talk with the government.
   Feb. 6, 1989 _ Negotiations begin with government.
   April 5, 1989 _ Deliberations conclude with endorsement of new
``social contract,'' including overhaul of legislative system and
partly democratic elections. Solidarity is granted legal status.
   June 4, 1989 _ Solidarity is overwhelming winner over Communist
Party in legislative elections.
   Aug. 16, 1989 _ Peasant and Democratic parties, former Communist
Party allies, endorse Walesa's plan for a governing coalition led by
Solidarity.
   Aug. 18, 1989 _ Jaruzelski approves Solidarity-led coalition.
   Aug. 19, 1989 _ Jaruzelski nominates journalist and Solidarity
activist Tadeusz Mazowiecki to be prime minister.
   Thursday _ The Sejm, the lower house of the National Assembly,
overwhelmingly approves Mazowiecki as prime minister.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890825-0009 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 0146EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Video-Lawsuit     08-25 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Video-Lawsuit,0392</SECOND>
<HEAD>Judge Issues Restraining Order on Video Law</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY STREFF BUZBEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KANSAS CITY, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state law that would have barred the
sale or rental of violent videotapes to children was blocked
Thursday by a federal judge who said the measure might clash with
the right of free speech.
   Under the law signed June 20 by Gov. John Ashcroft, video
retailers could be fined as much as $200 for renting or selling
so-called ``slasher films,'' to children under age 17. The law was
to take effect Monday.
   ``The gray areas are the important ones in this case, aren't
they?'' said U.S. District Judge B. Brook Bartlett. ``Because that's
where a prosecutor and store owner could have a difference of
opinion that could get the store owner in trouble.''
   The measure, which would also apply to videos considered
pornographic under Missouri law, would require stores to maintain
separate display areas for violent films.
   Video industry groups and retailers challenged the law with a
class action lawsuit and sought the temporary restraining order,
arguing that the law would force video store owners to decide by
Monday which videos fell under the law.
   The lawsuit names Attorney General William Webster and Cole
County prosecutor Richard Callahan contends the law violates
constitutional rights of free expression, equal protection and due
process of law.
   The Missouri law restricts videos that, based on contemporary
community standards, would be interpreted by the average person to
have ``a tendency to cater or appeal to morbid interest in
violence'' for persons under 17, that depict violence that is
``patently offensive'' and lack ``serious literary, artistic,
political or scientific value.''
   The lawsuit said the law would require video retailers to limit
sale and rental of videos that are not obscene and not
constitutionally subject to restriction under state or federal law.
   The lawsuit said terms such as ``violence'' and ``morbid'' have
no certain meaning. It also criticized the law for applying
arbitrarily to videos only, and not to identical expression in
television, movie theaters and magazines.
   The lawsuit was filed by the Video Software Dealers Association,
the Missouri Retailers Association, the Missouri Grocers Association
and the Motion Picture Association of America and two retailers,
Video Express, Inc. of Kansas City and Bailey's C.C. Enterprises Inc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
