<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica-School Bjt   08-25 0640</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-School, Bjt,0657</SECOND>
<HEAD>Parents, Students, Staff Seek to Save School by Integrating it</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID CRARY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It's a quintessentially South
African paradox. Johannesburg Girls High School has been ordered
closed for lack of pupils, yet its neighborhood abounds with
schoolgirls who wish they could enroll.
   Throughout its 102-year existence, the inner-city school has been
open only to whites. Now, with closure imminent because of white
flight to the suburbs, its students, teachers and parents are
petitioning for it to become South Africa's first multiracial
government-run school.
   ``We should prove to the rest of the world we can do it,'' said
Candice Bond, a 15-year-old student excited by the idea of black
classmates. ``Our school should feel privileged if it could be the
first.''
   The government has given no sign it will be swayed by the ``Save
Our School'' campaign, even though organizers say they have gathered
12,000 signatures supporting integration at the city's oldest high
school.
   But Sharon Bond, mother of Candice and chairman of the campaign,
says she hopes that mounting pressure might prompt the government to
reconsider its decision to close the school in December.
   On a brick wall at the school was a poster with the initials
S.O.S. _ for ``Save Our School'' _ and a crayon drawing showing a
white girl and black girl side by side, dressed in the school's
uniform.
   The school was built to accommodate 630 students, and now has
203. It is in the heart of the country's largest ``gray area,''
where thousands of black and Indian families have moved in defiance
of residential segregation laws.
   Acting President F.W. de Klerk, favored to win a full five-year
term after the Sept. 6 parliamentary elections, says he opposes
discrimination and favors legalization of selected multiracial
neighborhoods. But he has recommitted himself to the concept of
segregated public schools.
   Asked about Johannesburg Girls High School, he said children
should have ``mother-tongue education among people of their own
community.''
   Parents who wanted multiracial education could send their
children to integrated, state-subsidized private schools, de Klerk
said.
   But Mrs. Bond said most girls at the high school were from
low-income or single-parent families and could not afford the cost
of private schools.
   The parent-elected management council at Johannesburg Girls High
has been criticized by some parents for failing to consult the
school community fully before it advised the government to either
integrate the facility or close it.
   But council chairman Jack Foster said the declining enrollment
left no other option.
   ``It wasn't educationally viable anymore,'' he said. ``We
couldn't offer the variety of subjects you need in a high school
like that.''
   ``It's a great, great pity,'' he added. ``The facilities are all
there. It seems crazy not to utilize them.''
   The school is a spacious complex of modern red-brick buildings on
the border of Hillbrow and Berea, two neighborhoods dominated by
high-rise apartment buildings. They officially are designated as
``whites only,'' but an estimated 60,000 blacks, Indians and people
of mixed race have moved in and the government has virtually halted
enforcement of residential segregation laws in the area.
   However, no state schools have been established for these
non-white families. Their children must either go to costly private
schools or commute long distances to crowded, poorly equipped public
schools in outlying townships.
   Mrs. Bond said some black children spend nearly four hours daily
commuting to and from schools in Soweto, southwest of Johannesburg.
   If it closes, Johannesburg Girls High could be the first of many.
A new study by education specialists at Johannesburg's University of
the Witwatwersrand said 42 of the city's 175 white schools are at
risk of closure within five years because of declining enrollments.
   The study calculated that there were 13,150 vacant places for
students in the city's schools.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
