<FIRST>r w PM-CocaineMonkeys     08-25 0611</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Cocaine Monkeys,610</SECOND>
<HEAD>Monkeys Lose Cocaine Interest After Buprenorphine Shots, Researcher
Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL RECER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A pain-reliever that causes laboratory monkeys
to lose interest in cocaine may now be tested to see if it can help
human addicts lose the craving for drugs, researchers say in an
article published today.
   Researchers at a Harvard Medical School drug abuse research
center report that five Rhesus monkeys that had been dosing
themselves regularly with cocaine chose to ignore the drug after
receiving injections of buprenorphine. The study appears in the
journal Science.
   Dr. Jack H. Mendelson, a co-investigator in the research, said as
a result of the animals' response to buprenorphine, clinical studies
are proposed to determine if the analgesic will help people overcome
dependence on cocaine and heroin.
   ``We feel that it (buprenorphine) may provide an opportunity for
some persons to stop using cocaine and not feel the adverse effects
of cessation,'' Mendelson said in a telephone interview. ``This
would provide a window in time for someone who might be able to stop
using the drug and ultimately become drug-free.''
   In the laboratory studies, five Rhesus monkeys were fitted with
intravenous catheters that were connected to pumps operated by
levers. Each monkey, if it chose to, could press the lever and
receive a small dose of cocaine.
   ``The monkeys self-administer cocaine, but are under no
compulsion to do so,'' Mendelson said. ``It is completely an
elective act.''
   He said earlier studies showed that when given this choice, nine
out of 10 Rhesus monkeys will press the lever for cocaine, though
they will choose not to self-administer some other types of
pharmaceuticals.
   Mendelson said that when the five test monkeys received
injections of buprenorphine, their cocaine use rapidly declined, and
approached zero use at some doses of the buprenorphine.
   When a type of placebo, saline solution, was injected, the
monkeys chose to press the cocaine lever repeatedly.
   ``The placebo didn't do anything,'' Mendelson said. ``But the
buprenorphine suppressed the cocaine self-administration.''
   At the same time, he said, the monkeys continued to press another
lever to receive banana pellets, and otherwise behaved normally
while taking the buprenorphine.
   ``It doesn't produce the behavior changes and its safety is
enormous,'' said the researcher.
   Mendelson said buprenorphine may be particularly useful in
weaning abusers away from ``speedball,'' a combination of heroin and
cocaine that is becoming more widely used by drug-dependent people.
   ``We've tried (buprenorphine) in heroin-dependent persons and
most of them report they can detect that they've had a drug, but it
doesn't produce the degree of euphoria and certainly not the rush of
a drug like heroin or methadone,'' he said. ``Most of the people who
are heroin-dependent who have used the drug report that they don't
feel high, but they feel normal.''
   The factors of drug addiction are highly complex and stopping
dependence is not easy, Mendelson said. Though it appears that
buprenorphine would not become a ``substitute addiction'' for
cocaine, he said, it does not represent a ``magic bullet'' for the
effortless control of substance abuse, but possibly only an aide for
controlling such dependence.
   ``Some people,'' he noted, ``will abuse chicken soup.''
   Buprenorphine is commonly used in Britain for relief of moderate
pain, and is used in U.S. hospitals as an injectable pain reliever.
Norwich Eaton Pharmaceuticals Inc. markets it as the prescription
drug Buprenex.
   The Rhesus monkey study was coauthored by Mendelson, Nancy K.
Mello, Mark P. Bree and Scott E. Lukas, all researchers at the
Harvard Medical School-McLean Hospital drug abuse research center in
Belmont, Mass.
   Science, which published the study, is the journal of the
American Association for the Advancement of Science.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
