<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Deportee Bjt   08-25 0677</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Deportee, Bjt,0699</SECOND>
<HEAD>Deportation Order Tears at Palestinian Family</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EILEEN ALT POWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RAMALLAH, Occupied West Bank (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Amal Aruri steeled herself
for the worst but still found she was unprepared when the Israeli
Supreme Court ordered her husband deported to Lebanon.
   ``We fought it for more a year,'' Mrs. Aruri said, her voice
shaking. ``Even though I expected it day by day, still I was
shocked.''
   The 28-year-old Palestinian nursery school teacher learned from
Israeli radio news that an appeal by her husband, physics professor
Taysir Aruri, was rejected by the court Thursday. He is accused of
being a leader of the Palestinian uprising.
   The deportation order is expected to be carried out within a week
and could mean a long separation for the family. Mrs. Aruri has no
passport and fears she will not get special travel passes from the
Israeli military government.
   ``I haven't told the children yet,'' she said in an interview,
adding she was waiting ``until we can sit alone together ... maybe
at bedtime.''
   On Thursday, the sitting room in the family's white stone house
was crowded with relatives who came to lend support and distract the
three Aruri children, ages 2 to 7, while Mrs. Aruri talked with
lawyers and reporters.
   Taysir Aruri, a 43-year-old physicist at the West Bank's Bir Zeit
University, was served on Aug. 17, 1988, with a deportation order
signed by Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin.
   He has been jailed since in Juneid Prison near Nablus.
   Aruri was never tried but was accused by the army of being a
member of the outlawed Palestinian Communist Party and of being
``involved in planning the intefadeh and a member of the unified
command of the intefadeh.''
   ``Intefadeh'' is the Arabic word for the uprising Palestinians
have been waging since December 1987 against Israeli occupation of
the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The Supreme Court does not hear arguments in deportation cases
and only decides if the army acted properly. The court has never
overturned a deportation order.
   London-based Amnesty International has adopted Aruri as a
``prisoner of conscience,'' and hundreds of scientists in America,
Canada and Europe signed petitions and launched a letter-writing
campaign on his behalf.
   ``Maybe they didn't know they were dealing with a very cold
government here,'' Mrs. Aruri said.
   Her husband was one of four Palestinians whose petitions were
rejected Thursday. The others are Odeh Yusef Maali and Majed Labadi,
both union organizers, and Mohammed Matur, a teacher. Labidi's
brother, Mohammed, also a union leader, was expelled in June.
   The new expulsions to Lebanon will raise the number of deportees
to 59.
   The United States, the United Nations and international human
rights groups have said repeatedly that the practice violates
international law.
   This was not Aruri's first run-in with Israeli authorities. He
was jailed from 1974 to 1978 without charge or trial under Israeli
administrative detention procedures. Then, too, he was championed by
Amnesty International.
   Asked about the allegation that her husband is a leader of the
uprising, Mrs. Aruri said: ``I think every Palestinian is a leader
of the intefadeh. It doesn't depend on leaders, really, since it is
a popular revolution.''
   Petitions on Aruri's behalf, including one signed by nearly 1,000
foreign scientists and published in the English-language Jerusalem
Post in May, describe him as ``a man of peace.''
   An outspoken critic of the occupation, Aruri has urged an
international conference leading to creation of a separate
Palestinian state beside Israel, an idea long opposed by Israel's
government.
   Two months before he was arrested, Aruri joined other prominent
Palestinian and Israeli artists and intellectuals in signing a
``peace treaty'' calling for dialogue. He has argued that there can
be no military solution to the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Mrs. Aruri said the couple's children knew their father might be
deported to Lebanon.
   Natasha, the 5-year-old, often asked during weekly prison visits
about his future: ``Can we come to visit you? ... When will you come
home?''
   ``Right now I don't have answers for her,'' Mrs. Aruri said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
