<FIRST>r w PM-Contras     08-25 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Contras,460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Contra Appeals Court Rules on Torture-Murder Death</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Contra spokesman predicts the State
Department will object to a rebel appeals court decision that
exonerates a top commander found guilty in March of covering up a
murder.
   The Contra court, made up of four civilian lawyers living in
Miami, also upheld the conviction of one Contra commander and
reduced charges against four others in a torture-murder case, rebel
spokesman Bosco Matamoros said Thursday.
   Five of the six Contras were given dishonorable discharges _ the
stiffest penalty that can be handed out by the Contra internal court
system that was set up in 1987. Leniency was recommended for one,
according to a document obtained by The Associated Press.
   It could not be independently confirmed if the expulsions were
carried out.
   Meanwhile, the rebels fired their chief representative in
Washington, Ernesto Palazio, charging him with abuses of Contra
funds that Matamoros said could run into the hundreds of thousands
of dollars. Palazio, believed to be in Miami, could not immediately
be reached for comment.
   A 1986 law prohibits U.S.-supplied aid to any group that includes
a person ``found to engage in gross violations of internationally
recognized human rights.''
   A State Department official, speaking on condition he not be
identified, said the appeal would be reviewed.
   ``If they are guilty and maintained in the resistance, that
creates a problem,'' the official said. ``We will review the verdict
of the appeals tribunal and see what procedures were followed and
how they arrived at their decision.''
   Matamoros said he expected the State Department to object to the
dismissal of charges that Commander Mack, the chief of intelligence
for the Contras, covered up a murder. Mack was a member of the
national guard under the late Nicaraguan dictator Anastasio Somoza.
   Mack reportedly violated a State Department order that he be
suspended from his duties until after the appeal.
   The Contra tribunal found that rebel commander Isaac Blacker
Hurtado, known as Israelita, ``had the premeditated intention of
murdering Managua 2,'' a man who was killed in November 1988.
   The victim was suspected of being an agent of Nicaragua's
Sandinista government. The six Contras were charged in March by a
Contra court in connection with the murder and several rapes in
northern Nicaragua. The United States pressed for the investigation.
   The lawyers upheld charges of torture and cruel and inhuman
punishment against Israelita, as well as Contras known as Rambo,
Pandillero, Ali and Nolan. The judges recommended leniency for
Nolan, saying he joined the Contra ranks at age 15 and lost an eye
in the fight.
   The rebels, backed by the United States since 1981, have been
fighting to overthrow the leftist Sandinista government in
Nicaragua. Matamoros said he did not know the whereabouts of the
expelled commanders but believed they were in Nicaragua.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890825-0024 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 0242EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w PM-EnergyForecast     08-25 0439</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Energy Forecast,430</SECOND>
<HEAD>Forecasters Say Utilities Must Build Many More Power Plants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Electric utilities in the coming decade will
have to build at least twice as much generating capacity as
previously planned to meet the nation's growing appetite for
electricity, an industry group says.
   In an otherwise bright outlook for energy supplies and prices,
the Gas Research Institute said Thursday that the Northeast will
face a serious squeeze in electricity.
   ``The likelihood of a shortfall in electric utility generating
capacity, particularly in the near term, to the year 2000 and
through the 1990s, is very high,'' said Daniel Dreyfus, the group's
vice president for strategic planning and analysis.
   He said an electricity pinch in New England was ``now virtually
unavoidable,'' because demand would outstrip supply before new power
plants can be built.
   Even if the nation's electricity use grows relatively slowly to
2000, electric utilities will have to build at least 45 gigawatts of
new capacity _ roughly equivalent to 45 new large-scale power plants
_ beyond the 46 gigawatts of capacity already on the drawing board,
the report said.
   The research group, sponsored by natural gas pipeline and
distribution companies, also said the big increase in world oil
prices that many forecasters have projected for the mid-1990s is
unlikely to hit before the turn of the century.
   A key reason for expecting a longer period of stable prices, it
said, is that oil production in high-cost fields, such as the North
Sea, has remained strong. Some high-cost production has been lost _
particularly in the United States _ but the overall decline has been
smaller than expected after the 1986 price crash.
   Oil prices by 1995 are likely to be about $18 a barrel in current
dollars, rising to about $20 a barrel by 2000, the group said. Oil
is selling for about $18 a barrel, up from about $15 a barrel last
year.
   A faster price escalation is likely after the turn of the
century, Dreyfus said, as world oil demand moves closer into balance
with available supplies. The forecast said the price, in current
dollars, would be about $32 a barrel in 2010.
   Low oil prices during the 1990s imply a generally stable price
for all types of energy, including natural gas, coal and products
made from oil, such as gasoline, the forecast said. This is because
oil is the most versatile and dominant energy source.
   The report also said U.S. oil imports would reach 13.4 million
barrels a day by 2010, nearly double the current rate and meeting
about two-thirds of total U.S. oil needs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
