<FIRST>r a PM-Kiss-OffWedding     08-25 0448</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kiss-Off Wedding,0460</SECOND>
<HEAD>Couple in Kiss-Off Contest Plan Wedding; Others Aim for $10,000 Prize</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LAURA MYERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RENO, Nev. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The minister won't have to tell Lloyd Gubler he
may kiss the bride when he and his fiancee get married at noon
Saturday.
   Gubler, 23, and Laura Bradley, 25, both of Reno, have had their
lips locked at least 12 hours a day since Aug. 12 as contestants in
the Great Amercian Kiss-Off Contest in a furniture store's parking
lot.
   Gubler, an auto body shop foreman, and Ms. Bradley, who works in
a retail store, said Thursday the only thing that worries them about
tying the knot during the contest is that the vows won't be read
fast enough.
   ``We're concerned about the time factor since we only receive
five minutes per hour break time,'' Gubler said in between smooches.
   The couple is trying to accumulate break time for the wedding
ceremony; but if they must, they'll just say muffled ``I dos'' with
lips touching.
   Under rules of the contest, in its 14th day, couples must kiss
for 12 hours a day, 9 a.m. to 9 p.m.
   Marsha Thomas, spokeswoman for the contest, quipped that the
official who conducts the wedding will probably tell the couple,
``You may kiss the bride _ for another 30 days in a row.''
   Gubler and Ms. Bradley are one of six hardy couples among a
starting 15 who are still in the contest, which has become more than
a lark for those counting on the $10,000 top prize.
   ``There are some people competing out here who really need the
money,'' Ms. Thomas said. ``Right now, it appears that the six
couples left will go on forever.''
   Menette McVey, 19, of Reno, won't be able to last too long,
however. She's nearly eight months pregnant and is relying on the
$10,000 to pay hospitals bills when she gives birth.
   In applying to enter the contest, Ms. McVey and Jason Knapp, 20,
her kissing partner and father of the baby, both simply put ``baby''
for the reason why they entered the contest.
   Contestant Lori Block, 25, of Reno, lost her bank job this week
because the contest was going on too long, said Butch Lynn,
spokesman for the Kiss-Off. She's counting on the money to use
during a job search.
   ``I guess she didn't tell the bank she was going to enter this
until about a week before and they weren't too happy,'' Lynn said.
   Her partner, Bret Watson, 26, is a financial planner and
apparently is making good use of his kissing time by plotting ways
to make money. He's reading ``Think and Grow Rich'' among other
books.
</TEXT>
