<FIRST>r w PM-HUD-Demery     08-25 0486</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-HUD-Demery,480</SECOND>
<HEAD>Demery Approved HUD Subsidies for Boston Project after Recusing Himself</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KIM I. MILLS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Newly released documents show that a top HUD
official in the Reagan administration removed himself from dealing
with a Boston housing project in 1988 but approved a $51 million
federal subsidy for it two months later.
   ``Please let this memorandum serve as a formal notification of my
recusal in all matters arising from and pertaining to'' developer
Arthur D. Winn, Thomas T. Demery, who was Housing and Urban
Development assistant secretary for housing, said in July 1988 memo
about the Castle Square project in Boston's South End.
   However, Demery signed a Sept. 30, 1988, memo announcing a $51.2
million grant to the project.
   The recusal memo was among Demery's files, which were opened to
the media Thursday in response to a Freedom of Information request.
Demery, now a private consultant, is under scrutiny in the probe of
alleged fraud, abuse and mismanagement at HUD during the Reagan
years.
   Demery's files also revealed that he was lobbying in late 1988 to
be named HUD secretary, even while he was under investigation by
HUD's inspector general.
   Winn, a Massachusetts developer who owns the Bostonian Hotel, was
under contract in 1988 to buy Castle Square from Ronald Drucker.
Both men contributed to Demery's pet charity, F.O.O.D. for Africa,
with Winn holding a fund-raiser at his hotel, according to an
internal HUD investigation released earlier this year.
   HUD's inspector general concluded that Demery may have misused
his position to induce contractors seeking HUD-subsidized business
to contribute to the charity, but the Justice Department said last
month that it saw no evidence of criminal wrongdoing.
   In the memo released Thursday, Demery wrote to HUD's Under
Secretary Carl D. Covitz:
   ``The circumstances leading up to this decision to recuse myself
are nebulous at best; I think I would rather err on the side of
conservative safety, lest any appearance problem unnecessarily
occur.''
   Demery could not be reached for comment Thursday. A woman
answering his phone said he was on vacation.
   Winn was traveling on business, and Drucker had gone for the day
and could not be reached, their offices said Thursday.
   Demery is a former Michigan real estate agent and mortgage broker
who worked in Ronald Reagan's 1980 presidential campaign. As
assistant housing secretary, he administered several of HUD's
biggest programs, including $225 million in moderate-rehabilitation
funds awarded annually and the massive Federal Housing
Administration's mortgage insurance program.
   The rehabilitation program has been revealed to be governed by
influence-peddling while the FHA has been losing millions of dollars
annually through loan defaults and mismanagement.
   In his campaign to be named HUD secretary, Demery sent a Dec. 7
form letter to several members of Congress and a Bush transition
official asking for their support and seeking meetings to discuss
his qualifications.
   The position went to former Rep. Jack Kemp, R-N.Y.
</TEXT>
