<FIRST>u a AM-HUD-Pierce     08-25 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-HUD-Pierce,0388</SECOND>
<HEAD>Pierce Defends His Performance As HUD Chief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Secretary of Housing and Urban
Development Samuel R. Pierce Jr. denied allegations of favoritism at
HUD and accused critics of misrepresenting his performance,
according to a newspaper interview.
   ``Everybody was treated the same,'' he told the Los Angeles Times
in an interview published in Friday's editions. ``That was the
advice and the word that I gave to the people at HUD.''
   The interview marked Pierce's first public comments about the HUD
furor since he testified before Congress May 25.
   Pierce contradicted that testimony in asserting in the interview
that he was a hands-on manager. He said, however, that he did not
know of the extensive influence allegedly exercised by his former
executive assistant, Deborah Gore Dean.
   Pierce said his efforts to help former law partners did not
breach his pledge to sever his ties from the firm because he
received no financial benefit from the favors and had no agreement
to return to the firm.
   Testimony by former HUD officials and documents has portrayed the
agency under Pierce, who served throughout the Reagan
administration, as plagued by mismanagement and influence peddling.
   Pierce would not discuss some subjects, the Times reported. He
noted that he is scheduled to testify again Sept. 15 and has a deal
with a magazine he would not identify to publish his complete story
next month.
   But Pierce strongly rejected allegations that high-powered
Republicans were given preferential treatment by HUD, saying that
funding for projects was based on the merits.
   ``You would look at their project and, if was a worthy project,
they would be treated favorably. If not they would lose it,'' he
said. ``That was the basic approach to all of these. It wasn't an
approach that, if they are a Republican, you have got to add 10
points or give them something extra.''
   Pierce said he believes some members of Congress are attacking
his operation of HUD and misrepresenting his performance because
these lawmakers' traditional role in lobbying for HUD grants was
taken over in part by consultants.
   Developers have testified that they paid large amounts of money
to consultants because the developers thought that doing so was
essential to winning HUD action in the Pierce years.
</TEXT>
