<FIRST>u w AM-Frank-Prostitute     08-25 0383</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Frank-Prostitute,360</SECOND>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITS a0457 to add byline</HEAD>
<HEAD>Frank Admits Hiring Prostitute for Personal Staff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROSE ANN ROBERTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., acknowledged he
hired a male prostitute as a personal employee but fired him when
the congressman became suspicious the man was selling sex from
Frank's home on Capitol Hill.
   ``I was victimized,'' Frank said in a telephone interview from
Boston with The Associated Press early Friday morning. ``Yes, I
showed poor judgment.''
   Frank, an acknowledged homosexual, confirmed details of a story
in Friday's editions of The Washington Times.
   A man identified by the Times as Greg Davis told the newspaper
that Frank was aware that sex was being sold from the congressman's
apartment and was concerned that it might be discovered. The
newspaper said Davis was a professional name and it did not disclose
his real name.
   However, Frank called those allegations ``absolutely untrue.''
   When asked if the revelations might force him to resign from
Congress, Frank replied: ``Of course not.'' He said he planned to
run for re-election for a sixth term in 1990.
   He said he planned to hold a news conference at his Boston office
Friday morning.
   Frank said he met the man, whom he identified as Steve Gobie,
through an ``escort-model'' advertisement in a Washington gay
newspaper. He admitted having paid sex with Gobie, but said the
relationship later became one of friendship.
   ``He was a male prostitute and I thought he was ... smart enough
to do something else,'' Frank told the AP. ``I said he should get a
job.''
   Frank said he hired Gobie as a personal assistant to do work
around his house, drive his car and run errands. Gobie was paid with
personal money, Frank said.
   ``He was using me. I didn't see that,'' Frank said, adding that
he had no first-hand proof that Gobie was running a prostitution
service from Frank's apartment.
   Frank said he became suspicious when his landlady told him there
were ``strange goings-on'' at the house when he was away.
   ``I didn't have anything to go to court with,'' Frank said,
calling the situation ``intolerable.''
   In August 1986, Frank said: ``I called him and ordered him out. I
fired him.''
   There was no telephone listing for Gobie in Washington or its
suburbs.
</TEXT>
