<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Communists     08-25 0545</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Communists,0564</SECOND>
<HEAD>Most Communist Party Lawmakers Fall Behind Solidarity Prime Minister</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A majority of Communist Party lawmakers
voted for Solidarity's Tadeusz Mazowiecki as prime minister,
embracing the former adversary for his integrity and expressing hope
that he can help save a country in crisis.
   ``I accepted his election with the full conviction that the
government has an excellent helmsman who will steer this boat to
hope and not lead it into the shallows,'' lawmaker Tadeusz Fiszbach,
a deputy Sejm speaker from the Communist Party, said after the vote
Thursday.
   Mazowiecki received at least 91 of the votes from the 173-member
Communist caucus, whose deputies were allowed to vote as they wished
in a departure from traditional party discipline.
   The vote in the Sejm, or lower house of the National Assembly,
was 378-4 with 41 abstentions. Thirty-seven deputies did not appear
for the vote.
   ``There's a lot of them, a lot!'' exclaimed Solidarity journalist
Ewa Milewicz, peering from a balcony as she tried to count the
Communist votes in the Sejm.
   Fiszbach, who sat across the table from Mazowiecki to negotiate
accords that led to legalization of Solidarity in August 1980,
remembered the new prime minister ``as an honest, noble man with
high values, an excellent negotiator and politician.''
   Fiszbach later was stripped of his post as party chief in Gdansk
and his Politburo seat because of his sympathy for Solidarity.
   Army Col. Czeslaw Kosinski, another Communist deputy, also
supported Solidarity's choice for prime minister.
   ``I voted for Tadeusz Mazowiecki because the other Polish
political situation was worse. I know there is now hope that our
system can improve itself,'' he said.
   ``Things will be hard. The job of the prime minister will be to
obtain credibility,'' he said. ``Poles must believe in something and
he (Mazowiecki) is the one who has the best chances.''
   In Moscow, the Soviet Council of Ministers, or Soviet Cabinet,
sent a telegram congratulating Mazowiecki and expressed ``the
certainty that the traditional relations of friendship and
all-around cooperation between the Soviet Union and Poland will
continue.''
   An interview with Mazowiecki also was printed Thursday in the
Soviet government's evening newspaper, Izvestia. The new Polish
leader was quoted as saying his government would be open to all,
including the Polish Communist Party, but that the time was clearly
past ``when only one camp could form the government.''
   Solidarity has promised the Communists the strategic ministries
of defense and interior, which control the army and the police.
   ``I am convinced that the party will be represented in the
government and will cooperate. It is a new stage of democracy,''
said Fiszbach.
   Mazowiecki on Wednesday indicated that he would find additional
spots in the Cabinet for the Communists.
   For the first time in 45 years, the party will not lead the
government and Communist deputies say it is time for their movement
to develop new directions.
   ``The party now has a chance to form a new program ... Without
being on the front line,'' said Kosinski.
   In line with the change, a group of 15 deputies on Thursday
submitted a proposal to drop from the constitution the clause that
mandates that the Communist Party be ``the leading political force.''
</TEXT>
