<DOCNO> AP890825-0042 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 0441EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-FitzgeraldSearch     08-25 0454</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Fitzgerald Search,0466</SECOND>
<HEAD>Explorers Continue Fitzgerald Search</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAIGE St. JOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WHITEFISH POINT, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Researchers gazed at stark images
of rips and tears in the white carcass of the Edmund Fitzgerald, but
those pictures brought them no closer to answering why the famed
ship sank.
   ``Boy, it's awe inspiring to see. But none of it is surprising,''
said Phil Wright, a Canadian archaeologist on board the research
vessel Grayling that floated above the Fitzgerald wreckage again
Thursday.
   Researchers used a small, submersible robot to obtain the first
clear footage of the sunken boat. The expedition is being filmed for
the National Geographic Society's Explorer television series.
   The 729-foot steel freighter was carrying 27,000 tons of iron ore
down Lake Superior when it sank in a gale Nov. 10, 1975. All 29 crew
members died.
   The tragedy became legend within a year, when Canadian balladeer
Gordon Lightfoot sang of the crew, ``All that remains is the faces
and the names of the wives and the sons and the daughters.''
   Wright and other researchers aboard the Grayling marveled at
video images showing the Fitzgerald's crumpled pilothouse and
severed hull. Portholes were blown out and half-inch thick steel was
crinkled like tinfoil, while the ship's bell and water cooler
remained untouched.
   ``I was surprised by the visibility. I was surprised that the
bell was sitting on top. It's just unreal,'' said Tom Farnquist,
director of the Great Lakes Shipwreck Historical Society at
Whitefish Point and one of three expedition leaders.
   The official U.S. Coast Guard report said the Fitzgerald sank
after taking on water through its hatches as it plowed through
30-foot waves. Others believe the storm dropped the ship onto a
shoal, punching a hole in its hull.
   In either case, the boat sank so quickly there was never a
distress call. The captain's last words were that his ship was
holding its own in the storm.
   Wright said he didn't see any evidence that lent weight to either
theory.
   A 2- to 4-foot rip in the front of the Fitzgerald's hull puzzled
researchers somewhat. Wright theorized the damage occurred when the
boat struck the bottom of the lake.
   ``At the speed she was going, when she hit the bottom, boom,'' he
said, shoving his fist into his hand to illustrate an impact that
would have cracked open the freighter.
   ``I just find that terribly inexplicable,'' said author Fred
Stonehouse, also on board the Grayling. ``It's almost like you
cracked an eggshell. In this case, its half-inch steel.''
   An answer to why the modern freighter sank would be nice, but
expedition leaders are more interested in testing the submersible
robot and its three-dimensional camera system for use on other
shipwrecks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890825-0043 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 0350EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Lutherans     08-25 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lutherans,0492</SECOND>
<HEAD>Lutherans Order Up Studies on Social Issues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROSEMONT, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The newly consolidated Lutheran church's
interim policy against ordaining practicing homosexuals prompted a
clergywoman to comment, ``So this is the policy we will have about
it while we are trying to develop a policy about it.''
   The remark by the Rev. Gwendolyn King of Hanover, N.H., indicates
the somewhat misty hiatus in which the church finds itself on
various social issues.
   In keeping with Lutheranism's characteristic analytical approach,
the Evangelical Lutheran Church in America's first decision-making
assembly called for more study before taking definite stands on
several sensitive questions, including sexuality.
   Of that subject's myriad aspects, the Rev. Gerald L. Falk of
Chicago, executive director of the church's social-concerns
commission, said, ``It's a very difficult issue that we must study
carefully, prayerfully and thoroughly so that we can discern the
path which God is calling us to follow.''
   The Evangelical Lutheran Church in America is the result of the
Jan. 1, 1988 merger of the Lutheran Church in America, the American
Lutheran Church and the Association of Evangelical Lutheran Churches.
   The 5.3-million-member denomination ordered studies on a batch of
issues, including the homeless, family life, capital punishment and
health care.
   Action was pending on a proposal for a two-year study of
sexuality, including homosexuality and abortion, but a women's
caucus was pressing for immediate action on abortion.
   ``It's a stopgap until the study is done,'' said Barbara Nelson
of Lindsborg, Kan. It was proposed as necessary because of the
recent Supreme Court decision allowing some state regulation of
abortion.
   Sidestepping numerous proposals by different congregations and
regional synods for definite stands on various social issues, the
assembly referred most of them for study.
   Responding briefly on a grass-roots proposal, the assembly did
condemn racism as a sin and urged Lutherans to stay alert to the
``destructive results of racism.''
   Also, the church affirmed commitment to a ``just and equitable
welfare system'' and encouraged ``those engaged in the task of
welfare reform.''
   The assembly asked for study of gun control by Lutherans, a
church commission and by government to ``explore options for better
management of these weapons through an outright ban or regulation of
lawful sales.''
   On health care, the assembly declared it supported ``high quality
health care for everyone,'' and advocated legislation to achieve
that goal, but authorized studies to develop a policy on the matter.
   The 1,050 voting delegates still had before them some proposed
actions on divestment from companies doing business in South Africa
and on membership in major ecumenical councils.
   The eight-day assembly began Wednesday.
   Noting that many issues were being delayed for studies prior to
action at the second biennial assembly in 1991, the church's
president, Bishop Herbert W. Chilstrom said, ``This means that our
1991 assembly should be a lively one.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890825-0044 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 0606EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a PM-Colombia-Florida     08-25 0522</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Colombia-Florida,0535</SECOND>
<HEAD>`Most Wanted' Lists Include Cartel Chiefs Indicted in Miami, Jacksonville</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Colombia, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four alleged Colombian drug kingpins
face charges in U.S. indictments that resulted from testimony in the
1988 conviction of a leader of the Medellin drug cartel, Carlos
Lehder Rivas.
   The other reputed Medellin cartel leaders, Pablo Escobar Gaviria,
Jose Gonzalo Rodriguez Gacha, Jorge Ochoa Vasquez and Fabio Ochoa
Vasquez, were on the ``most wanted'' list of 12 Colombian drug
dealers issued by the U.S. Justice Department this week. The four
were indicted last March in Jacksonville.
   Those four, along with Ochoa's brother, Jorge Ochoa Vasquez, were
also indicted on drug trafficking charges in 1986 in Miami. All are
at-large.
   About 80 alleged Colombian drug traffickers have been indicted in
the United States, but their cases have languished since the
Colombian Supreme Court overturned its extradition treaty with the
United States in 1987.
   Colombian President Virgilio Barco, prompted by last week's
assassination of presidential candidate Luis Carlos Galan,
instituted emergency measures to allow the immediate resumption of
extraditions.
   The extradition treaty was overturned shortly after the
extradition of former cartel leader Lehder in 1987. He was tried in
Jacksonville, convicted of operating a continuing criminal
enterprise, and is now in federal prison serving a life sentence
without parole.
   Cartel leaders Thursday declared war on the Colombian government
just as bombs blew up offices of two principal political parties in
the Colombian city of Medellin, which serves as a base for the
world's biggest cocaine cartel.
   At the time of the March indictment, U.S. Attorney Robert W.
Genzman, said that Escobar was responsible for the April 1983
assassination of Colombian Justice Minister Lara Bonilla.
   After the killing, according to the indictment, cartel members
including Escobar, Lehder, Rodriquez and Fabio and Jorge Ochoa fled
to Nicaragua.
   In Nicaragua, the cartel brought in 1,400 kilograms of cocaine to
the Los Brasiles Air Force Base. Most of the cocaine was flown into
the United States.
   One of the flights resulted in the seizure of 665 kilograms of
cocaine by the federal Drug Enforcement Administration. A second
cocaine flight was made by Lehder's pilots from Nicaragua over Cuba,
to Andros Island in the Bahamas and eventually into United States.
   If convicted of the Jacksonville indictment, which lists 205
separate acts beginning in 1974 and continuing until this year, the
Ochoas, Escobar, and Rodriquez would face mandatory life prison
terms. Prosecutors said the indictment involves the importation of
44,000 pounds of cocaine worth $1 billion. In all, 30 people were
named in the indictment.
   Lehder was convicted of creating a small, private air force and
then using the Bahamian island of Norman's Cay as a way station for
shipments for more than 20 tons of cocaine into the United States
for the Medellin cartel.
   The Miami indictment, which alleges smuggling activities of the
Medellin cartel from 1978 to 1986, claims the practices used by the
cartel included ``the corruption of the public officials of foreign
govenments, the use of force, violence, threats, physical assaults
and murders of informants, discordant employees, and cartel
opponents.''
</TEXT>
