<DOCNO> AP890825-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 0518EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-China-AsiaGames     08-25 0565</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-China-Asia Games,0580</SECOND>
<HEAD>Olympic Council Head Says Asia Games in China Will go as Planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Next year's Asian Games in Beijing will be the
first held under martial law if China does not lift the security
measure, the president of the Olympic Council of Asia said today.
   But Sheikh Fahad Al Ahmad Al Sabah of Kuwait told reporters after
an eight-day inspection tour of the Asian Games facilities that he
was confident China could open the games as planned on Sept. 22,
1990.
   There has been much speculation about whether martial law,
instituted in late May during the popular democracy movement, would
be lifted before the 11th Asian Games. Martial law troops armed with
assault rifles still are stationed at major intersections and
bridges throughout the capital.
   ``If there is martial law or any other security system, it
doesn't concern the OCA,'' the sheikh said.
   Fahad did not say if Chinese officials had told him whether
martial law would end before the games.
   He also did not say if any of the Olympic Committee's 38 member
countries in Asia planned to boycott the games. Hong Kong residents
have urged a boycott to protest the June crackdown on the
pro-democracy movement in which hundreds, perhaps thousands, were
killed.
   Fahad said he was satisifed with the progress the Chinese have
made in preparing for the games, which will include 27 events.
   Between 6,500 and 7,000 athletes and officials are expected to
attend. In addition, 4,000 journalists are expected.
   ``The OCA feels that the percentage of construction already
completed is very satisfactory. They have reason to believe that all
the construction facilities will be ready ahead of time,'' the
Olympic Committee delegation said in a news release.
   Reporters touring the main games complex in northern Beijing
earlier this week could see that much work remained to be done. A
future press center and two planned hotels were mere shells, and the
swimming stadium and warm-up gym had roofs but no walls.
   Construction of 16 stadiums and renovation of 11 existing
facilities slowed to a virtual crawl last winter because of a
shortage of building materials and theft. Work was interrupted this
spring by the student-led democracy movement, which hampered
delivery of supplies. Workers were lured off the job to watch or
participate.
   Asked what he thought was the biggest problem, Fahad said:
``Security is a great problem. Food is a great problem.
Transportation is a great problem. Communication is a great problem.
Accommodations is a great problem. All these are great problems.''
   Chinese officials have acknowledged that funding also is a
problem.
   Wu Zhongyuan, spokesman for China's Asian Games Committee, said
on Monday that the estimated cost of holding the games has risen to
$673 million, up from last year's estimate of $565 million.
   To raise money and to drum up enthusiasm for the games, officials
have started selling lottery tickets, which ordinarily are illegal.
Interest seems to be high, with crowds gathered around tables set up
on main streets to buy the tickets, which each go for 1 yuan, or
about 27 cents. The top prize is worth $270.
   Red banners throughout the city appeal to residents' patriotism
and exhort them to help with Asian Games preparations. Collection
boxes have been seen on some streets, and a billboard at a major
intersection counts down the number of days left until the opening
ceremony.
</TEXT>
