<HEAD>Soviets Turn to South Korea For Ship Repairs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has turned to South
Korea for ship repairs in Asia by shifting away from Singapore and
Japan, industry officials said today.
   South Korean shipyards have repaired 36 Soviet ships and earned
$55 million since the end of last year, when the two countries began
direct economic dealings despite a lack of diplomatic ties, they
said.
   The officials, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said it is
more expensive to have ships repaired in Japan and that South Korea
is closer to Soviet Far Eastern ports than Singapore.
   Most of the repairs the first half of this year went to Hyundai
Mipo Dockyard Co. Ltd., which operates a major repair yard in Ulsan
on the southeast coast, said the officials.
