<FIRST>r a PM-DortchSentence     08-25 0527</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Dortch Sentence,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Former Top PTL Executive Sentenced to Eight Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENNIS PATTERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former PTL vice president Richard Dortch
said he was humiliated by his actions that resulted in an eight-year
prison sentence and a $200,000 fine.
   ``I failed my master, failed my family and failed myself,'' said
Dortch, as he pleaded for mercy at his sentencing Thursday.
   Dortch's sentence was part of a plea agreement in exchange for
testimony against Jim Bakker, founder of the television ministry,
whose trial on the same fraud and conspiracy charges starts Monday.
   ``I could not believe that I participated in this ... in
deceiving people, in doing something I knew was wrong,'' Dortch said
after prosecutors showed the judge charts detailing a pattern of
financial manipulations at PTL. ``The shame of that was the most
humiliating thing I have ever known.''
   Prosecutor Deborah Smith said memos between Dortch and the PTL
financial office showed calculated attempts to hide PTL's financial
difficulties.
   ``The victims in this case are in the thousands,'' she said.
``They are waiting to see the court's assessments. They are waiting
for justice.''
   Dortch, Bakker's top assistant at PTL, pleaded guilty earlier
this month to four counts of conspiracy and fraud and agreed to
testify against Bakker. Bakker is charged with using ministry funds
to finance his opulent lifestyle, including expensive homes, cars
and an air-conditioned dog house.
   Dortch is the third former Bakker aide to be convicted. Former
aides James and David Taggart, were convicted of evading taxes on
$1.1 million in ministry funds that prosecutors said they used to
buy Cartier jewelry, designer clothes and a Manhattan apartment.
They will be sentenced Sept. 8.
   Thursday, prosecutors presented evidence that even though Dortch
and Bakker said there would be a limit of 30,000 ``lifetime
partnerships'' sold in the Towers Hotel at PTL's Heritage USA
religious theme park, 68,755 partnerships were sold.
   Lifetime partners made a one-time donation of $1,000 in exchange
for three nights' free lodging each year for life, but the Towers
Hotel and other hotels planned for Heritage USA were never built or
were left uncompleted.
   Prosecutors said the Towers project alone generated $74.2 million
but only $11.4 million was spent on the uncompleted facility.
   The indictment alleges that the PTL executives spent more than $4
million on themselves and used some of it for operating expenses.
   The charts showed that Dortch collected $1,128,735 in salaries,
bonuses and tax-deferred retirement payments between January 1984
and June 1987. The bonuses alone in those three years amounted to
$550,000.
   Investigators also said that Dortch lived rent-free in a
PTL-owned home valued at $400,000 and that he had asked PTL's
builder to ``bury'' $233,000 in parsonage renovations in the
construction account for the Towers Hotel project.
   Dortch didn't attempt to blame Bakker.
   ``I lost the thing that I lived for _ my ministry,'' he said, his
voice cracking, before he was sentenced.
   U.S. District Judge Robert Potter gave Dortch four years in
prison and a $100,000 fine on the wire fraud charge, and four years
in prison and a $100,000 fine on the conspiracy. The prison terms
were consecutive.
</TEXT>
