<HEAD>Thunderstorms Rumble Over Northern Plains</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Thunderstorms lingered across the northern Plains early today,
hours after storms produced large hail and damaging winds in Montana
and the Dakotas.
   Showers and thunderstorms also struck Kansas and southern
Nebraska today. A thunderstorm late Thursday in central Kansas
produced golf ball-size hail at Hesston.
   Thunderstorms in western South Dakota produced hail 1\ inches in
diameter near Opal. Thunderstorms west of Rapid City produced more
than 2 inches of rain in less than an hour Thursday evening.
   Storms in eastern Montana left up to 4-foot drifts of hail in
ditches along roads and produced golf ball-size hail which broke
windows at Rock Springs. A thunderstorm at Jordan, Mont., produced
wind gusts to 65 mph.
   Thunderstorms in northwestern North Dakota produced hail an inch
in diameter at Bowbells and damaging winds near Newtown.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms were scattered today along a
stationary front from southern Illinois and western Kentucky to
Virginia and North Carolina.
   Showers doused the northern Rockies and widely scattered showers
and thunderstorms lingered over the southern Rockies.
   Clear skies prevailed across the Southwest and from the
Mississippi Valley to the northern Atlantic Coast.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
over the northern and central Plains, the middle and lower
Mississippi Valley, the lower Ohio and Tennessee valleys, the Gulf
Coast and the southern Atlantic Coast; thunderstorms developing over
parts of west Texas; and showers over the northern Rockies.
   Highs are expected to be in the 60s and 70s in the northern
Atlantic Coast, the Great Lakes, northern New England, the northern
Plains, the northern Rockies, the Pacific Northwest and along the
California coast; in the 100s in parts of central and southwest
Texas and the desert Southwest; and in the 80s and 90s elsewhere.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 39
degrees at Yellowstone Park in Wyoming to 88 degrees at Phoenix.
   Other reports:
