<FIRST>r i PM-Ethiopia     08-25 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Ethiopia,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Ethiopian Rebel Group Accepts Carter's Mediation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second rebel group in Ethiopia has
accepted former President Jimmy Carter as an observer in peace talks
and called on the Ethiopian government to ``respond quickly'' to the
proposal.
   The Tigre People's Liberation Front made the announcement in a
clandestine radio broadcast.
   ``The TPLF fears that the talks can be delayed while looking for
observers and, therefore, accepts former American President Jimmy
Carter, who has expressed his readiness to be an observer at the
talks,'' the group said Monday.
   Carter already is to act as an observer in peace talks between
Ethiopia's government and another rebel group, the Eritrean People's
Liberation Front, scheduled to begin in Atlanta on Sept. 7.
   The Eritreans, in Ethiopia's northernmost Eritrea province, have
been fighting for independence since 1961.
   The Tigrean rebels, in neighboring Tigray province, took up arms
14 years ago to press for increased autonomy for their region.
   Early this year, they scored several major victories and forced
troops out of five towns, including the provincial capital of
Mekele, 470 miles northwest of Addis Ababa.
   Both rebel groups agreed to peace talks following President
Mengistu Haile Mariam's announcement in June that the government had
no preconditions and welcomed an independent observer.
   In its broadcast, the Tigre People's Liberation Front accused the
government of failing to respond to a previous offer for talks ``in
order to complete preparations'' for a counterattack in Tigray
province.
</TEXT>
