<FIRST>r i PM-Korea 2ndLd-Writethru   08-25 0612</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Korea, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0516,0629</SECOND>
<HEAD>Opposition Leader Indicted in South Korea</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 1 graf after 7th, `Also today...' to UPDATE with no
arrests or injuries reported in protests. Pickup 8th, `Prosecutors...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY TUNNEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Kim Dae-jung and two
other opposition lawmakers were indicted today on charges connected
with a lawmaker's secret and illegal trip to Communist North Korea.
   Kim, head of the Party for Peace and Democracy, denounced the
indictments as political persecution and said all the charges
against him and others were fabricated to discredit his opposition
group.
   ``I have nothing to fear. I will squarely face trial,'' he told
supporters.
   Also today, leftist students students yelling ``Yankee go home!''
and ``Overthrow (President) Roh Tae-woo!'' battled riot police with
iron bars, clubs, firebombs and rocks.
   Police firing tear gas from two armored vans clashed with about
l,000 students inside Seoul National University after the
demonstrators tried to march from the campus.
   Students demanded the withdrawal of 43,000 U.S. troops, which
they claim hinder talks on unification with North Korea. They also
demanded the release of a radical female student who was jailed
after making an unauthorized trip to North Korea.
   Also today, about 400 radical students at Seoul's Hankuk
University of Foreign Studies battled police for two hours with
firebombs.
   No arrests or injuries were reported in the protests.
   Prosecutors charged in the indictments that Kim and two party
lawmakers failed to report National Assemblyman Suh Kyung-won's
secret trip to North Korea last year, a violation of national
security laws.
   The three indicted politicians will not be jailed pending trial,
prosecutors said. If convicted, Kim, party floor leader Kim Won-ki
and Rep. Lee Chul-yong could be sentenced to up to five years in
prison.
   Kim Dae-jung said his trial may never take place because the
government knows it has no chance of winning the case.
   Suh was expelled from the party on June 28, the same day he was
arrested on charges of espionage, violating a ban on unauthorized
travel to North Korea and receiving $120,000 from North Korean
agents before and during his secret trip to Pyongyang last August.
   Prosecutors said they have evidence Kim Dae-jung knew about Suh's
trip in advance. The opposition leader denies the charge.
   Kim Dae-jung, 64, also was charged with violating the Foreign
Currency Control Law for allegedly receiving $10,000 from Suh, who
is said to have received it from North Korean agents.
   However, prosecutors said the opposition leader apparently did
not know the money came from North Korea, so the charge was limited
to a minor violation that requires anyone receiving foreign currency
to report it within 10 days.
   Kim Dae-jung said his party will hold a rally in the western city
of Bupyong on Saturday to protest what he called ``deliberate
political persecution.''
   The Seoul government prohibits unauthorized travel to North Korea.
   Also today, a Seoul appellate court reduced the sentence given to
the brother of former President Chun Doo-hwan to two years in prison
and a fine of $477,000 for embezzlement.
   Chun Ki-hwan, 55, was arrested last year for diverting $4.3
million in public money after he took over a Seoul fish market in
1985 with the help of government officials.
   He was convicted by a Seoul district court and sentenced to four
years' imprisonment and a fine of $1.5 million. He appealed the
guilty verdict.
   About a dozen members of Chun Doo-hwan's family have been linked
to corruption since he left office last year after a seven-year rule.
   The former president himself went into rural exile late last year
after publicly apologizing for corruption committed under his
administration.
</TEXT>
