<HEAD>Twins Plunge to Death From Building</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Twin sisters with histories of mental problems
smoked several cigarettes together on the roof of a building before
jumping six stories to their deaths, authorities said.
   ``There was nothing to indicate the women were thrown off,''
police Capt. Edward Voehl said.
   The 24-year-old twins, Valeria and Claudia Marmon, died Thursday
after plunging from the building in Brooklyn, police said.
   Their father, Bert Marmon, said Valeria was a recent outpatient
from New York Hospital, where she was recovering from an overdose of
pills, according to police.
   A worker who saw the sisters enter the building said it seemed
they were going to pass the building when they apparently entered on
impulse. No suicide note was found, police said.
