<FIRST>r i PM-Poland-Reaction 1stLd-Writethru   08-25 0694</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Poland-Reaction, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0456,0709</SECOND>
<HEAD>Western Leaders Express Excitement; Moscow Looks For Good Relations</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 6 grafs after 4th, `Danish Prime...' to UPDATE with
Vietnam criticism, Italy comment. Pickup 5th pvs, `Soviet Foreign. ..'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCUS ELIASON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Western leaders quickly gave strong backing to
Poland's first non-Communist prime minister in more than 40 years,
and Moscow said it hoped its relations with the Warsaw government
would remain close.
   After Poland's lower house of Parliament elected Tadeusz
Mazowiecki to the post Thursday, President Bush promised ``our
strong support as (Mazowiecki) seeks to lead his country toward
economic recovery and democratic change.''
   Bush praised Communist President Wojciech Jaruzelski's
``political wisdom in endorsing a government reflecting the genuine
will of the Polish people and Solidarity, under the leadership of
Lech Walesa, for its constructive role in helping bring about a new
beginning in Poland.''
   Danish Prime Minister Poul Schlueter, who was visiting Bush,
said: ``You are seeing right now very positive and exciting
international developments.''
   But Communist Vietnam criticized the new government today,
condemning ``anti-socialist forces backed and abetted by the United
States and the West for fomenting a deep political crisis in
Poland.''
   A transcript of a commentary in the Communist Party newspaper
Nhan Danh, seen in Bangkok, said a fierce struggle was going on in
Poland between ``revolutionary and pro-socialist forces and ...
counterrevolutionary and anti-Socialist forces.
   ``Taking advantage of the increasing economic political
difficulties deliberately caused and aggravated by themselves, the
opposition ... aided by the United States and the West as well as
the (Roman Catholic) Church has been carrying out hectic activities,
blaming the (Communist) Party and Poland for the troubles and trying
to increase their influence on the people,'' it said.
   It said the ``complicated struggle'' in Poland will ``rally the
working class'' to fight anti-socialist forces and resolve the
``present crisis.''
   Mazowiecki was nominated as prime minister by Communist President
Wojciech Jaruzelski and approved by Polish lawmakers, including a
majority of the Communist delegation.
   In Rome, Italian Premier Giulio Andreotti sent a message of
congratulations and said he hoped Poland would ``consolidate its
democratic and reformist course.''
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Yuri A. Gremitskikh said: ``We
shall regard Comrade Mazowiecki as our partner in the relations that
link our two countries.''
   The Council of Ministers, or Soviet cabinet, sent Mazowiecki a
cable of ``friendly congratulations,'' and added:
   ``We express the certainty that the traditional relations of
friendship and all-round cooperation between the Soviet Union and
Poland will continue developing on the basis of sovereign equality
and respect, mutual benefit and mutual responsibility.''
   West German Chancellor Helmut Kohl sent ``heartfelt best wishes''
to Mazowieck. ``I wish God's blessing on the tasks ... lying ahead
of you,'' Kohl said.
   He said added his government would ``do all in its power to
support you on the chosen path.''
   Kohl said he hoped for closer relations with Poland, especially
since 1989 is the 50th anniversary of Nazi Germany's invasion of
Poland and the start of World War II.
   ``I am convinced that our two countries in this year ... should
move closer together ... to smooth the way for a lasting
reconciliation between our two peoples,'' he wrote.
   British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's message recalled
``with much pleasure'' her meeting with Mazowiecki in November, when
she visited Walesa and his colleagues in Gdansk, Poland.
   Her office said she reaffirmed ``Britain's readiness to help
Poland to achieve democracy and economic recovery,'' but listed what
she saw as the three main challenges facing Poland: ``The need to
form a government that truly reflects the will of the Polish people;
to take Poland along the path of democracy; to implement the
difficult decisions necessary to restore Poland's economic health.''
   Swedish Prime Minister Ingvar Carlsson welcomed the latest
``development in the democratic process in Poland.''
   ``The new Polish government, it is true, has no easy task,'' he
said. ``It faces great and difficult problems, especially in the
economic sphere.''
   His government hoped for ``increased and deeper cooperation with
the new government in Warsaw, not the least concerning problems that
can be solved best through international cooperation.''
</TEXT>
