<FIRST>r w PM-Frank-Profile 2ndLd-Writethru a0514 08-25 0693</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Frank-Profile, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0514,680</SECOND>
<HEAD>Frank: Homosexuality Irrelevant to Performance in Congress</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 5th graf, The lawmaker, with to show how two men
met</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., who publicly
acknowledged his homosexuality two years ago, insists his sexual
preference is not relevant to the way he performs his job in
Congress.
   ``If you ask the direct question: `Are you gay?' the answer is:
Yes. So what?'' Frank said in May 1987 when he became the second
member of Congress to discuss his homosexuality in public. Gerry
Studds, a fellow Massachusetts Democrat, also is an acknowledged
homosexual.
   ``I don't think my sex life is relevant to my job,'' Frank said
at the time. ``But on the other hand I don't want to leave the
impression that I'm embarrassed about my life.''
   Frank, a five-term congressman, acknowledged today that he hired
a male prostitute as a personal employee but fired him after
becoming suspicious the man was selling sex from Frank's home on
Capitol Hill.
   The lawmaker said he met the man in 1985 through an
``escort-model'' advertisement in a Washington gay newspaper. He
admitted having paid for sex with the man, but said the relationship
later became one of friendship.
   Frank said he ``showed poor judgment'' in hiring the man, but had
no direct proof the man was engaging in prostitution from the
congressman's apartment.
   The liberal Democrat said he saw no reason why he should resign
from Congress or should not seek re-election in 1990.
   Frank, 49, was first elected to Congress in 1980 and re-elected
in Massachusetts' 4th Congressional District in November 1988 by a
70 percent to 30 percent margin over his Republican opponent,
Deborah Tucker.
   Frank, who is not married, contended in June 1987 that most of
his constituents don't care that he's homosexual.
   ``Hardly anyone is interested in the sex life of a boring,
middle-aged politician,'' Frank said. ``As long as a person is kind,
loving and caring, not much else matters.''
   In February 1988, he said ``voters care about performance in
office,'' not about personal issues such as sexual preference.
   But his homosexuality became enmeshed in controversy this summer
when the Republican National Committee mailed a memo comparing his
voting record with that of new House Speaker Thomas S. Foley.
   The memo, titled, ``Tom Foley: Out of the Liberal Closet,'' said
Foley's voting record was as liberal as Frank's.
   Frank contended the memo was ``extraordinarily scurrilous'' and
implied he viewed it as an effort to portray Foley as homosexual.
Frank said he might reveal the identity of homosexual Republican
congressmen if such attacks on Democrats continued.
   The RNC aide who wrote the memo resigned and RNC Chairman Lee
Atwater apologized to Foley.
   Frank said he decided to acknowledge his homosexuality after
public scrutiny of the private lives of former Democratic
presidential candidate Gary Hart and the late U.S. Rep. Stewart B.
McKinney of Connecticut. Hart, who is married, was forced to
withdraw from the 1988 race after being linked with model Donna
Rice. McKinney died of AIDS in 1987.
   Frank has worked for approval of legislation requiring
replacement of low-income housing demolished under urban renewal, a
bill requiring special prosecutors to investigate alleged wrongdoing
by public officials, and legislation barring the government from
denying visas based on politics.
   ``We would have more money for health issues if it weren't for
increased defense spending,'' said Frank in July 1988.
   Regarding anti-abortion activists, he once said: ``Sure, they're
pro-life. They believe that life begins at conception and ends at
birth.''
   He also contended the Reagan administration ignored the AIDS
issue.
   Frank is a member of the House Government Operations subcommittee
on housing and employment, which is investigating the
influence-peddling scandal at the Department of Housing and Urban
Development.
   Born in Bayonne, N.J., Frank was executive assistant to Boston
Mayor Kevin White and an administrative assistant to Rep. Michael J.
Harrington, D-Mass., before being elected to the Massachusetts House
of Representatives in 1973.
   He served in the state Legislature until he was elected to
Congress.
   Frank earned his bachelor's degree from Harvard in 1962 and his
law degree in 1977 from Harvard Law School.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
