<FIRST>r a PM-WrongMother     08-25 0498</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wrong Mother,0515</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mistaken Custody Arrest Over Look-Alike Kids, Mother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CLEWISTON, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Florida woman was jailed for two days
and her sons were put into a foster home when authorities in two
states mistook her for a West Virginia woman who fled with her two
sons after losing a custody battle.
   Not only do Melissa Dobbins, of Clewiston, and her 8- and
6-year-old sons bear striking resemblances to Lori Butcher and her
children, but the boys have the same names _ Joe and Nathan _ and
are about the same age, West Virginia police said.
   Mrs. Butcher disappeared with her two sons from Huntington,
W.Va., two years ago in defiance of a court order awarding the sons'
custody to their father.
   Mrs. Dobbins _ a large-boned woman with a Southern accent and
light brown hair _ matches Mrs. Butcher's description.
   ``I'm still not believing it happened,'' Mrs. Dobbins said
Thursday after finally getting her boys back. ``They put me through
torture.''
   Mrs. Dobbins' nightmare began in early August. A Clewiston
teacher spotted pictures of the Butcher boys on a missing children's
poster, noticed they looked like the Dobbins boys and notified
police.
   Clewiston police notified police in Huntington, confirming the
mothers' resemblance and the boys' resemblance _ and identical names
and ages.
   Huntington police then obtained a fugitive warrant from the FBI
charging Mrs. Dobbins _ whom they thought was Mrs. Butcher _ with
child concealment.
   Mrs. Dobbins was arrested Aug. 18 while visiting her husband at
South Miami Hospital, where he had undergone gall-bladder surgery.
   ``I said, `I'm not her. I'm Melissa Dobbins,''' Mrs. Dobbins
recounted. ``They didn't believe me.''
   ``I don't think we did anything wrong to apologize for,'' said
Huntington police Sgt. Darrell Black. ``I'm sorry if we put them
out. We were going on police instincts.''
   After being fingerprinted, strip-searched and booked at Dade
County Jail, she finally got to a telephone _ 12 hours later.
   That was when she discovered that state Health and Rehabilitative
Services workers had taken her children and put them in a temporary
home.
   The frightened boys also told authorities they were making a
mistake. ``I was scared I wouldn't see my mom again,'' Joe said.
   On Saturday, Ray Buck, an attorney from Tennessee, where Mrs.
Dobbins once lived, spent all day on the phone trying to convince
the FBI and police they had the wrong woman.
   Police finally checked to see whether Mrs. Dobbins had Mrs.
Butcher's markings _ a butterfly tattoo and two Caesarean scars. She
did not, and police freed her Sunday.
   But Black then decided Mrs. Dobbins could have been a baby sitter
for the missing Butcher boys, and the HRS refused to release the
Dobbins brothers.
   It took two more days of legal wrangling, including exchanges of
photographs between police in Huntington and in Florida, before the
boys were returned to their parents.
   ``The court system shouldn't work this way,'' Buck said. ``People
are entitled to better treatment than this.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
