<FIRST>r i PM-Angola 1stLd-Writethru   08-25 0446</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Angola, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0529,0455</SECOND>
<HEAD>Angolan Rebels Report 83 Killed in Fighting With Government Troops</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 4 grafs to CORRECT that casualty toll one of the
worst since June, ADDS report on fighting last week. Pickup 4th graf, `A
source...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TONY SMITH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan rebels said today that 77
government troops and six rebels were killed in heavy fighting this
week. The casualty toll was one of the highest reported since a
cease-fire was declared in Angola in June.
   In a statement released in Lisbon, the UNITA rebels said 19
rebels were injured in the clashes that occurred earlier this week
in the central and southern provinces of Cuand-Cubango, Cunene,
Huambo and South Cuanza.
   The statement said the rebels shot down a Soviet-built Mi-25
helicopter, destroyed four tanks and several combat vehicles, and
captured arms and ammunition in the fighting. There was no
independent confirmation of the attacks from the government in
Luanda.
   Last week, UNITA claimed government warplanes killed 150 people
in a raid on Mavinga. Casualty reports are often exaggerated by both
sides and news organizations are rarely able to verify them.
   A source close to the government said in a telephone interview
that Angolan Defense Minister Pedro Maria Tonha would meet later
today with his Zairean counterpart along the border in Angola's
northeastern corner.
   The source could not confirm the purpose of the meeting but said
he expected an official statement to be released.
   Cooperation between Angola and Zaire has increased recently since
President Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire began mediating in Angola's
civil war before a summit of 18 African leaders at Gbadolite on June
22.
   The summit produced a historic handshake between Angolan
President Jose Eduardo dos Santos and UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi
that sealed a short-lived truce in their 14-year-old civil war.
   The truce began collapsing one week later and was formally
renounced Thursday by Savimbi. He acted after seven African leaders
met Tuesday in Harare, Zimbabwe, and supported dos Santos' claims
that Savimbi had accepted a ``temporary and voluntary retirement''
from Angola during peace negotiations.
   Western-backed UNITA, the Portuguese acronym for the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, have been fighting the
government and its Cuban allies to force a power-sharing agreement
since shortly after Angola gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
   UNITA was not party to U.S.-brokered international accords signed
in New York in which South Africa pledged to halt aid to the
guerrillas and allow Angola's southern neighbor Namibia to gain
independence. In return, Cuba began a phased withdrawal of its
estimated 50,000 troops from Angola.
   UNITA still receives $15-$18 million annually in U.S. military
aid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
