<FIRST>u i PM-Israel-Kidnapping 1stLd-Writethru   08-25 0324</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Israel-Kidnapping, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0498,0330</SECOND>
<HEAD>Israeli Kidnap Victim Found Alive</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New thruout to UPDATE with man found in well, one arrest. No
pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Security agents found an Israeli gold merchant
in a well today after he was kidnapped by masked Palestinians in the
West Bank, officials said. One kidnap suspect was arrested.
   Shaul Mishaniya, 47, who reportedly went to the West Bank to
collect debts, was located by Shin Bet secret service agents during
a search involving helicopters and hundreds of soldiers and police.
   ``I am healthy, thank God, and thank you to the Israeli army and
all the soldiers who helped me,'' Mishaniya said on Israel radio.
   Maj. Gen. Yitzhak Mordechai, commander of troops in the West
Bank, also said on the radio that Mishaniya had been held in the
well after being brought to an Arab village near Tulkarem.
   ``We found the well and brought him out, and I identified him and
he is all right,'' Mordechai said.
   Army officials said Mishaniya was found standing in about 5 feet
of water at the bottom of a 20-foot-deep well in the Arab village of
Abush.
   Mishaniya said he had been taken from a taxi by unknown men
Wednesday night. ``I didn't know them, and I don't know their
names,'' he said.
   The radio said he had spoken to his family in Tel Aviv.
   Col. Renaan Gissin, deputy military spokesman, said Shin Bet
agents were led to the scene by an Arab suspect who was captured
Thursday. He said other suspects were being sought.
   ``The motive is not known. The investigation is looking into
whether it is political or criminal or both,'' said Gissin.
   Mishaniya was the first Israeli civilian abducted during the
20-month-old Palestinian uprising, prompting speculation that
underground leaders had opted for new tougher tactics as part of
their revolt against Israeli occupation.
   However, officials also said they were investigating possible
criminal motives for his kidnapping.
</TEXT>
