<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1103EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i PM-Lebanon 1stLd-Writethru   08-25 0807</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Lebanon, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0535,0827</SECOND>
<HEAD>Soviet Diplomat Calls For Cease-Fire in Lebanon</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Subs 5-6 grafs pvs, `The U.S...not elaborate.' with 2 grafs
to UPDATE with Pentagon comment. Pickup 7th pvs, `Police said...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Soviet envoy who met with Christian and
Moslem leaders called today for a cease-fire in Lebanon and said the
warring factions should lift blockades on each other's ports.
   French radio stations reported today that ships of the U.S. Sixth
Fleet were anchored about 50 miles off Lebanon in the eastern
Mediterranean, the same distance as a French flotilla of warships.
   Pro-Iranian groups have threatened to attack the French ships if
they intervene militarily in Lebanon. France says it sent the ships
to Lebanon to evacuate French nationals if the fighting worsens.
   In Moscow, a Soviet foreign ministry spokesman denied French
radio reports that the Soviet missile launcher Kirov was headed to
join other Soviet warships in the area. ``There are no Soviet
military vessels off Lebanon's coast,'' spokesman Yuri Gremitskikh
said. He said ``no Soviet military vessels are heading to Lebanon's
shores.''
   Lebanon's Communist Voice of the People radio station in Lebanon
said Sixth Fleet vessels visiting the Israeli port of Haifa were
coordinating activity with the French task force. It did not
elaborate.
   The U.S. Embassy in Beirut declined comment on the reports. The
Pentagon said in Washington that the Sixth Fleet was not engaged in
unusual activities and that its ships have not teamed up with those
of the French flotilla. The Pentagon declined to say precisely where
the U.S. fleet was located.
   Police said one person was killed and four wounded in overnight
and early morning clashes between Syrian and Christian forces in
Beirut and in the mountains southeast of the capital.
   The latest casualties raised the overall toll from five months of
fighting between army commander Gen. Michel Aoun's mostly Christian
troops and Syrian forces with their Moslem militia allies to 792
killed and 2,218 wounded.
   The conflict began March 8 after Aoun blockaded Moslem-run ports
south of Beirut. Syria and its Moslem allies retaliated by shelling
and besieging the Christian heartland and ports north of Beirut.
   Soviet envoy Gennady Tarasov met today with Maronite Catholic
Patriarch Nasrallah Sfeir in Bkirki, north of Beirut, before driving
to Beirut's eastern Baabda suburb for a meeting with Aoun.
   He told reporters his talks were ``useful,'' adding: ``The
patriarch and I agreed that the time is ripe for a political
solution.''
   ``Everything should be discussed politically and far from
military solutions... A cease-fire should go into effect and
blockades should be lifted,'' Tarasov said without elaborating.
   The Soviet envoy walked the last 500 yards along a shell-pitted
road to the hilltop presidential palace, where Aoun has his
headquarters in an underground bunker. The two-story palace has come
under heavy Syrian shelling since Aoun declared a ``war of
liberation'' to drive out the Soviet-equipped Syrian army.
   Syria claims to be in complete harmony with the Soviets over the
Lebanon crisis, but Arab diplomats have reported serious differences
between Moscow and Damascus, which has refused Arab appeals to
withdraw from Lebanon. The Syrians also refuse to negotiate directly
with Aoun.
   Tarasov, who heads the Soviet foreign ministry's Middle East
department, held lengthy talks with Acting Prime Minister Salim
Hoss, a Sunni Moslem, after arriving Thursday in west Beirut.
   He refused to speak to reporters before the meeting with Sfeir.
But sources at Hoss' Moslem cabinet, speaking on condition of
anonymity, said Tarasov was promoting a comprehensive peace plan to
halt the confrontation and begin a political dialogue among Lebanese
leaders to end the 14-year civil war.
   Tarasov discussed the Lebanese situation with Syrian Foreign
Minister Farouk Al-Sharaa in Damascus on Wednesday. The two nations
are bound by a treaty of friendship and cooperation.
   Sheik Sobhi Tofeili of Hezbollah, or Party of God, said the
pro-Iranian radical Shiite group was ``in a state of war with the
French forces.''
   ``We shall practice our right in this regard and defend ourselves
against the French who have declared war on us by coming close to
our coast,'' Tofeili said in a statement carried today by An-nahar
and other publications.
   A previously unknown group calling itself the Organization for
the Defense of the Oppressed also pledged to ``confront the flagrant
French military intervention in internal Lebanese affairs.''
   The group, in a statement delivered to a Western news agency in
Beirut, said its ``Mujahedeen (holy warriors) are ready to carry out
God's verdict in striking at western interests, topped by French
interests.''
   France has said its six-ship flotilla was sent on a
``humanitarian'' mission to help evacuate the estimated 7,000 French
nationals living in Lebanon if the situation deteriorated.
   However, Syria's allies claimed the French warships were on a
mission to support Aoun's troops in the 310-square-mile Christian
enclave.
</TEXT>
