<FIRST>u a PM-RacialAttack 1stLd-Writethru a0480 08-25 0784</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Racial Attack, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0480,0802</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gang Trying to Block Interracial Dating Kills Black Youth in New
York</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with four suspects charged, note
that neighborhood is Italian-Jewish, DELETE outdated material. Pickup 11th
graf, `Mayor Edward...' ADDS 1 graf at end with 1987 racial incident in
same neighborhood. Note language in 6th graf.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four young white men were charged today with
being part of a gang accused of killing one black teen-ager and
chasing three others from a white neighborhood with baseball bats.
   The gang of as many as 30 white youths, intent on preventing an
interracial couple from meeting, attacked the black teen-agers
Wednesday night as they were going to meet someone selling a used
car, authorities said.
   The killing of Yusef Hawkins, 16, was reminiscent of the 1986
Howard Beach case, in which a group of white teen-agers in the
Howard Beach section of Queens chased three blacks, one of whom was
hit by a car and killed.
   In Brooklyn's mostly Italian-Jewish Bensonhurst section Wednesday
night, the white gang gathered to waylay blacks or Hispanics they
believed were headed for a young white woman's birthday party in the
neighborhood, authorities said.
   Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward said the 18-year-old woman had
recently jilted her white boyfriend and had been dating black and
Hispanic men.
   The spurned boyfriend had threatened the girl and made comments
to her about ``your nigger boyfriend'' and ``bringing niggers into
the neighborhood,'' said Deputy Commissioner Alice McGillion.
   The slain youth's father stood Thursday night on his own Brooklyn
street, which is mostly black, and laid the blame squarely on racism.
   ``My son will never turn this corner again and it's only because
of this: the pigment of his skin,'' Fred Stewart said bitterly.
   Four young Brooklyn men whom police believe were part of the gang
were taken into custody. Keith Mondello, 18; Steven Curreri, 18;
Pasquale Raucci, 19, and Charles Stressler, 21 were charged today
with assault, riot, aggravated harassment, violation of civil
rights, menacing and possessing a weapon, said Sgt. Norris Hollomon.
The weapon was a bat.
   Mondello and Curreri also were charged with conspiracy, Hollomon
said. Police said none of those arrested fired the shots that killed
the victim.
   Police said the former boyfriend was being sought for questioning.
   Mayor Edward I. Koch, with Ward at a news conference Thursday,
called the killing ``an enormous tragedy.''
   Other candidates in New York City's Sept. 12 mayoral primary
issued statements deploring the killing.
   David Dinkins, in a virtual dead heat with Koch for the
Democratic nomination, said he accused no one of causing the racial
violence but added: ``The tone and climate of this city does get set
at City Hall.''
   Hawkins and his friends, Troy Banner and Claude Stanford, both
18, and Luther Sylvester, 17, went into the neighborhood to answer a
newspaper ad for a used car.
   Ward said the whites followed the blacks for about a block and a
half and witnesses heard them say: ``Are these the ones? Is this
them?''
   What they didn't know was that the girlfriend had told her new
boyfriend, a Hispanic, not to come and called off her birthday
party, McGillion said.
   McGillion said the girl, Gina Feliciano, saw the killing from her
window.
   ``She knew there was going to be trouble. There were rumblings in
the neighborhood. Her mother had looked out the window and saw the
boys with the bats,'' McGillion said.
   When the white gang stopped and confronted the blacks, four shots
were heard. Hawkins fell with two shots in the chest. Banner had an
injury to the arm, but it wasn't known whether it was from a grazing
bullet or a blow, police said. The other two were unhurt.
   The gang scattered. When police arrived they found four
.32-caliber shells and several bats nearby. No gun was recovered
despite police searches of a parked car and sewers.
   ``This neighborhood is definitely prejudiced. They don't like
blacks. They don't like Puerto Ricans,'' said Joanne Carretta, a
26-year-old lifelong Bensonhurst resident.
   Others said Bensonhurst was no more prejudiced than other
communities.
   Yet, one teen-age girl standing not far from where Hawkins was
killed said: ``The black people don't belong here. ... This is our
neighborhood.''
   Bensonhurst was the scene of a racial incident on Christmas Day
1987 in which two black men were allegedly beaten by a gang of white
youths while they collected bottles in a shopping cart. Two arrests
were made in the attack, which spawned a protest march through the
neighborhood by 400 blacks as angry white residents jeered and
shouted ``Howard Beach!'' at the participants.
</TEXT>
