<FIRST>u i PM-Kenya-Adamson 1stLd-Writethru a0519 08-25 0374</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Kenya-Adamson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0519,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Arrested in Slaying of Conservationist</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 5th pvs, `Police Commissioner...,' to
UPDATE with background on recent attacks. Pickup 6th pvs, `Adamson, 83...'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police have arrested three people in the
slaying of George Adamson, the British conservationist known as the
Lion Man of Kenya, the governing party newspaper reported today.
   The Kenya Times said police arrested the three men in the
northern Kora National Reserve. It did not say when the arrests
occurred. Authorities began searching the area Sunday after Adamson
and two assistants were shot and killed in an encounter with three
robbers armed with automatic rifles.
   Adamson trained lions born in captivity to return to the wild.
   The Times, owned by the ruling Kenya African National Union, said
police were interrogating the suspects and planned to parade them
before Adamson's workers who witnessed the shooting for possible
identification.
   Police Commissioner Philip Kilonzo was not immediately available
for comment, and Richard Leakey, the director of wildlife
management, said he had no way to confirm or deny the report.
   Adamson's slaying was the third fatal attack in Kenya's wilds
since July. Publicity surrounding his death and the slayings of an
American woman and a French couple threatens to harm Kenya's tourism
industry, the country's number one foreign exchange earner.
   Officials say travel is basically safe. They blame the recent
violence partly on a massive effort to save Kenya's elephants, which
they say has driven well-armed poachers into other forms of banditry.
   Adamson, 83, earned international fame by his efforts along with
his wife Joy to return lions to the wild. Their achievements were
detailed in the film ``Born Free'' and a sequel, ``Living Free.''
Both movies were based on books by Joy, who was killed at the
northwestern Shamba Game Reserve in 1980 by a servant she had
dismissed on suspicion of theft.
   Adamson moved into Kora National Reserve in 1971 and helped
dozens of lions learn to survive in the bush before turning them
loose.
   He and Joy, who separated in the late 1960, had no children.
   Leakey said Adamson, whose body was flown to Nairobi Aug. 21,
would be buried with honors at Kora National Reserve next week.
</TEXT>
