<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1130EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r i PM-FemaleLawmakers     08-25 0209</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Female Lawmakers,0212</SECOND>
<HEAD>Global Survey Finds Fewer Women in National Legislatures</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The proportion of women in the world's parliaments
dropped to 12.7 percent by the end of June, close to the level of 15
years ago, according to a survey.
   At the start of last year, the figure was 14.6 percent, according
to figures published Thursday by the Geneva-based
Inter-Parliamentary Union.
   Sweden's Parliament has the highest proportion of female
legislators, 38.1 percent, a rise from 30.1 percent in January 1988,
a summary of the survey said. Norway and Romania were listed next
with 34.4 percent each, followed by Cuba, East Germany, Finland and
Denmark.
   Sharp drops were registered in the Soviet Union, where the
percentage fell from 34.5 to 15.3 after elections in March, and in
Poland, where the proportion dropped from 20.2 to 13.3 percent. In
France, the share of women deputies declined from 6.4 to 5.7
percent, the survey said.
   In Venezuela and Bolivia, the percentage more than doubled in the
18 months surveyed. Rises were also listed for Ecuador, Mexico and
Canada.
   As of June 30, 3,937 out of 31,055 parliamentarians in 130
countries were women _ a figure almost as low as the 12.5 percent
recorded in 1975, the group said.
</TEXT>
