<HEAD>Woman Gets 15 Years' Probation For Giving Cocaine to Babies Via Bloodstream</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANFORD, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A cocaine-addicted mother convicted of
delivering drugs to her two babies through the bloodstream was
sentenced today to 15 years' probation and completion of a drug
treatment program.
   Jennifer Johnson, who faced a maxium 30-year prison sentence,
must remain free of drugs, receive periodic testing, complete a high
school equivalency education and meet other terms of a lengthy
probation program imposed by Seminole County Circuit Judge O.H. Eton
Jr.
   Ms. Johnson, 23, was convicted July 12 of delivering drugs to her
newborns under a criminal drug-dealing law rarely applied in such
cases.
   She was convicted in a non-jury trial of delivering drugs through
the children's umbilical cords at birth. In his ruling, the judge
determined that the cocaine passed from her body into the babies at
birth, but before their umbilical cords were severed.
   Ms. Johnson's attorney, James Sweeting, who has said he would
appeal the conviction, called the sentence ``tough for her to meet.
... It's not excessive for the crime for which she was convicted,
but we do not think she should have gone to trial on that charge.''
   Ms. Johnson, who is at a drug program that runs 12 to 16 months,
did not speak during the sentencing except to tell the judge she
understood the terms.
