<FIRST>u i PM-Philippines-US 1stLd-Writethru a0482 08-25 0605</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Philippines-US, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0482,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>No Treaty Without Aquino Pressure: Enrile</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 4 grafs after 3rd pvs, `Mrs. Aquino...' to UPDATE with
largest Senate party saying it will oppose bases. Pickup 4th pvs, `Sen.
Juan...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Philippine Senate will not ratify
a treaty extending U.S. military bases after 1991 without strong
pressure from President Corazon Aquino, a prominent opposition
lawmaker said today.
   The United States maintains Clark Air Base, the Subic Bay naval
base and four smaller installations under an agreement that expires
in September 1991. Talks are expected to begin late this year on
extending the agreement.
   Mrs. Aquino refuses to say whether she supports a new agreement,
which must be approved by two-thirds of the 23-member Senate. On
Thursday, 12 senators called for closing the bases in 1991, showing
the Aquino administration lacks the votes for ratification.
   The Liberal Party, the most dominant political group in the
Senate, announced after a two-hour closed-door meeting late today
that it would oppose any extension of the bases treaty.
   Senate President Jovito Salonga, the Liberal Party's president,
said his party will ask U.S. officials to withdraw their troops and
dismantle the bases upon the expiration of the treaty.
   He said the party also will conduct a nationwide information
campaign against the bases.
   Eight of the 23 senators belong to the Liberal Party, making it
the most dominant group in the upper chamber.
   Sen. Juan Ponce Enrile, a former defense minister and one of the
resolution's co-sponsors, told foreign reporters he believes all 12
co-signers are strongly committed to closing the bases.
   ``Unless President Aquino exerts her power and influence over her
coalition members, I think that the 11 will stay committed to the
resolution,'' said Enrile, the Senate's only opposition member.
``For myself I know how I will vote, and there are no `ifs' and
`buts' about that.''
   The United States claims the bases are essential for maintaining
security in the Far East. Filipino opponents claim the bases are a
vestige of U.S. colonial rule and infringe on national sovereignty.
   Enrile said the resolution was aimed at pressing Mrs. Aquino into
notifying the United States that the bases will not be extended.
That would give Washington time to relocate its forces elsewhere in
the Pacific and for the Philippines to find alternative uses for the
facilities, he said.
   ``I think that the 11 other members who cosigned the resolution
with me seem to be very committed in what was stated in the
resolution, that the Military Bases Agreement should not be extended
beyond ... 1991,'' Enrile said.
   He suggested that Manila's international airport be relocated to
Clark Air Base, 50 miles north of the capital. Enrile said he
believed the United States could remove its 40,000 service members,
military dependents and civilian employees within six months.
   In the resolution, the 12 senators ruled out a phased withdrawal
that would last beyond 1991, as called for by some Filipino
lawmakers.
   ``Whereas to be fair to all concerned, the undersigned manifest
that they are opposed to any further extension of the presence of
foreign military bases in our country beyond 1991,'' the resolution
says.
   In October 1988, the United States agreed to pay $481 million a
year to keep the bases until 1991. Filipino officials had asked for
$2 billion and are expected to press for more money during future
talks.
   The issue is expected to figure in talks during Mrs. Aquino's
visit to Washington in November. The bases provide jobs to about
70,000 Filipinos and pay more than $96 million annually in civilian
salaries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890825-0089 </DOCNO>
