<FIRST>r a AM-BusCrash-Markers     08-25 0275</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bus Crash-Markers,0283</SECOND>
<HEAD>Highway Signs Erected After Four-Month Battle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CARROLLTON, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two markers have been placed at the site
of a fiery church bus crash that claimed 27 lives last year.
   The Rev. Don Tennison began trying to get a marker placed at the
site in April. Many of the members of his church, First Assembly of
God in Radcliff, are family and friends of the victims.
   They were angered when they learned a state highway crew on March
28 had removed a makeshift memorial of two crosses surrounded by
flowers in the median.
   The markers, on both sides of Interstate 71, are typical highway
markers, green with white lettering, and say ``SITE OF FATAL BUS
CRASH MAY 14, 1988.''
   A final decision on the markers was made Wednesday by the state
department's chief engineer, Gilbert Newman, after he met with state
Sen. Virgil Pearman and Tennison, to whom the markers were presented.
   Tennison learned from state officials that the earlier memorial
had been designated a traffic hazard because drivers had been
slowing to look at it.
   The markers erected Thursday were approved by the Federal Highway
Administration, said Angela Siegel, spokeswoman for the state
Transportation Department.
   Ms. Siegel said there was no ceremony for the 44-by-72-inch
markers' installation, ``because if we made a big deal, we might
create a traffic hazard.''
   The crash occurred when the bus, owned by the Radcliff church,
was hit by a pickup truck traveling the wrong way on the interstate.
Larry Mahoney, the pickup's driver, was charged with 27 counts of
murder and drunken driving in the accident. His trial is scheduled
to begin in November.
</TEXT>
