<FIRST>u i PM-SouthAfrica-Zaire 1stLd-Writethru a0541 08-25 0643</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-South Africa-Zaire, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0541,0659</SECOND>
<HEAD>South Africa, Zaire Will Try to Salvage Angola Truce</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts 3 grafs after 2nd pvs, `De Klerk...' to UPDATE with
details on talks. Pickup 3rd pvs, `Mobuto has...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Angola</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GREG MYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GOMA, Zaire (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   F.W. de Klerk, South Africa's acting
president, and Zaire's President Mobutu Sese Seko agreed at a summit
meeting today to cooperate in trying to salvage a collapsing peace
agreement in war-torn Angola.
   De Klerk, on his first diplomatic mission since assuming the
presidency Aug. 15, conferred with Mobutu for nearly three hours at
a resort on the shores of Lake Kivu. His trip was the latest in a
series of forays into black Africa by white South African officials
seeking to ease their country's isolation.
   The two men gave no indication of any breakthroughs following the
talks, which were described in a joint communique as ``positive,
opportune and constructive, particularly at this critical state of
developments in Angola.''
   They refused to answer any questions.
   An official close to the talks, who requested anonymity,
suggested South Africa and Zaire would try to keep the peace process
alive by serving as intermediaries between Angola's Marxist
government and the UNITA rebels.
   Mobutu has been spearheading efforts to negotiate a settlement of
Angola's civil war, and South Africa has endorsed his initiative
after ending its material support for the Angolan rebel movement,
knwon as UNITA.
   In the joint communique, Mobutu and de Klerk said they discussed
the ``delicate situation'' in Angola and agreed to work to get the
peace process back on track.
   The communique, read by South African Foreign Minister Pik Botha,
said the two leaders agreed there should be a ``follow-up'' to
today's discussions.
   De Klerk, leader of South Africa's governing National Party, is
favored to win election to a five-year term as president after
parliamentary elections on Sept. 6. He became acting president Aug.
15 after P.W. Botha resigned, angered by de Klerk's plans for a
meeting Monday with Zambian President Kenneth Kaunda.
   Mobutu was expected to press de Klerk for details about his
promises to reform South Africa's apartheid policies.
   De Klerk has proposed a five-year plan to extend political rights
to blacks. But he has indicated he wants to maintain white veto
power over major decisions and to continue with segregated
neighborhoods and schools for whites.
   De Klerk met Mozambique's President Joaquim Chissano in July.
   Botha met last year with four black African leaders, including
Mobutu, in a bid to ease South Africa's isolation on the continent.
   Prior to those trips, Botha had not traveled abroad for a summit
meeting with any African leader since coming to power in 1978.
   South Africa has improved its standing in Africa with its
decision to grant independence to Namibia, the neighboring territory
it has ruled for 74 years.
   South Africa agreed to Namibian independence in December when it
signed a regional peace treaty with the Marxist Angolan government
and its Cuban allies.
   The accord calls for a phased withdrawal of Cuba's 50,000 troops
from Angola, where they have assisted in the fighting against UNITA
_ the National Union for the Total Independence of Angola.
   Mobutu hosted an African summit June 22 in which the Angolan
government and UNITA agreed to a cease-fire. Since then, he has
mediated sporadic negotiations between the two sides. However, UNITA
leader Jonas Savimbi said Thursday that the truce was over and told
his rebel forces to prepare for further fighting.
   And today, UNITA issued a statement saying 77 government troops
and six of its rebels were killed in heavy fighting in Angola this
week.
   South Africa supported UNITA until December's peace treaty.
   The United States still aids the rebels, and some of the
assistance is routed through Zaire. UNITA has been fighting since
1975 for a power-sharing agreement with the Angolan government.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
