<FIRST>u a PM-Frank-Prostitute 4thLd-Writethru a0566 08-25 0981</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Frank-Prostitute, 4th Ld - Writethru, a0566,1005</SECOND>
<HEAD>Congressman Admits Hiring Prostitute for Personal Staff</HEAD>
<BYLINE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to insert new Frank comments, move up
reference to man's duties; Picks up 15th graf, ``He was ...'; SUBS grafs
22-32, `Frank said ...' with 4 grafs to tighten, delete now-redundant material;
Picks up 33rd graf, ``Paying for ...' ^By DAN BEEGAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWTON, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rep. Barney Frank said today he hired a male
prostitute as a personal employee but fired him two years ago when
he became suspicious the man was selling sex from Frank's Capitol
Hill apartment.
   ``I was victimized,'' Frank, D-Mass., said in a telephone
interview with The Associated Press.
   ``I knew he had been a prostitute. ... I was trying to get him to
stop. I didn't know he was expanding his business. From firsthand
knowledge I (still) don't know that,'' said Frank, 49, a liberal
Democrat who publicly acknowledged his homosexuality in May 1987.
   During a news conference later at his office in this Boston
suburb, Frank said he had shown poor judgement in hiring the man.
   ``Thinking I was going to be Henry Higgins and trying to turn him
into Pygmalion was the biggest mistake I ever made,'' he said. ``He
took me.''
   Frank said he met the man in 1985 through an ``escort-model''
advertisement in a Washington gay newspaper. The congressman
admitted paying for sex with the man one time, but said the
relationship quickly became one of friendship. He said he no longer
uses escort services.
   In a report in today's editions of The Washington Times, a man
identified as Greg Davis told the newspaper that Frank was aware
that sex was being sold from the congressman's apartment and was
concerned that it might be discovered.
   Frank called those allegations ``absolutely untrue.''
   ``His suggestion that he was procuring sex partners for me is a
lie,'' Frank also said.
   When asked if the revelations might force him to resign from
Congress, Frank replied: ``Of course not. Why should it?'' He said
he planned to run for re-election for a sixth term in 1990.
   ``I don't think I'm going to be heavily penalized by the voters
for being suckered by a guy I was trying to help,'' he said.
   ``I hired him out of a charitable impulse. I misjudged his
character. ... I think he was a pretty good con man,'' he said.
   Frank said he hired the man as a personal assistant to do work
around his house, drive his car and run errands. Frank said he paid
him about $20,000 a year for about a year and a half with personal
money. He said no government or campaign funds were used.
   Frank said he fired him in August 1987 after his landlady told
him for the second time that the man may have been arranging
liaisons at the apartment in Frank's absence.
   ``He was angry. He threatened me with a variety of retributions
and apparently he decided the way to to that was go to The
Washington Times,'' Frank said.
   In a companion story today, the Times reported that the principal
of an elementary school in the well-to-do Washington suburb of Chevy
Chase, Md., acknowledged that he had allowed Davis to use school
offices in 1987. School officials placed the principal on leave
after the story broke.
   The prostitute told the Times he used a telephone in the school
guidance counselor's office to arrange liaisons, but Principal
Gabriel Massaro denied to the newspaper that he knew what Davis was
doing.
   The newspaper said Davis was a professional name and it did not
disclose his real name, but Frank identified the man as Steve Gobie.
There was no telephone listing for Gobie in Washington or its
suburbs.
   ``He was a male prostitute and I thought ... that he was smart
enough to do something else,'' Frank said. ``I said he should get a
job. He said he was on probation and couldn't get a job because of
that.''
   The Times said the man's probation stemmed from four felony
convictions in 1982: possession of obscene material, production of
obscene items involving a juvenile, oral sodomy and possession of
cocaine. He also was convicted of cocaine distribution in 1975, the
newspaper said.
   ``I thought I could help him reform,'' Frank said.
   Frank said he wrote letters of reference on his congressional
stationery to the probation board to verify that Gobie was employed.
   The congressman said he knew that Gobie sometimes stayed at his
apartment when he was out of town and that he told Gobie there
should be no drugs there.
   ``But it never occurred to me to say don't engage in
prostitution,'' Frank said.
   Frank said he gave Gobie a couple of small jobs to do in 1987
after he complained about having a difficult time finding work, but
fired him after he ``tried to extort me'' and ``I ordered him not to
have any access to me.''
   ``Paying for sex, that's one of the things that led me to
acknowledge being gay,'' Frank said. ``Before, living as a closeted
gay man was difficult. ... It was one of the reasons I was
vulnerable to being preyed on.''
   Asked when was the last time he paid for sex, Frank replied:
``I'm not going to get into that.''
   He did say he has been in a monogamous homosexual relationship
for about two years.
   ``He's a very sensible person and a steadying influence,'' Frank
said about his partner.
   Frank's homosexuality became the subject of controversy this
summer when the Republican National Committee circulated a memo
comparing his voting record with that of new House Speaker Thomas S.
Foley.
   The memo, titled ``Tom Foley: Out of the Liberal Closet,'' said
Foley's voting record was as liberal as Frank's. The RNC aide who
wrote the memo resigned and RNC Chairman Lee Atwater apologized to
Foley.
</TEXT>
