<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1304EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Poland-Baltics Bjt   08-25 0831</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Poland-Baltics, Bjt,0852</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baltics Look West to Warsaw in Independence Drive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VILNIUS, U.S.S.R. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Residents of the Soviet Baltic republics
are encouraged by neighboring Poland's bold steps away from
communism as they probe the limits of President Mikhail S.
Gorbachev's reforms.
   As more than a million Baltic residents formed a human chain this
week to mourn the independence they lost to Stalin's tanks a
half-century ago, a poster was displayed in Vilnius, the Lithuanian
capital:
   ``Lithuanians and Poles: Let's Unite Against the Common Enemy.''
   It was not clear whether the message was directed at Poles living
in their homeland or the Polish minority in Lithuania, but there was
little doubt about the ``common enemy'': Soviet-style communism.
   The message tried to cuts across the border formed by Stalin's
incorporation of the Baltics in 1940 to emphasize Lithuania's
location twice as far Moscow as from Warsaw, and five centuries of
history when the two lands were united in one kingdom.
   Poland's Solidarity trade union capped its nine-year reform
battle with the election Thursday of one its leaders as prime
minister, the first non-Communist in that post in the East bloc. On
the previous day in the Baltics, residents held hands to mark the
50th anniversary of a secret Nazi-Soviet agreement that gave Poland
to Germany and the Baltics to the Soviet Union on the eve of World
War II.
   Although Baltic activists stress there are many differences
between their campaign and that of Solidarity, they say the group's
experience is valuable.
   Vytautas Landsbergis, president of the Lithuanian grassroots
independence movement Sajudis, said in an interview that
Solidarity's accomplishments were important ``for all democratic
forces in Eastern Europe, like the movement in 1968 in
Czechoslovakia.''
   So far, the Kremlin's reaction to the formation of a
non-communist government in Poland has been calm, taking the line
that it is the country's internal affair and offering to work with
the new prime minister. The response to the Baltic movement has been
harsh words against calls for independence but overall an
unprecedented level of tolerance and even sympathy to their demands
for at least economic autonomy.
   Some Baltic residents, especially the elderly who saw troops roll
in 1940 to impose Soviet rule, fear the Kremlin will again send in
tanks and troops, as it did in Hungary in 1956 and Czechoslovakia 12
years later, to crush the Baltic democratic movement.
   But others point to Solidarity's victory as proof that force will
not work.
   Peter Sookruus, deputy propaganda chief of Estonia's Communist
Party Central Committee, said Gen. Wojciech Jaruzelski's imposition
of martial law in Poland in December 1981 backfired.
   ``Poland finally faced bigger problems than it had originally. In
that sense, Poland served as an example,'' Sookruss told a news
conference in the Estonian capital of Tallinn. ``The Polish
Communist Party was willing to give up its monopoly on power.''
   Zbigniew Romaszewski, a Solidarity official who in a sign of the
group's improved standing has become a Polish senator, traveled to
Vilnius and the Latvian capital Riga to join in last week's
ceremonies. In an interview in the Sajudis offices, he agreed the
Kremlin would be unlikely to repeat the mistake and forcibly put
down the Baltic independence drive.
   ``We couldn't be destroyed even if we were in prison. The
symbols, ethos (of Solidarity) are very important in the socialist
bloc. This was all preserved despite the imposition of martial law
in December 1981,'' said Romaszewski, sporting a red Solidarity pin
on his lapel.
   Solidarity proved that ``it is possible to organize an
anti-totalitarian movement,'' he said.
   The senator said Gorbachev's reform effort and worsening economic
conditions in Poland and the Soviet Union are forcing Communist
leaders to realize they must put up with opposition groups and
democracy, and that the Kremlin must allow Poland and the Baltics to
settle their problems without interference.
   While they reject Kremlin meddling, activists on both sides
welcome cooperation between the democratic movements.
   Algis Cekuolis, a member of Sajudis ruling council, said
Solidarity leader Lech Walesa has promised to travel to Lithuania
this fall to try to help Sajudis persuade the republic's Polish
minority to join the group in fighting for independence.
   Poles, representing about 8 percent of Lithuania's population,
are more aligned with Russians than Lithuanians and have formed a
political group, Unity, to fight for their own rights. So far, the
Poles are concerned about Sajudis' Lithuanian nationalism.
   But while they see a future of cooperation, many Lithuanians say
they and the Poles are too different to copy each other's tactics.
   ``Everybody has their own way,'' said Raimonda Kaminskiene, an
English teacher interviewed at a pro-independence rally in Vilnius.
``We are not so quick in our character. We are more northern, more
Scandinavian. We always have to think what we are doing.''
   She then quoted a Lithuanian saying about sewing, similar to one
in Russian, to underscore the point. ``You have to think nine times,
and the 10th you have to cut.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
