<FIRST>r w AM-SilentMarch     08-25 0205</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Silent March,200</SECOND>
<HEAD>NAACP `Silent March' Saturday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Muffled drumbeats should be the loudest sound
Saturday when the NAACP recreates in the capital the ``Silent
March,'' a civil rights protest in New York City 72 years ago.
   The protest will focus on ``the Supreme Court and its recent
hostile decisions'' diluting affirmative action and minority
set-aside programs, said NAACP executive director Benjamin L. Hooks.
   The 1917 demonstration, in which 8,000 people led by W.E.B.
DuBois paraded in silence down Fifth Avenue, protested segregation
laws and lynchings in the South.
   The Washington march, also led by six drummers playing on muffled
instruments, is designed to duplicate the New York march in tone and
style if not in crowd size.
   The march will end at the Capitol with a rally, including
speeches by Hooks, the Rev. Jesse Jackson and the Rev. Joseph
Lowery, head of the Southern Christian Leadership Conference.
   Hooks and other officials of the NAACP _ National Association for
the Advancement of Colored People _ gave no crowd projection other
than ``several thousand.''
   ``We are not looking toward bringing vast numbers of people to
Washington,'' he said. ``In this instance, the medium is the message
and the medium is the silent march.''
</TEXT>
