<FIRST>u i PM-Pakistan-Plane 3rdLd-Writethru a0564 08-25 0253</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Pakistan-Plane, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0564, a0570,0255</SECOND>
<HEAD>Plane Missing in Pakistan With 54 People Aboard</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS thruout to UPDATE with American believed on board, details.
No pickup.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Bad weather forced the suspension
today of a search for a Pakistan International Airlines plane with
54 people aboard that disappeared over the Himalaya and Korakoram
mountains.
   Two Pakistan Air Force C-130 aircraft, helicopters and a small
PIA plane scanned the mountains for signs of the twin-engine
Fokker-27 until the onset of darkness and rains forced them to wait
until Saturday, said Azra Sultan, an airline spokeswoman.
   The airline said the twin-engine plane had not been heard from
since it took off early this morning on what should have been a
45-minute flight from Gilgit to Islamabad.
   Ms. Sultan said most of the 49 passengers aboard were Pakistanis,
but the list included an American, Paul McGorrian, a freelance
journalist believed to be from St. Petersburg, Fla. There were five
crew members.
   Rescue workers in planes searched the mountains today, but their
effort was hampered by thunderstorms and heavy rains.
   It was not known if the missing plane had encountered bad
weather, but planes generally don't leave the Korakoram Mountain
city of Gilgit in storms.
   A chief pilot at Pakistan International Airlines, who identified
himself only as Khizar, said the search was conducted by the
Pakistan Air Force, the Civil Aviation Authority, their Indian
counterparts, and the U.N. Military Observer Group in India and
Pakistan posted in the disputed state of Jammu-Kashmir.
</TEXT>
