<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1450EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Brites     08-25 0451</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Brites,0467</SECOND>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENVILLE, S.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A history buff who calls herself one of
``those slightly wacky kind of people'' placed an advertisement in
the newspaper this week to commemorate the death of King Richard III
of England _ who died more than 500 years ago.
   Yvonne Mason paid for a memorial to King Richard that was run
Tuesday on the obituary page of The News, complete with his emblem,
the white boar, and his motto ``Loyaulte Me Lie,'' which translates,
``Loyalty binds me.''
   King Richard, who was the object of a play by Shakespeare, was
accused of having his two young nephews murdered so he could claim
the throne. Ms. Mason, a member of the Richard III Society, believes
history dealt unfairly with him.
   ``I think most of us, the people who are involved in this, are
kind of those slightly wacky kind of people who just seriously
believe in something and want it to be different,'' Ms. Mason said.
   After reading Shakespeare's play, she started reading books about
the king. ``I thought, `You know, something is not right here. This
man doesn't seem quite as bad as he's painted,''' she said. She said
Friday that she believs the order to have the boys killed came from
someone else.
   The Richard III Society claims 5,000 members including about 800
in the United States.
   She has run her memorial for three or four years in The News.
Other society members do the same in London and in other towns.
   ``I think in the context of history, it's really time that he's
recognized for the able and just and intelligent leader that he was,
instead of, `Isn't he the one who killed those children in that
tower?''' she said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>COSTA MESA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sam Gregory is bringing a touch of
Merrie Olde England to his Southern California neighborhood.
   Remembering a time of courageous knights and horse-drawn
carriages, Gregory is building a castle complete with cast-iron
gates, a spiraling staircase, a moat and a drawbridge.
   Once finished, the 3,000-square-foot structure around Gregory's
existing home will contain a living room, master bedroom, study,
kitchen, dining room and bathrooms, said Gregory, who has been a
general contractor for 25 years.
   Already, the masonry and the skeleton of the structure has been
completed. And there are two ducks, gifts to Gregory's wife, Rose,
swimming in the moat.
   Before the last concrete block is placed, Gregory said he expects
to spend $300,000 _ a little more than planned.
   But cost is no object, he said, explaining he intends to keep the
promise he made to his wife several years ago.
   ``This is dedicated to the one I love,'' he sang off-key.
</TEXT>
