<FIRST>u i AM-Korea     08-25 0625</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Korea,0642</SECOND>
<HEAD>Indicted Dissident Charges Fabrication, Persecution</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PAUL SHIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEOUL, South Korea (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kim Dae-jung, South Korea's best-known
dissident, said Friday his indictment under the national security
laws was an act of persecution intended to discredit his opposition
political party.
   Radical students shouting slogans against the government and the
United States battled riot police with rocks and firebombs in the
worst campus violence for several months. The protests were not
inspired by the action against Kim, but were directed at the laws
under which he was charged.
   Kim leads the Party for Peace and Democracy, the largest
opposition group in South Korea. He said the charges were fabricated
and declared to followers: ``I have nothing to fear. I will squarely
face trial.''
   Prosecutors charged in the indictments, presented earlier Friday,
that Kim and two legislators from his party failed to report
National Assemblyman Suh Kyung-won's secret trip to Communist North
Korea last year. The three opposition figures were not jailed
pending trial.
   National security laws forbid unauthorized travel to North Korea,
which South Korea has defined as an enemy country since the
peninsula was divided in 1945. The two Koreas fought a war in
1950-53, but no peace treaty has been signed.
   If convicted, Kim, party floor leader Kim Won-ki and Rep. Lee
Chul-yong could be sentenced to prison terms of up to five years.
   Kim said prosecutors knew they could not win the case, so the
three might never be tried. Aides said the government could
influence the judiciary to delay proceedings indefinitely.
   Legal experts said the trial of Suh, the man who made the trip,
should be finished within six months. It is to begin in September.
   Suh was arrested June 28 on charges of espionage, violating a ban
on unauthorized travel to North Korea and receiving $120,000 from
North Korean agents before and during the trip to Pyongyang in
August 1988.
   Prosecutors said they had evidence that Kim knew about Suh's trip
two months before it was made public in June. Kim has said he did
not learn of the trip until shortly before Suh turned himself in to
authorities in late June.
   The 64-year-old opposition leader also was charged with violating
the Foreign Currency Control Law by receiving $10,000 from Suh.
Prosecutors said Kim apparently did not know the money was from
North Korea, so the only charge was failing to report it.
   Kim, who ran for president in 1971 and 1987, has denied having
anything to do with Suh's trip to North Korea or his alleged
espionage.
   Suh, 52, was elected to the National Assembly in April 1988. He
was expelled from Kim's party after his trip was made public.
   Fighting was reported at two Seoul universities after police
blocked attempts by 1,400 students to march into the streets after
campus rallies. No injuries were reported.
   A main theme of the protests was the arrest of a radical woman
student who returned home across the land border at the Panmunjom
truce village Aug. 15 from an illegal trip to North Korea.
   Im Su-kyong visited the North in late June to attend a world
youth festival July 1-8. She said her trip was a symbolic gesture
for reunification.
   At Hankook University of Foreign Studies, about 400 students
fought police with firebombs and rocks for two hours before police
drove them back to the campus with tear gas.
   The students demanded the release of Miss Im and repeal of the
national security laws. They also demanded withdrawal of the 43,000
American soldiers stationed in South Korea.
   At Seoul National University, about 800 riot police firing tear
gas from two armored vans blocked 1,000 students from leaving
campus. The students at Seoul National did not use firebombs.
</TEXT>
