<FIRST>u a PM-Bush 2ndLd-Writethru a0556 08-25 0602</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Bush, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0556,590</SECOND>
<HEAD>Boating Mishap Snags President</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Inserts new 3rd graf, Asked whether, with Bush comment</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KENNEBUNKPORT, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Bush bade farewell to the
visiting prime minister of Denmark today, then hit a snag in his
vacation when his speedboat became became snarled in a line and was
disabled.
   The summer White House, meanwhile, prepared to turn its attention
later in the day to a package of new assistance for combating drugs
in Colombia. Officials said details of the $2.5 million aid package
would be announced here later today.
   Asked whether he would send helicopters or other equipment to
help Colombia fight the drug lords, Bush replied, ``We're working on
the problem. There's a lot going on on that front ... We're working
to accommodate President (Virgilio) Barco ... We're working now with
his people in Washington.''
   Bush escorted his house guests, Danish Prime Minister Poul
Schlueter and his wife, Anne Marie, to the helicopter pad on his
11-acre vacation compound here.
   The Schlueters, who are on their honeymoon, arrived Thursday and
were traveling to Boston after leaving Maine.
   Although Bush said Thursday that he and Schlueter, whom he first
met at the United Nations in the 1970s, would discuss ``fascinating
changes'' in Europe and the international war on narcotics, the two
first families spent much of their time boating and fishing.
   Bush, asked by reporters about apparently dimmed prospects that
Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega will step down as Panama's military
ruler, shrugged his shoulders and said, ``We just keep on going.''
   He had no other coments as he waved a farewell to his guests.
   Bush then went out for a fishing trip, taking two reporters
along, but returned to the dock after only a few minutes.
   The president's boat, Fidelity, appeared to have run over a
lobster trap line and one of its two propellers was disabled.
   Despite efforts by a underwater frogman to unsnarl the line, Bush
and his party left the boat and it was taken to a local marina for
repairs.
   On Thursday, Bush voiced praise for the new Solidarity-led
government in Poland, complimenting both the old and the new regimes
in a carefully worded statement. That day, Poland became the first
Soviet-bloc nation to have a non-communist-led government.
   Bush said in the statement that Poles ``will have our continued
support as they meet the serious economic and political challenges
before them.''
   He congratulated the new Polish prime minister, former Solidarity
activist Tadeusz Mazowieck.
   ``I also salute President (Wojciech) Jaruzelski for his political
wisdom in endorsing a government reflecting the genuine will of the
Polish people and Solidarity, under the leadership of Lech Walesa,
for its constructive role in helping bring about a new beginning in
Poland,'' the president said.
   ``These developments hold promise not only for a peaceful
democratic transition in Poland but also for a broader process of
European reconcilation, toward a Europe whole and free.''
   The vacation White House, meanwhile, had little to say on new
violence in Colombia, which presidential press secretary Marlin
Fitzwater said was being closely monitored.
   Authorities in Colombia said drug traffickers Thursday bombed the
headquarters of two political parties and set fire to two
politicians' homes, killing one person.
   Meanwhile, Bush, who has yet to catch a fish despite daily
fishing outings in his power boat, was presented a 5-pound haddock
by a local fisherman as the president gave the Danish couple a boat
tour of the Kennebunkport waterfront.
   ``He gave it to me,'' Bush told onlookers, showing the fish.
``It's the only way I can get them.''
</TEXT>
