<FIRST>r w AM-US-Angola     08-25 0307</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Angola,300</SECOND>
<HEAD>U.S. Urges Cease-Fire in Angola</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Bush administration on Friday urged warring
Angolan factions to reach a cease-fire to end the outbreak of
violence in the civil war there.
   ``In order for there to be an effective cease-fire, there must be
a comprehensive cease-fire agreement. Such an agreement would be in
the interest of both sides,'' said State Department spokesman
Richard Boucher.
   Angola's UNITA guerrilla leader Jonas Savimbi on Thursday
renounced a truce that began in June. The agreement between Savimbi
and Angolan President Jose Eduardo dos Santos was designed to end
the 14-year civil war.
   The truce began collapsing the week after it began. UNITA on
Friday said 77 government troops and six of its rebels were killed
in heavy fighting this week.
   F.W. de Klerk, South Africa's acting president, and Zaire's
President Mobutu Sese Seko agreed at a summit meeting Friday in
Goma, Zaire, to cooperate in trying to salvage the Angolan peace
agreement.
   Mobutu has been spearheading efforts to negotiate a settlement of
Angola's civil war, and South Africa has endorsed his initiative
after ending its material support for UNITA.
   Boucher said the United States was urging Angolan factions ``to
resume negotiations under Zairean mediation'' to reach a cease-fire
agreement.
   Western-backed UNITA, the Portuguese acronym for the National
Union for the Total Independence of Angola, has been fighting the
government and its Cuban allies to force a power-sharing agreement
since shortly after Angola gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
   UNITA was not party to U.S.-brokered international accords signed
in New York in which South Africa pledged to halt aid to the
guerrillas and allow Angola's southern neighbor, Namibia, to gain
independence. In return, Cuba began a phased withdrawal of its
estimated 50,000 troops from Angola.
   UNITA still receives $15 million to $18 million annually in U.S.
military aid.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
