<FIRST>u w AM-US-Cambodia     08-25 0399</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-US-Cambodia,400</SECOND>
<HEAD>Baker Will Sit out Meeting Due to Lack Of Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Secretary of State James A. Baker III will sit
out next week's close of the Paris peace conference on Cambodia
because of the lack of progress on a truce and power-sharing
arrangement, the State Department said Friday.
   Accusing Vietnam and its surrogate government in Cambodia of
inflexibility, State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said
``Secretary Baker does not plan at this time to return to Paris for
the August 28th to 30th ministerial session.''
   Baker took part in the opening round of the talks that seek an
agreement between the Cambodian government and a rebel coalition
backed by Prince Norodom Sihanouk once Vietnam withdraws the last of
its troops next month.
   Boucher said there had been too little pogress on the central
sticking point of the talks _ who would take part in a transitional
government that will rule Cambodia until free elections can be
arranged.
   ``Prince Sihanouk has demonstrated admirable flexibility in
attempting to resolve this key power-sharing problem,'' Boucher
said. ``Unfortunately, his reasonable attitude has not been
reciprocated by Hanoi or the Phnom Penh regime. At this point,
therefore, a comprehensive settlement is not in sight.''
   The Paris conference, under the sponsorship of 19 countries and
the United Nations, sent a fact-finding U.N. team to Cambodia to
gather information for establishment of a peacekeeping force that
would oversee the withdrawal of the estimated 26,000 Vietnamese
troops and implementation of a cease-fire.
   The United States wants Sihanouk to head an interim government.
But Cambodian leader Hun Sen rejects any participation by Sihanouk's
main coalition partner, the China-backed Khmer Rouge. The communist
faction ruled Cambodia in the 1970s and is believed to have killed
more than 1 million people before being forced out by Vietnam in
1978.
   U.S. officials say Sihanouk has offered the working groups in
Paris several formulas for power-sharing, while Hun Sen has failed
to concede any role for Sihanouk except at the head of a commission
to oversee elections.
   Sihanouk believes that if the Khmer Rouge are left out of an
interim government they will fight and endanger chances for peace,
U.S. officials say. But he is also thought to believe that a new
Cambodian government can eventually split the Khmer Rouge by weeding
out and removing the most dangerous elements within the faction.
</TEXT>
