<FIRST>u w AM-Colombia-Thornburgh     08-25 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>^AM-Colombia-Thornburgh,420</SECOND>
<HEAD>Thornburgh: Colombian Fugitives Endanger Host Countries</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-US-Colombia Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROLYN SKORNECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Attorney General Dick Thornburgh said Friday
that countries considering harboring drug traffickers who fled their
native Colombia's crackdown should take heed of the violence
plaguing that nation.
   ``I think any nation around the world is certainly going to take
notice of the enormous cost that Colombia is paying for letting
these criminals proceed to dominate the processes of law,''
Thornburgh said. ``I would hope that any country where these
individuals seek refuge will respond accordingly.''
   But Thornburgh said he could not confirm reports that some of the
drug kingpins had fled to Brazil or Panama.
   ``As usual, when you're looking for fugitives, there are a number
of reported sightings, but I don't think I could give you anything
with authority,'' he said.
   As for Eduardo Martinez Romero _ the one person arrested in
Colombia's nationwide sweep who the United States has said it wants
to extradite _ Thornburgh said the extradition proceedings ``have
about been completed.''
   ``Our hope is that we will be in a position to deliver over the
weekend the necessary documentation to Colombian officials,''
Thornburgh said.
   Martinez was indicted in March in Atlanta on charges of
laundering money for the Medellin cocaine cartel, reputed to be the
largest in the world.
   While Colombian authorities have said they have arrested other
people who are wanted on charges in the United States, Thornburgh
did not respond when asked if the Justice Department was seeking
their extradition as well.
   Other administration officials have said they are unfamiliar with
the other people arrested.
   Although Thornburgh and Colombian Minister of Justice Monica de
Greiff had planned to meet this week to discuss extradition
procedures, the Colombia embassy in Washington said Friday that Ms.
de Greiff remained in Bogota following an outbreak of bombings and
fires in Medellin allegedly set by drug traffickers who declared
``total war'' on the government.
   The Colombian Supreme Court, under threat from drug traffickers,
threw out an extradition treaty in 1987. Colombian President
Virgilio Barco resumed extraditions last weekend in an emergency
action following the assassination of Luis Carlos Galan, a leading
presidential candidate who strongly opposed the drug trade.
   Meanwhile, Thornburgh said it was unclear what impact the
Colombian crackdown was having on the flow of cocaine from Colombia
to the United States.
   ``That's hard to say,'' the attorney general said. ``The ultimate
dislocation of the cocaine problem in the United States is going to
come when people quit using cocaine.''
</TEXT>
