<FIRST>r a AM-People-JFKJr     08-25 0173</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-People-JFK Jr,0176</SECOND>
<HEAD>JFK Jr. Won't Lose His License</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John F. Kennedy Jr.'s first week as a prosecutor
ended Friday with an acquittal _ his, on a charge of driving an
uninsured vehicle, the state Department of Motor Vehicles said.
   Kennedy's attorney, Richard A. Halloran, brought evidence to the
DMV office in Queens that his client's car was insured when police
ticketed the presidential son on July 9, said DMV spokesman Tom
Apple.
   The charge was then dismissed, although DMV has six months to
verify the Kennedy documents, Apple said. The uninsured vehicle
charge was the most serious of four against Kennedy; he could have
lost his license for one year if convicted.
   Kennedy, who joined the Manhattan district attorney's office on
Monday, did not appear at the hearing Friday.
   A charge of driving an unregistered car was put off until Sept.
29, which is also the deadline for Kennedy to pay a $127 fine on his
guilty pleas to speeding and driving an uninspected vehicle, Apple
said.
