<FIRST>r a AM-Drownings     08-25 0360</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drownings,0376</SECOND>
<HEAD>Wife Defends Husband Accused of Drowning Children</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A man charged with drowning his four children and
trying to kill his wife by driving their car into a river ``lived
for those kids'' and is innocent, the wife said.
   ``Right now, I love him with every ounce of my body,'' Suzanne
DeLisle told The Detroit News in a story published Friday. ``There's
no doubt in my mind what happened. It was a complete and total
accident. I know how hard he tried to stop the car.''
   Lawrence DeLisle was arrested Aug. 10 and charged with four
counts of first-degree murder and one of attempted murder. The
family's car slammed through a barricade and into the Detroit River
in Wyandotte on Aug. 3, killing their children, Bryan, 8, Melissa,
4, Kathryn, 2, and Emily, 8 months.
   DeLisle and his wife escaped and passing boaters rescued them.
   DeLisle, 28, initially said a leg cramp caused him to jam down
the gas pedal and careen into the river. But police said he later
admitted that, distraught over deep debts, he deliberately plunged
the car into the river.
   Mrs. DeLisle, 32, told the News she thought police coerced her
husband into making the admission.
   ``They were using every technique in the book on him and he
cracked,'' she said in an interview from a relative's home in Tampa,
Fla.
   ``He lived for those kids. We never did anything without them,''
she said. ``He would never have hurt the kids.''
   ``I have lost four of the most precious things in my life. That's
all I ever wanted was children,'' Mrs. DeLisle said.
   She also said she fears testifying at her husband's preliminary
hearing, scheduled for Thursday.
   ``I don't want them to manipulate me. I don't want to be the one
who locks him away for the rest of his life for something they
mistook and turned around,'' she said.
   DeLisle remains in the Wayne County Jail without bond, and his
wife said he is confused and depressed.
   ``He thinks I blame him, which I don't,'' she said. ``It could
have been me who was driving. It could have been anybody.''
</TEXT>
