<DOCNO> AP890825-0130 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 2149EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r w AM-BRF--DadaArt     08-25 0174</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Dada Art,170</SECOND>
<HEAD>National Gallery Acquires Dada Art Work</HEAD>
<UNK></UNK>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The National Gallery of Art recently bought its
first work by French artist Francis Picabia, titled ``Machine Turn
Quickly,'' and will put the modernistic image on display Sunday as
part of a long-term exhibition on 20th century art.
   Picabia, Marcel Duchamp and Man Ray were the New York leaders of
the so-called dada movement of ``anti-art'' that arose in Europe and
America from disillusionment over the events leading to World War I.
   Dada artists emphasized word play, the absurd and the importance
of chance in artistic creation, and often used machine imagery to
portray human activity.
   Picabia's ``Machine Turn Quickly,'' produced in 1916-18 using
gouache and metallic paint, depicts man and woman as gears enmeshed
in an endlessly repeating cycle.
   National Gallery director J. Carter Brown said the Picabia work,
purchased from a dealer, will be displayed with two other dada works
from the gallery's permanent collection, Duchamp's ``The Box in a
Valise'' and ``Untitled (Medici Prince)'' by Joseph Cornell.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
