<FIRST>u i AM-Bulgaria     08-25 0380</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bulgaria,0393</SECOND>
<HEAD>Violence Reported Involving Minority in Bulgaria</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Diplomats in Sofia said Friday that at
least 15 people were killed in southern Bulgaria in mid-August in
clashes involving security forces and members of the 200,000-strong
Pomak minority.
   The state news agency BTA said the report was untrue.
   In many places, soldiers and tanks moved in to quell the unrest,
said the diplomats in the Bulgarian capital, who were reached by
telephone from Vienna and spoke on condition of anonymity.
   They reported deaths in Dobnitsa, Kornitsa and Lozhnitsa in the
Blagoevgrad area and said other casualities occurred in at least a
dozen other villages.
   The actual death toll was likely to be much higher, according to
reports reaching the diplomats. They said no report on wounded was
available.
   The diplomats said the Pomaks, ethnic Bulgarians of Moslem faith,
were protesting government refusal to give them passports to
emigrate to Turkey.
   At least 310,000 ethnic Turks living in Bulgaria have received
passports and crossed to Turkey since May, when communist
authorities said at least nine ethnic Turks died in clashes with
security forces in northern Bulgaria.
   The diplomats put the number of May deaths at 30 or more.
   According to the sources, the new disturbances started this month
in northeastern Bulgaria near Razgrad and Varna on the Black Sea,
where anger flared among the Pomaks over the travel ban.
   In the south, disturbances took place both in Pomak and in mixed
Pomak-Turkish communities, said the diplomatic sources, who
mentioned the villages of Volko Selo, Ribnovo, Khostanie and
Breznitsa.
   Unlike the ethnic Turks, Pomaks have not been granted passports.
Turkey this week closed its border to the ethnic Turks from
Bulgaria, saying they want a formal emigration agreement with Sofia
before allowing more to enter.
   Diplomats said Pomaks were threatened with legal proceedings if
they did not stop applying for passports.
   Bulgaria faces an acute labor shortage with the sudden emigration
of hundreds of thousands of ethnic Turkish workers. Last month,
special regulations empowered authorities to draft labor from towns
to the fields for harvesting.
   Reports of the unrest followed word from emigre sources that
Pomaks in northeastern Bulgaria were conducting hunger strikes to
protest the refusal to grant passports and the continued detention
of six prominent dissidents.
</TEXT>
