<FIRST>u i AM-Soviet-Ethnic     08-25 0405</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Soviet-Ethnic,0417</SECOND>
<HEAD>Moldavian Strike Spreads, Officials Appeal for Calm</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strikes in Moldavia against a pending language law
spread on Friday and the southern republic's government appealed for
calm, the official news agency Tass reported.
   It said railroad workers at Bendery and four other stations held
two-hour strikes. More than 90 factories were idled on Thursday.
   About 50,000 people attended a rally in Tiraspol to urge
postponement of the law, which would make the language of the
Moldavian majority the official one for the republic.
   The Presidium of the republic's legislature said strikes
increased ``the destablization of the socio-political situation.''
It said the law could be considered only in a calm atmosphere.
   Russians, Ukrainians and other non-Moldavians say the law is
discriminatory and would set Moldavia on the same path of
inter-ethnic relations as the three Baltic republics _ Estonia,
Latvia and Lithuania.
   Pravda, the national Communist Party newspaper, said Friday that
no tolerance for minorities remained in Lithuania. ``An overt
division of forces ... is now under way in the republic,'' it
declared.
   It accused leaders of the Lithuanian Communist Party, who
recently have joined calls for independence from the Soviet Union,
of lacking a clear program of local reform.
   The Moldavian strikes follow the pattern in Estonia, where
non-Estonians walked out for nine days earlier this month to protest
a law setting residency requirements for voting and seeking local
office.
   Protesters in Moldavia also say the republic's government allowed
too little time for public discussion of the law before the
legislature considers it Aug. 29. The draft law was published by the
official press Sunday.
   Leaders of the Moldavian People's Front say the draft proposal
does not go far enough.
   Yuri Rozhgo, a spokesman, said it gives Russian nearly the same
status as Moldavian. He said the People's Front supported the law
but would try to have it amended by the legislature.
   Rozhgo said the People's Front would hold a large rally Sunday in
central Kishinev to press its demands.
   Moldavians make up about 64 percent of the republic's 4.2 million
people but are outnumbered in many major cities, where Russian is
widely used.
   In addition to making Moldavian the official language, the law
would return the republic to the Latin alphabet from the Cyrillic.
After Moldavia was forcibly taken from Romania in 1940, the alphabet
was changed to emphasize the Soviet view that Moldavians and
Romanians were distinct nationalities.
</TEXT>
