<FIRST>u i AM-Rushdie 1stLd-Writethru a0587 08-25 0425</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Rushdie, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0587,0440</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rushdie, Wife Living Apart, Publisher Says</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to ADD wife's earlier comments on being in
hiding, other. No pickup</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Salman Rushdie, the novelist threatened with death
by the late Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini for writing the book ``The
Satanic Verses,'' is living apart from his American wife, Marianne
Wiggins, she announced Friday through her publisher.
   Secker and Warburg issued a brief statement saying Ms. Wiggins,
herself a writer, and the Indian-born Rushdie ``have been living
separately for four weeks.
   ``Scotland Yard security arrangements for the protection of Mr.
Rushdie have been reordered since then and Ms. Wiggins does not know
where he is,'' the statement said.
   ``Ms. Wiggins requests privacy; She is not prepared to discuss
the matter further.''
   The couple, who were married in January 1988, had been in hiding
since last Feb. 14, when Khomeini said Rushdie should be killed
because ``The Satanic Verses,'' blasphemed Islam.
   Khomeini died June 3, but his order has not been revoked.
   Before the separation, Ms. Wiggins was quoted as saying they had
moved 56 times, through a succession of ``safe houses'' used for
spies and intelligence contacts.
   They had dined occasionally with friends, literary acquaintances
and political figures, such as Neil Kinnock, leader of the
opposition Labor Party. Such meetings dwindled since March at the
insistence of Rushdie's guards, friends say.
   In an interview published in June in Options, a British women's
magazine, Ms. Wiggins, 41, was quoted as saying she had been
``living the life of a paranoid schizophrenic'' in hiding.
   ``Suddenly, I have been removed from the world and made into this
person alienated in the extreme.''
   The threat forced her to cancel a promotional tour in the United
States for her novel ``John Dollar.''
   Her biggest recent loss was social contact, she was quoted as
saying _ ``The thing about this situation is that one is completely
of good mental health and yet living the life of a paranoid
schizophrenic.'
   Ms. Wiggins grew up in Lancaster, Pa., listening to her
Scots-Irish father preach in a conservative Christian church. Her
mother was Greek and on her 10th birthday, she was baptized in the
Greek Orthodox Church.
   Like her husband, who was raised as a Moslem, she fell away from
her childhood faith.
   Scotland Yard said it never confirmed that Rushdie and Ms.
Wiggins were under guard and it had nothing to say about the impact
of the couple's separation.
   ``We don't discuss security matters,'' a spokeswoman for Scotland
Yard said, speaking under condition of anonymity.
</TEXT>
