<FIRST>r w AM-Filberts     08-25 0124</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Filberts,120</SECOND>
<HEAD>Severe Cold Harms Projected Hazelnut Harvest</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year's filbert harvest in Oregon and
Washington is estimated at 13,500 tons, down 18 percent from 1988
and the smallest output since 1984, the Agriculture Department said
Friday.
   The Oregon crop of filberts, or hazelnuts, was forecast at 13,300
tons, compared with 16,300 tons in 1988. The Washington harvest was
indicated at 200 tons, the same as last year.
   Officials said filbert trees, particularly of the Barcelona
variety, were hurt by severe cold in early February during their
crucial pollination stage.
   ``As a result, nut set is lighter than in 1988,'' the report
said. ``Also, growers report a larger-than-normal number of blanks.
Nut size, however, is up significantly from last year.''
</TEXT>
