<FIRST>u a AM-School-Prostitute 1stLd-Writethru a0656 08-25 0853</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-School-Prostitute, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0656,790</SECOND>
<HEAD>School Principal Won't Be Allowed Back After Call-Boy Story</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Congressman-Prostitute Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: INSERTS 2 grafs after 16th graf pvs, bgng: ``I just,'' to UPDATE
with prostitute saying no kids were involved and he wants to sell his story.
Picks up 17th graf, ``People living''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHEVY CHASE, Md. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elementary school principal who
admitted he let a male prostitute use offices in the building has
been suspended and will not be allowed to return to work there, the
president of the school board said Friday.
   And in the narrow neighborhood streets that surround Chevy Chase
Elementary School in this upscale suburb of Washington, D.C., few
people were aware of what went on for several months since Gabriel
Massaro became principal two years ago.
   Massaro, who was suspended with pay from his job after school
officials read an article about his activities in The Washington
Times on Friday, admitted in an interview with the newspaper he had
a four-year relationship with a call-boy and gave him access to
facilities at the school.
   The prostitute, who the newspaper said used the alias of Greg
Davis, was identified Friday by Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass., as Steve
Gobie. Frank said he had a two-year relationship with the
prostitute, beginning in 1985.
   Massaro was not at home and was not at the school on Friday.
   ``Right now he is suspended and there will be an acting principal
in the school on Monday,'' said James Cronin, president of the
Montgomery County School Board. ``So far as the children are
concerned, his presence won't be a factor.
   ``What will happen in the future, I don't know,'' Cronin added.
``But I think it will be safe to say he will not return to Chevy
Chase Elementary.''
   Debra Wood, co-chair of the Chevy Chase Elementary School PTA,
said ``I really don't have any comment. The matter is under
investigation. It's unfortunate ... kind of takes you by surprise.
And it's too bad.''
   The prostitute told the Times he had used a guidance counselor's
office at the school, usually in the evenings, where he used the
telephone to set up appointments with his customers. He said he did
not have contact with any of the children in the school, which has
students in grades three through six.
   Massaro said he did not know the man was engaged in arranging
prostitution services from the building.
   ``I knew he was an escort, but I didn't know he was running an
escort service,'' he told the Times. ``I couldn't condone it from
going out of here (the school) ... He may have done that, but I did
not know that.''
   The prostitute told the newspaper that the principal ``was very
aware of what I was doing and what was going on.''
   He also said that on at least one occasion he performed a
homosexual act with a client in the guidance counselor's office. The
prostitute said Massaro did not know ``that I had met a client at
the school.''
   ``There were some afternoons where he just had nowhere to go, so
I would just let him come here to the school and just use the
bathroom and stuff like that,'' Massaro told the Times.
   The principal said he ended his relationship with the call-boy
after the call-boy had misused his credit card.
   ``I just used very poor judgment. What can I tell you,'' Massaro
told the Times. ``It was just stupid. I never thought it through. I
just thought I was helping somebody.''
   In an interview with a Washington television station, WUSA, Gobie
said ``categorically'' that no children were ever involved in any of
his activities at the school.
   He admitted he has been convicted on felony sex and drug charges
in Virginia, and said he went public on the relationship with
Massaro and Frank because he wants to sell his story to the
entertainment industry.
   People living around the school and Massaro's neighbors in
Rockville, another nearby Maryland community, said nothing at the
school or in the principal's behavior offered a clue as to what had
been going on.
   None of them wanted to be quoted by name.
   A woman who lives near Massaro said her family and his are close
friends, especially after she and Massaro both had sons die in their
late teens or early twenties.
   She said Massaro and his wife had been nearly daily visitors to
comfort the neighbor in the weeks since her son died.
   ``He's friendly, he's outgoing,'' she said.
   Across the street a man said ``He's one of the nicest people I
ever met.'' The man said he was ``flabbergasted.''
   Back near the school and a few doors down the street, a young
mother said her family had just moved into the neighborhood and her
kids were to start attending the school this fall.
   She sent her kids out into the yard to blow bubbles, while she
stood inside the door and read the story in the newspaper provided
by a reporter.
   Then she rolled her eyes and said ``It's just our luck.''
</TEXT>
