<FIRST>u i AM-France-USMovies     08-25 0308</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-France-US Movies,0316</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mayor Says Americans Must Stop Making Movies in Paris</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Americans can't make any more movies in Paris until
French director Elie Chouraqui is allowed to shoot his film in
Chicago and Kansas, Mayor Jacques Chirac said Friday.
   Chirac's order threatened ``Mr. and Mrs. Bridge,'' starring Paul
Newman and his wife Joanne Woodward and directed by James Ivory,
which began six planned days of shooting Friday.
   Chirac said he would ``suspend all authorizations for American
films currently shooting in Paris'' until Chouraqui and his crew
were given visas to start work on his film ``Miss Missouri.''
   Culture Minister Jack Lang said he found the U.S. treatment of
Chouraqui ``humiliating and unacceptable,'' but did not support
blocking U.S. films being made in France because of assurances from
American movie industry officials that the situation would be
cleared up immediately.
   Both Chirac and Lang said in their statements they had been
trying to get action from U.S. officials since Monday, when
Chouraqui had planned to begin work, but there apparently was
opposition from the Directors Guild of America.
   Lang's office issued the text of a message it said he received
from Jack Valenti, president of the Motion Picture Association of
America, saying Chouraqui would have his visa ``this weekend or
Monday at the latest.''
   The message said officials of the directors' guild had agreed to
end their opposition to a visa for Chouraqui and immigration
officials had promised quick action.
   A spokesman for the Ivory production said privately: ``The
situation has been resolved. Once people who knew what they were
doing got involved the whole thing was cleared up. We're totally
behind France and France is totally behind us.''
   Chouraqui is known in France for such films as ``Paroles et
Musique'' (Words and Music) and ``Qu'est-ce Qui Fait Courir David?''
(What Makes David Run?).
</TEXT>
