<HEAD>Dole Pledges To Seek More U.S. Aid for to Rebuild Armenia</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: SUBS 2nd graf to show that Dole made pledge while in Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate Republican Leader Bob Dole said Friday
he will seek increased American aid for reconstruction in
earthquake-damaged Soviet Armenia.
   According to a statement released by his Washington office, Dole,
R-Kan., made the pledge in Poland after he and his wife, Labor
Secretary Elizabeth Dole, toured the damaged areas in Armenia and
delivered $50,000 worth of relief supplies. The supplies were
gathered by Project Hope, a private U.S. relief agency.
   The U.S. government has provided $4 million worth of assistance,
most of it in transportation, since the Dec. 7, 1988, earthquake
that killed 25,000 people. Americans have given another $160 million
privately, Dole said.
   ``If anybody wants to look at a place where they could use help _
whether they're children, whether they're schools, whether they're
homes _ here's a little country of 3.3 million people with 700,000
homeless,'' he said.
   Dole said he will deliver to President Bush a letter from U.S.
relief organizations outlining their needs in Armenia.
