<FIRST>u i AM-FrenchGuiana     08-25 0333</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-French Guiana,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Strike To Protest Crime Wave Shuts Down French Guiana</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAYENNE, French Guiana (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Businesses, public transport and
government offices were shut down Friday in a 24-hour strike to
protest a crime wave attributed to immigrants from neighboring South
American nations.
   The strike, called by the Chamber of Commerce and backed by
businesses and trade unions, paralyzed Cayenne, the capital; Kourou,
site of the European space station, and St. Laurent, on the western
border with Suriname.
   The Chamber of Commerce closed Rochambeau International Airport,
which it manages, but police occupied it Friday and forced it to
open.
   Chamber of Commerce President Pierre Prevot said the strike was
called to protest ``a surge in burglaries, crimes of all sort,
usually committed with violence, and street attacks in broad
daylight.''
   Police blamed most of the crime on foreign immigrants, especially
from neighboring Guyana and Suriname.
   In recent weeks a Cayenne accountant for a forestry company was
killed and robbed of $47,000 in workers' salaries he was carrying,
jewelry boutiques and food stores in the three main towns were
robbed, and burglars broke into dozens of private homes.
   French Guiana is a French overseas department, or state, on the
northeast shoulder of South America.
   About 40 percent of its 100,000 residents are foreigners, mostly
Haitian, Surinamese, Brazilians or Guyanese.
   Prevot said residents demanding the government give ``more
material for police and gendarmes to help them better control
foreign workers.''
   He said in a statement that if authorities fail to act,
``citizens will create militias to patrol towns and protect
ourselves.''
   Immigrants and illegal aliens have flocked here in recent years
to work in the lumber industry and raising shrimp, or, in the case
of an estimated 10,000 Surinamese, to escape army repression.
   The only prison in Cayenne, a town of 45,000, is filled with
inmates, mostly from Guyana and Suriname.
   ``We propose to help finance the construction of a new prison in
Cayenne, because the only existing one is overcrowded,'' Prevot said.
</TEXT>
