<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1811EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Cambodia     08-25 0449</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cambodia,0461</SECOND>
<HEAD>New Cambodia Proposal Being Prepared; Conference Threatened</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ELAINE GANLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PARIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several nations were drawing up a new power-sharing
proposal Friday in hopes of breaking a deadlock at the international
conference on Cambodia, but there was no sign of agreement among
Cambodian factions.
   Secretary of State James Baker will not participate in next
week's three-day closing session, the State Department said, and it
was not clear how many other foreign ministers from the 19 countries
attending would be there.
   State Department spokesman Richard Boucher said in Washington
that ``a comprehensive settlement is not in sight'' after a month of
meetings because Vietnam and the Cambodian government it sponsors
had not shown flexibility.
   ``The gap on major issues remains rather substantial,'' a Western
delegate said privately. ``It does not appear likely the conference
will achieve its objectives.''
   It was called to lay the groundwork for a comprehensive
settlement of the civil war in Cambodia, which began when Vietnam
invaded in December 1978 and ousted Pol Pot's genocidal Khmer Rouge
government. Vietnam says all its forces will be withdrawn next month.
   The Khmer Rouge is the strongest faction in the guerrilla
alliance led by Prince Norodom Sihanouk, the former ruler of
Cambodia, and he insists on a role for it. China supports the Khmer
Rouge.
   When he arrived in Paris on Friday, Hun Sen said: ``There will be
no comprehensive settlement without the elimination of the Khmer
Rouge.'' He said the government in Phnom Penh ``cannot sacrifice the
vital interests of the Cambodian people to satisfy other countries.''
   Sihanouk had proposed that a government of the three rebel
factions and Hun Sen run the country until general elections. He has
refused any power-sharing arrangement between himself and Hun Sen to
the exclusion of the others, and rejected a French compromise this
week.
   A source in the Association of Southeast Asian Nations said the
six member nations consulted with other delegations Friday on the
outline of a new compromise. He would not elaborate, but said it
represented ``one last good-faith effort.''
   The ASEAN members are Brunei, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore and Thailand.
   In its first concrete action, the conference sent a U.N.
fact-finding mission to Cambodia to gather information for the
dispatch of a force to monitor the Vietnamese withdrawal and oversee
an eventual cease-fire.
   Hun Sen's government objects to a role for the United Nations as
long as it continues to recognize Sihanouk's coalition as the
Cambodian representative.
   On Wednesday, the U.N. mission gave the conference a six-page
report recommending self-sufficiency for a monitoring force.
   ``They don't try to give the impression it would be an easy
operation,'' a Western delegate said.

</TEXT>
