<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1828EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-Namibia     08-25 0457</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Namibia,0472</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report Namibian Guerrillas Detained Leaders' Wife</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Namibian guerrilla officials
were so worried about infiltration by spies that they once detained
the wife of their leader, a newspaper sympathetic to their cause
reported Friday.
   The Weekly Mail, a respected anti-apartheid newspaper based in
Johannesburg, said in a front-page story that Kowambo Nujoma, wife
of the guerrilla movement's president Sam Nujoma, was detained in
1986 for an unspecified period on suspicion of being a South African
spy.
   It said she now is free and is believed to have been reconciled
with her husband's South-West Africa People's Organization.
   The movement waged a 23-year bush war against South African rule
of Namibia before agreeing to a truce as part of the ongoing
U.N.-sponsored transition to independence.
   It is expected to win November independence elections but has
come under mounting criticism for its treatment of dissidents and
suspected spies during the war.
   Asked about The Weekly Mail report, guerrilla official Nahas
Angula said in Windhoek, Namibia, that he could not comment without
checking with the movement's headquarters in Luanda, Angola. Jesaya
Nyamu, a guerrilla spokesman in Luanda, declined to comment.
   Angula said he believed Mrs. Nujoma is in Luanda.
   Theo-Ben Gurirab, the movement's foreign affairs secretary,
confirmed at a news conference Wednesday that the guerrillas had
tortured some political prisoners.
   He also invited officials of international human rights
organizations to inspect camps in Angola to verify the guerrillas'
claim that all their prisoners have been freed. In the past, the
movement refused to allow inspections.
   On Thursday, officials of the U.N. monitoring force in Namibia
said they may inspect the camps.
   The Weekly Mail, quoting freed dissidents who have returned to
Namibia, said there had been an atmosphere of ``absurd paranoia and
spy obsession'' within the movement.
   ``Persistent, detailed claims of torture and atrocities made by
237 former detainees ... have led even longstanding allies of the
organization to rebuke SWAPO and demand a full inquiry into the
treatment of suspected spies,'' said the newspaper.
   The ``wave of terror,'' it said, resulted partly from resentment
by poorly educated security officials against members of the
movement who had received university education abroad.
   The Weekly Mail quoted a former detainee as saying Mrs. Nujoma's
sister, Hilma Mushimba, had been forced to say during interrogation
in 1986 that her sister was a South African agent. The newspaper
said Mrs. Nujoma subsequently was detained, but it was not known for
how long.
   South African government officials frequently say the newspaper
is biased in favor of black opposition groups. Since its founding in
1985, the newspaper has carried numerous reports from Namibia
critical of South African policies in the territory and conveying
the positions of the territory's guerrilla movement.
</TEXT>
