<FIRST>u a AM-DEAAgent     08-25 0290</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-DEA Agent,0298</SECOND>
<HEAD>DEA Agent, Brother Plead Innocent to Drug Trafficking Charges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal drug agent and his brother pleaded
innocent to cocaine trafficking charges Friday, and a U.S.
magistrate said she would decide Monday whether either man should be
freed on bail.
   Prosecutor Thomas Burrows asked U.S. Magistrate Patti Saris to
hold Edward O'Brien and his brother John without bail.
   Defense lawyers recommended that Edward O'Brien be released with
an electronic bracelet that would let authorities check his
whereabouts and that John O'Brien be freed on bail.
   ``I do believe there is a serious risk of flight,'' Saris said,
but added that she was intrigued by the bracelet idea.
   Edward O'Brien, who formerly ran the DEA office in Springfield,
and John O'Brien were each indicted Thursday on five counts of
cocaine trafficking. Edward O'Brien, 44, has been placed on
administrative leave pending the outcome of his case.
   O'Brien, a former expert in government ``sting'' operations, was
arrested by undercover officers Aug. 14 at Boston's Logan
International Airport while allegedly delivering suitcases filled
with 62 pounds of cocaine.
   The 18-year DEA veteran said in an alleged confession presented
Thursday in court that he was paid to ferry drugs from Florida to
Boston.
   On Friday, the defense accused the government of creating the
case against the O'Briens.
   ``It's the government that decided how much drugs to give him.
It's a government-manufactured case. They attempted to present a
case where they can ask for him not to be released under any
conditions,'' said Susan L. Crockin, an attorney for Edward O'Brien.
   Richard Cohen, John O'Brien's attorney, said his client is a
family man and a businessman with $100,000 in equity put up by his
brother and his girlfriend.
</TEXT>
