<FIRST>r i AM-Lebanon-Palestinians     08-25 0227</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Lebanon-Palestinians,0234</SECOND>
<HEAD>Abu Nidal Group Says It Will Avenge Killing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Palestinian terrorist group said in a
statement published Friday it will kill 15 spies to avenge the
assassination of one of its senior leaders.
   The statement from the Fatah-Revolutionary Council of master
terrorist Abu Nidal did not divulge the names or nationalities of
the alleged spies or set a deadline for their killing.
   ``The movement will execute the death sentence against 15 spies
belonging to several groups involved in this crime,'' said the
statement published by several Beirut newspapers.
   The statement identified the dead man as Abdul-Rahim Riyahi. He
was shot Wednesday at the entrance to the southern port city of
Sidon.
   Police said Riyahi was driving from Beirut with his bodyguards
when gunmen in a black Mercedes raked his car with machine-gun fire.
One bodyguard, Hisham Saeed, 28, was seriously wounded.
   No group claimed responsibility for the assassination.
   Abu Nidal long has been at odds with Palestine Liberation
Organization chief Yasser Arafat, who has re-established a major
power base in Sidon's refugee camps of Ein el-Hilweh and Mieh Mieh.
The Fatah-Revolutionary Council also has strongholds in the two
camps.
   Abu Nidal, whose real name is Sabri al-Banna, is wanted by the
U.S. and West European government for scores of terrorist attacks,
including the 1985 attacks at Rome and Vienna airports.
