<FIRST>r a AM-Knight-Ridder-Chapman     08-25 0445</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Knight-Ridder-Chapman,0458</SECOND>
<HEAD>Chapman Steps Down as K-R Chairman; Batten Succeeds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Knight-Ridder Inc. announced Friday that Alvah
Chapman will step down as chairman of the board effective Oct. 1,
and will be replaced by Chief Executive Officer James K. Batten.
   Chapman, 68, who has headed the board since 1982, will continue
as chairman of the company's executive committee and a member of the
board, and will also serve as a consultant.
   ``I have honored my commitment to the board and CEO Jim Batten
when I delayed my retirement at their request almost 18 months
beyond our mandatory retirement age,'' Chapman said.
   Batten, 53, who also is a board member of The Associated Press,
will continue as chief executive officer when he assumes the
chairmanship, the company said.
   Batten, a native of Suffolk, Va., began his career as editor of
the newspaper at Davidson College. He was a reporter for The
Charlotte Observer in North Carolina, then worked in Knight-Ridder's
Washington bureau.
   Starting in 1970, he served in editorial positions at the Detroit
Free Press and The Charlotte Observer and moved to vice
president-news for Knight-Ridder in 1975.
   P. Anthony Ridder, 48, will succeed Batten as president and
continue as president of Knight-Ridder's newspaper division.
   ``I will do all in my power to make sure Knight-Ridder is forever
synonymous with the best in newspaper publishing and business and
professional information,'' Ridder said.
   The company announced last month that Richard G. Capen Jr.,
publisher of The Miami Herald, will become vice chairman of
Knight-Ridder on Sept. 1. The company previously announced that
David Lawrence Jr., who has been publisher at the Detroit Free
Press, would become Herald publisher.
   Chapman served as Knight-Ridder's chief executive officer from
1976 until 1988, when Batten assumed the position. He graduated from
The Citadel in 1942 with a bachelor of science degree in business
administration, and served in World War II as a bomber pilot.
   He joined the staff of the Columbus (Ga.) Ledger-Enquirer after
the war, later becoming executive vice president and general manager
of the St. Petersburg Times in 1953.
   He became part owner, president and publisher of the Savannah
(Ga.) Morning News and Evening Press in 1957. He joined the Knight
organization in 1960, moving up to vice president and general
manager of the Herald, becoming president in 1969.
   He was named president of Knight Newspapers in 1973, and was the
first president of Knight-Ridder Newspapers Inc. at the time of the
merger in 1974. Knight-Ridder currently owns 29 daily newspapers,
and is completing the sale of its eight broadcast stations. The
company also has investments in cable television and in business
information services, including Dialog.
</TEXT>
