<FIRST>u i AM-Chile-BurnVictims     08-25 0258</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Chile-Burn Victims,0266</SECOND>
<HEAD>Army Captain Sentenced In Burning Of Dissidents</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A military judge sentenced army Capt.
Pedro Fernandez to 300 days in prison for the burning of two young
dissidents _ one fatally _ during an anti-government protest, but
Fernandez will not go to jail.
   In handing down the sentence Thursday night, the judge, army Gen.
Carlos Parera, said Fernandez could show up in court every week for
one year and sign a control book instead of actually being
incarcerated.
   The procedure, called remission of sentence, is frequent in
Chilean courts.
   The victims' lawyers said they will appeal the sentence.
   Fernandez commanded an army patrol quelling widespread street
protests against the military government on July 2, 1986, when
Rodrigo Rojas, 18, a Chilean photographer living in Washington,
D.C., and Carmen Gloria Quintana, a 19-year-old university student,
were severely burned.
   Rojas died four days later. Ms. Quintana survived after lengthy
treatment in Chile and in Canada.
   Ms. Quintana and at least two witnesses charged that soldiers
doused Rojas and her with gasoline and then set them on fire.
   Fernandez said the two were burned accidentally when a pot of
gasoline they were carrying ignited. He said they intended to set
street barricades on fire.
   Parera basically accepted Fernandez's account, but ruled he was
negligent in abandoning the two teen-agers instead of taking them to
a hospital.
   Luis Toro and Hector Salazar, the lawyers for the victims, said
Fernandez was guilty of the more serious crime of ``unnecessary
violence resulting in death and serious injury.''
</TEXT>
