<FIRST>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     08-25 0398</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0409</SECOND>
<HEAD>Temperatures Drop in Northeast; Heat Wave in South</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Summer vacationers donned overcoats in the Northeast and snow
fell in Montana on Friday, while the deep South experienced
uncomfortable summer heat.
   Fall weather made an early appearance as temperatures fell to as
low as 29 degrees at East Haven, Vt. Warm coats were needed atop of
Mount Washington, N.H., where temperatures were around 30 degrees
and winds gusted over 60 mph.
   Scattered frost is expected Saturday morning in the colder
valleys of northern New England and northeastern New York state.
   Cold weather also the rule across the northern and central
Rockies, with temperatures in the 50s and 60s.
   Heavy rain since Wednesday has caused flooding in parts of
northwest Montana, where more than 2{ inches rain fell from noon
Thursday to noon Friday at Great Falls.
   Heavy snow covered some mountain ranges in Montana. The Beartooth
Highway southwest of Red Lodge was covered with 1 to 2 inches of
snow Friday morning.
   Elsewhere, showers and thunderstorms were scattered from eastern
portions of the northern and central Plains across Arkansas and the
Gulf Coast to the southern Atlantic Coast.
   Widespread thunderstorms drenched northern Florida. A
thunderstorm doused Daytona Beach with almost an inch of rain in a
half-hour.
   A warm front extended from southern Missouri across northern
Kentucky to the Carolinas, separating cloudy and cool weather in the
North from hot weather in the South.
   Temperatures as high as the mid-90s and high humidity made things
uncomfortable from south-central Texas across the lower Mississippi
Valley to Georgia.
   The low temperature in the lower 48 states Thursday morning was
28 degrees at Gunnison, Colo. At 3 p.m. EDT, the low was 47 degrees
at Yellowstone Park in Wyoming and the high 100 degrees at
Montgomery, Ala.
   Saturday's national forecast called for showers and thunderstorms
over the upper half of the Mississippi Valley, the lower Ohio and
Tennessee valleys and Florida; and widely scattered thunderstorms
over the northern Rockies, much of the Plains and the central Gulf
Coast.
   Highs were expected to be in the 60s in northern Maine, western
Montana and along parts of the Pacific Coast; in the 90s in the
southern Atlantic Coast, the Gulf Coast, the lower Mississippi
Valley, the southern Plains and interior valleys of California; near
100 in the desert Southwest; and in the 70s and 80s elsewhere.
