<FIRST>u i AM-Canada-ToxicWaste     08-25 0344</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Canada-Toxic Waste,0353</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Charges 13 People with Contempt in Toxic Waste Scandal</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   BAIE-COMEAU, Canada (AP) _ Thirteen people, including the captain
of a Soviet freighter, were charged with contempt of court Friday
for the dumping of 15 containers of toxic waste barred by a court
injunction.
   The cargo remained on the government wharf of this St. Lawrence
seaport Friday, blocking shipments and an adjacent ferry. It was
unloaded there before dawn Thursday by the Soviet freighter Nadezhda
Obukhova, which then steamed out of the harbor.
   Judge Paul Corriveau of Quebec Superior Court charged four
officials from Dynamis Envirotech, the Montreal company hired to
dispose of the waste; a vice-president of the public utility
Hydro-Quebec, which was to store the waste; six truck drivers hired
to move it to a storage depot; a man, apparently Canadian,
identified only as Gaeten Halle; and the freighter captain, who was
not identified by name.
   They must appear before Corriveau on Sept. 28. Offenders can be
fined up to $5,000 and a year in jail.
   The cargo of polychlorinated biphenyls, or PCBs, was shipped from
Montreal to Liverpool, in Britain, where it was turned away by dock
owners and workers after protests from environmentalists.
   The Soviet freighter then returned to Canada with the cargo,
which was to be stored temporarily at a facility near Baie-Comeau
while authorities considered other ways to get rid of the poisonous
chemical, which usually is incinerated at very high heat.
   Baie-Comeau community groups won a court injunction early
Thursday forbidding the unloading of the cargo.
   Court documents say the captain was served with the injunction,
but the ship slipped its moorings and set sail without the
containers.
   The cargo is part of 1,500 tons of noxious waste that the Quebec
government contracted Dynamis Envirotech to dispose of for $7.9
million.
   Polychlorinated biphenyls were used primarily as a coolant in
electrical transformers but have been banned in North America
because of links to cancer. They cause skin diseases and are toxic
to a variety of animals, especially fish, and may affect animal
reproduction.
</TEXT>
