<FIRST>u a AM-ParkMurder     08-25 0585</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Park Murder,0602</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rapist, Freed on Bail, Charged With Murdering Bank Executive</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER VILES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A convicted rapist freed on bail while
awaiting trial in another rape case has been charged with murdering
a bank executive who apparently was kidnapped on her lunch hour and
shot in a city park.
   Daniel J. Webb, 27, was ordered held on $1.6 million bond Friday
in the death of Diane Gellenbeck, 37, of Newington, a vice president
at Connecticut National Bank.
   Ms. Gellenbeck was last seen alive when she left for her lunch
break Thursday. At about 1 p.m., police checking reports of gunshots
found her bullet-riddled body, fully clothed except for shoes, near
the golf course in Keney Park. Police were awaiting test results to
see if she had been raped.
   A spokesman for the bank said Ms. Gellenbeck was single and had
worked for the bank for 16 years.
   Webb turned himself in at Hartford police headquarters about four
hours later, after police surrounded his Bloomfield home.
   The attack in the park was similar to the 1984 kidnap and rape
that landed Webb in prison. He was convicted of abducting a woman
from the Hartford Civic Center parking garage, taking her to Keney
Park and raping her.
   Police have not confirmed that Ms. Gellenbeck was kidnapped
Thursday, but two legal sources said she was kidnapped at the Civic
Center garage before she was taken to the park.
   ``Based on her (appointments) calendar, there was no reason for
her to be in the park at that time,'' said Hartford police Lt.
Frederick Lewis. The large public park is about two miles from
Gellenbeck's downtown office.
   Asked if Webb was known to Hartford police, Lewis sighed and
said, ``notoriously.''
   Hartford State's Attorney John Bailey said Webb has been arrested
several times since his release from prison, believed to be in 1986,
each time on charges of sexual assault or robbery. But prosecutors
have been unable to keep him behind bars as he awaits trial.
   After being freed from prison and put on probation for his 1984
conviction, Webb was arrested and jailed again in June 1988 on
charges he forced a woman's car off of a highway in New Britain,
then kidnapped her and raped her. But in June of this year, Webb,
still awaiting trial, was released when he put up his father's
storefront church as a $200,000 property bond.
   Webb was arrested again July 29 on charges of robbery and larceny
in East Hartford, but again he made bond. Prosecutors went to court
as recently as Monday seeking to have the bond increased, but a
judge put off a ruling because Webb's lawyer was out of town.
   ``This has been a very frustrating case for the state,'' Bailey
said. ``We have done everything we could under the current law to
keep him incarcerated.''
   Bailey complained that state laws prevent pretrial detention for
suspects believed to be dangerous, and prevent judges from
considering how dangerous an accused criminal is when they set bond.
   Bond is set based on whether a judge believes the accused will
show up for trial, and no one is held without bond, Bailey said.
   ``We've been arguing for five years for preventive detention _ no
bail _ if the guy is dangerous,'' Bailey said.
   Superior Court Judge Andre Kocay set Webb's current bond so high,
Bailey said, because the number of charges against him increased the
likelihood that he would not show up for trial.
</TEXT>
