<SECOND>AM-Letterman Intruder,0436</SECOND>
<HEAD>Woman Who Claims To Be Mrs. Letterman Sentenced to Prison</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NORWALK, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A woman who at one time claimed to be David
Letterman's wife was sent to prison Friday after police said she
trespassed at the talk show host's Connecticut home for the fifth
time in the past year.
   Margaret Ray, 37, was arrested Thursday after being caught by the
talk show host at his home in New Canaan.
   Superior Court Judge Harold Dean ruled that Ray had violated
terms of her probation by reappearing at the home outside New York
City. He ordered her to spend nine months at Niantic Women's Prison
in eastern Connecticut.
   Letterman declined to press charges after notifying police
Thursday he had seen Ray walking on the grounds of his home, said
Assistant State's Attorney Robert Hall. But prosecutors pressed the
case, noting her appearance violated the terms of her probation,
Hall said.
   Ray of Paonia, Colo., was on probation for earlier break-ins to
Letterman's home. She was arrested at the New Canaan railroad
station about 4 p.m. Thursday, said police Sgt. Frank Basso.
   Ray, who was previously arrested in May 1988 and February of this
year in connection with break-ins at the comedian's home, pleaded
guilty May 30 to using Letterman's car without his permission and to
two counts of first-degree criminal trespass. As part of a plea
bargain, other charges including burglary and larceny were dropped.
   Norwalk Superior Court Judge William F. Hickey Jr. gave her a
one-year suspended sentence and three years probation, ordering her
to stay away from Letterman and continue to undergo psychiatric
treatment.
   In an interview with The Associated Press in April, Ray described
Letterman as ``the dominant figure in my life,'' and apologized for
breaking into his home.
   In May 1988, Ray was arrested when she tried to pass herself off
as Letterman's wife after she was stopped at the Lincoln Tunnel
between New Jersey and New York City driving Letterman's sports car.
Police said she told a toll collector she was married to Letterman
and the small child with her was their son.
   Police said they later discovered that someone had broken into
the comedian's home and apparently lived there for several days
while he was out of town.
   Letterman originally declined to press charges, but Ray was then
arrested a few days later at his home. She was placed on probation
in September and underwent psychiatric treatment.
   She was arrested again twice in February in connection with
break-ins at Letterman's home Feb. 24 and Feb. 28.
