<FIRST>u i AM-Greece-Scandal     08-25 0371</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Greece-Scandal,0383</SECOND>
<HEAD>Papandreou Refuses To Testify On Bank Scandal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATHENS, Greece (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Premier Andreas Papandreou on Friday
refused to testify before a parliamentary committee looking into his
alleged involvement in a major financial scandal that led to his
fall from power.
   Instead, Papandreou sent a note questioning the committee's
legality.
   Parliament voted in July to authorize investigation of
Panpandreou and four of his former ministers in the $210 million
Bank of Crete embezzlement scandal.
   Papandreou's Panhellenic Socialist Movement lost national
elections in June amid allegations that he and former ministers
authorized the activities of the bank's owner and chairman, George
Koskotas, or took bribes from him..
   A government formed by the conservative New Democracy Party and
the Communist-led Coalition of the Left and Progress vowed a cleanup.
   Koskotas fled to the United States in November, but a Boston
magistrate ruled this week he should be extradited to Greece.
   The banker has claimed in interviews that Papandreou blackmailed
him into embezzling for the benefit of his party. Papandreou denies
it.
   In his message to the committee on Friday, Papandreou wrote: ``I
will not go into the legality of the proposal for an investigation
and the procedures of the committee, nor into the interests which
they undoubtedly serve.''
   He referred members to a memorandum he submitted last February to
an earlier commission of inquiry formed when he was premier. That
committee was disbanded prior to the elections before submitting a
report.
   Papandreou said then that he met three times with Koskotas at
Koskotas' request, but that he moved swiftly to order an
investigation into the banker's illegal activities when informed of
them.
   Papandreou and his party say the scandal has been exploited by
their political enemies.
   The committee must submit its report to Parliament by Sept. 9.
Deputies will then vote on whether Papandreou and his former
ministers will stand trial before a special court.
   Meanwhile, another parliamentary committee investigating
widespread wiretaps allegedly carried out during Papandreou's eight
years in power asked Papandreou on Friday to testify or submit a
memorandum before the month ends.
   Papandreou is also being investigated in connection with his
government's purchase of 80 U.S. and French jet fighters that the
present government claims were overpriced.
</TEXT>
