<SECOND>AM-Stroessner Son,0241</SECOND>
<HEAD>Paraguay Asks Brazil to Extradite Son of Ex-Dictator</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paraguay asked Brazil on Friday to
extradite the Gustavo Stroessner, son of deposed Paraguayan dictator
Alfredo Stroessner, to face charges of extortion and other crimes.
   Geronimo Narvaez, first secretary of the Paraguayan Embassy, told
The Associated Press his country formally petitioned Brazil to turn
over the 46-year-old former air force colonel, presumed to be living
in Brasilia, Brazil's capital.
   Gustavo flew to exile in neighboring Brazil with his father after
a coup in February ended 34 years of Gen. Stroessner's dictatorial
rule.
   The new government stripped Gustavo Stroessner of his military
rank and charged him with corruption and illicit gains. Narvaez said
the government seized $100 million of the son's holdings in April
and that charges against him include extorting money from Paraguayan
casinos.
   A Paraguyan police report said Gustavo Stroessner received at
least $725,000 a month from three Asuncion bingo houses in 1985-88.
   Foreign Ministry spokesman Ruy Nogueira said Brazil has not yet
received a formal extradition request. He said Brazil told Paraguay
on April 19 that the Justice Ministry had approved in principle
permanent political asylum for Gustavo Stroessner.
   An extradition request would have to be approved by the Foreign
Ministry, the Justice Ministry and the Supreme Court, Nogueira said.
   The son was once proposed as a possible successor to the elder
Stroessner as ruler of Paraguay.
