<FIRST>r a AM-CocaineBaby     08-25 0488</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Cocaine Baby,0506</SECOND>
<HEAD>Mother Of Cocaine Baby Sentenced</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Cocaine Mother</HEAD>
<DATELINE>FAIRBANKS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of a baby who died of a cocaine
overdose has been sentenced to six months in jail for criminally
negligent homicide.
   Geralyn Sue Grubbs, 23, who is 7{ months pregnant, also was
placed on five years probation by Superior Court Judge Jay Hodges.
   ``Life is cheap,'' said Assistant District Attorney Ken Goldman
after the sentencing Thursday.
   Grubbs originally was charged with manslaughter, which carries a
maximum penalty of 20 years. She pleaded no contest when the
district attorney's office agreed to reduce the charge.
   An autopsy found 2-week-old David died Oct. 22, 1988, from a
heart attack caused by a cocaine overdose.
   Grubbs, a former exotic dancer, was charged after state troopers
tested the infant's bottle and found traces of cocaine in it.
   A trooper said Grubbs, a confessed cocaine user, admitted to
mixing the formula and feeding the infant earlier that evening.
   ``The infant was killed as a result of substance abuse,'' Hodges
ruled.
   David was born with cocaine in his system. The Division of Family
and Youth Services would not release the baby to Grubbs until the
drug left his system and Grubbs agreed to have him tested for the
drug twice a week.
   Trooper Investigator Steve Foster said Grubbs brought David in
twice for the test, which he passed, but she missed the third
session.
   Grubbs' 18-month-old son, Jeffrey, was also tested after his
brother's death and cocaine was found in his system.
   Goldman told Hodges that urinalysis tests for cocaine given to
Grubbs from January through June 12 found traces of cocaine residue
in her system. Goldman said that meant Grubbs was using cocaine
during the first trimester of her present pregnancy.
   She must report to jail Dec. 1. She is due to deliver her next
child Oct. 1.
   Grubbs also was ordered to complete a six to 18-month drug
treatment program after her jail term.
   In announcing the sentence, Hodges said the court is obligated to
send a message to the public that ``this kind of conduct will not be
tolerated.''
   Grubbs' attorney, Paul Canarsky of the public defenders office,
said Grubbs was herself a victim _``a passive recipient of drugs''
from her former boyfriend.
   He said the man beat Grubbs, forced her to work as a topless
dancer and supplied her with cocaine. Canarsksy said since Grubbs
left the man she has been drug free and her urinalysis tests have
come back clean. Grubbs has been free on her own recognizance since
her arrest.
   Canarsky asked Hodges to assign Grubbs to a residential treatment
program instead of jail. He said Friday that Grubbs has not decided
whether to appeal.
   In Florida Friday, a judge imposed 15 years of probation on a
cocaine-addicted mother convicted of delivering drugs to two of her
children at birth. Jennifer Johnson, 23, faced a 30-year prison
sentence on the conviction.
</TEXT>
