<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 2041EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u i AM-PuertoRico-Crash     08-25 0159</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Puerto Rico-Crash,0164</SECOND>
<HEAD>West German Pilot, 3 Dutch Passengers Die In Small Plane Crash</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN JUAN, Puerto Rico (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A plane crashed in Puerto Rico's
mountainous interior Friday, killing the pilot and three Dutch
passengers, officials said.
   A spokesman for the Isla Grande Airport control tower in San Juan
identified the pilot as Michael Wenceslaus Goes, a West German
resident of Puerto Rico and employee of the German-owned Looss
Aviation, a flying school that operates the rented plane.
   The airport spokesman, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the plane was hired by three Dutch sailors on a port call.
   The U.S. Navy identified the Dutch navy ship as the Pieter
Florisz.
   The airport spokesman said the plane crashed about a half-hour
after it took off on a sightseeing trip.
   Police say the plane crashed near Barranquitas, a small mountain
town about 20 miles southwest of San Juan.
   The names of the sailors were not immediately available.
</TEXT>
