<DOCNO> AP890825-0172 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 2251EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-Walesa-Interview     08-25 0330</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Walesa-Interview,0338</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Says West Being Shy in Helping Poland</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The West, while applauding Poland's new
Solidarity government, is being reticent about helping the country
get back on its economic feet, Lech Walesa said in a television
interview.
   In an interview with Barbara Walters on ABC's ``20-20,'' Walesa
said the world _ including the United States _ would be blamed if
Poland does not get any more financial help and the fledging
Solidarity government fails to bring economic prosperity.
   The interview was scheduled for broadcast Friday evening.
   Walesa said Solidarity's vision involved a mixture of
philosophies and practices combining the best of capitalism with the
best of what Poland has now.
   ``We're not able to do it by ourselves alone, and we ask
everybody who is listening to us to loosen the loop of our debt,''
Walesa said. ``Today the West is applauding Poland, but it's
behaving like a young lady who wants to, but she is afraid at the
same time.''
   He invited joint ventures and said: ``Give us the money, we'll
implement the contract, and we'll give the money back. ... We want
cooperation. We don't want new debts.''
   Poland's failure would be the world's failure, he said.
   ``I will say that, if we fail, we can blame the world, even the
United States, that you haven't contributed with cooperation in
these conditions of civilization development, you will be to blame
for Polish failure,'' Walesa said.
   Asked if Poland wanted to emulate the United States, he said:
``Who wouldn't want to be the United States? ... But, on the other
hand, we would like to leave what is good in our country, to retain
what is good in our country, so it would be a mixture of the United
States and Poland.''
   Prime Minister Tadeusz Mazowiecki assumed office Thursday in a
historic transfer of power from the Communist Party to a
Solidarity-led coalition, the first government led by non-Communists
in the East bloc.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
