<FIRST>u i AM-Kenya-Adamson     08-25 0334</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Kenya-Adamson,0343</SECOND>
<HEAD>Three Arrested in Slaying of Conservationist</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police are interrogating three suspects in
the slaying of George Adamson, the British conservationist who
devoted his life to returning lions born in captivity to the wild,
the ruling party newspaper said.
   The Kenya Times said police arrested the three men in northern
Kora National Reserve, where Adamson and two assistants were shot
and killed Sunday by three robbers armed with automatic rifles. It
did not say when the suspects were arrested.
   Adamson's slaying was the third fatal attack in the wilds of this
East African nation since July. Publicity surrounding his death and
the slayings of an American woman and a French couple threatens to
harm Kenya's tourism industry, the country's prime foreign currency
earner.
   Officials say travel basically is safe. They blame the recent
violence partly on a massive effort to save Kenya's elephants, which
they say has driven well-armed poachers to other forms of banditry.
   The Times, owned by the governing Kenya African National Union,
said police plan to parade the suspects for possible identification
before Adamson's workers who witnessed the killings.
   Police Commissioner Philip Kilonzo was not available for comment,
and Richard Leakey, the director of wildlife management, said he had
no way to confirm or deny the report.
   Adamson, 83, earned international fame for his work with his wife
Joy to return lions to the wild. Their achievements are detailed in
the film ``Born Free'' and a sequel, ``Living Free.'' Both movies
are based on books by his wife, who was killed at northwestern
Shamba Game Reserve in 1980 by a servant she had dismissed on
suspicion of theft.
   Adamson moved into Kora National Reserve in 1971 and helped
dozens of lions learn to survive in the bush before freeing them.
   He and his wife separated in the late 1960s and had no children.
   Leakey said Adamson, who was called the Lion Man of Kenya, will
be buried with honors at Kora National Reserve next week.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
