<FIRST>r a AM-DrugAgent     08-25 0517</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Drug Agent,0532</SECOND>
<HEAD>Arrested Drug Agent Allegedly Confessed to Drug Trafficking</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SONNI EFRON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former federal drug agent charged with cocaine
trafficking allegedly confessed to the crime the night he was
arrested, according to testimony Thursday in federal court.
   But Edward O'Brien's defense attorneys portrayed him as a man
known by government investigators to be in deep financial and
emotional trouble months before they set him up and arrested him in
an undercover sting.
   O'Brien signed a statement Aug. 15 saying that on two occasions
he was paid a total of $39,000 to ferry drugs with another man from
Florida to Boston for a man who identified himself as a cocaine
dealer, according to a copy of the document presented at the hearing
before U.S. Magistrate Patti Saris.
   Arthur Carter Jr., a senior inspector with the DEA's Office of
Professional Responsibility, also testified that O'Brien admitted
under questioning that he had used a total of $147,000 in DEA money
for personal business, but later replaced the money.
   O'Brien, who formerly ran the DEA office in Springfield, and his
brother John O'Brien were each indicted Thursday on five counts of
cocaine trafficking.
   The two were being held without bail pending the outcome of the
detention hearing, which was expected to resume Friday.
   Charges against a third brother, Paul O'Brien, were dismissed
Thursday, but prosecutor Thomas N. Burrows refused to explain why.
   Attorneys for Edward O'Brien argued that the pre-trial publicity
had already made it impossible for the brothers to get a fair trial.
They asked the judge to close the bail hearing to the public.
   Saris refused, saying the most damaging information has probably
already been disclosed. That decision cleared the way for O'Brien's
alleged confession to be read allowed in court.
   In the five-page statement, O'Brien wrote in longhand that he
brought drugs to Boston twice, once by car for $25,000 and again by
airplane for $14,000. He was arrested after the second trip.
   O'Brien said he gave $8,000 from the first advance to his brother
John to repay a loan to John's girlfriend.
   In addition, O'Brien wrote, ``During the last 2{ years ... I
utilized some of the seized funds which were later replaced. The
total used, but not in one lump sum, was approximately $147,000.''
   O'Brien allegedly used the money to help bail out the family's
floundering company, Cape Cod Ice. Carter testified that Edward
O'Brien told him that John O'Brien had allegedly skimmed some
$230,000 from the business.
   Under cross examination by defense attorneys, Carter acknowledged
that he had information from three informants and a Springfield
police lieutenant as early as February or March indicating that
Edward O'Brien was emotionally unstable and possibly suicidal.
   The defense attempted to show that the DEA never approached
O'Brien about the missing money, or requested a psychological
evaluation, or offered him any kind of help. Instead, the DEA set up
a sting.
   ``You just wait for them to fall,'' concluded John O'Brien's
defense attorney, Richard Cohen.
   ``I'm not a psychiatrist,'' Carter replied. ``My job is to put
people in jail.''
</TEXT>
