<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 2324EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ABCContract     08-25 0372</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ABC Contract,0381</SECOND>
<HEAD>Technicians Union Accepts Cap Cities-ABC Contract</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER ALAN HARPER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Broadcast engineers, camera workers and
newswriters have accepted a four-year contract with Capital
Cities-ABC Inc.
   The contract goes into effect Saturday for all 2,500 members of
the National Association of Broadcast Employees and Technicians
except two people who make up a newswriters unit in Chicago. Union
officials said something would be worked out soon with the two
holdouts.
   The contract, which replaces one that expired March 31, provides
a first-year ratification bonus ranging from 6.1 percent to 7
percent. There are 3 percent raises in each of the second and third
years and a 4 percent increase in the fourth year.
   ``The contract, although lacking in many areas, is considered by
the union as the best it could obtain under the present
circumstances facing NABET and others in the broadcast industry,''
said John Krieger, a union spokesman.
   ``It was best to reach a settlement through considerable
compromise rather than through any confrontation as we did with NBC
in the 17-week strike in 1987,'' Krieger said.
   NABET represents engineers, camera workers, video tape editors,
newswriters, makeup people, publicists, couriers and traffic and
communication coordinators.
   The contract covers units at Cap Cities-ABC radio and television
network operations and radio and television stations in New York,
Los Angeles, Washington, San Francisco, Chicago and various news
bureaus.
   The pressing issue was job security for radio engineers in an era
when broadcast companies are needing their specialized, restricted
services less and less.
   Krieger said the company promised to move the endangered radio
engineers into television if necessary.
   The company said it got increased flexibility to overcome a
number of restrictive work rules, including rules that restricted
certain jobs, such as turning microphones off and on, to engineers.
   The company said the contract also gives it an enhanced ability
to acquire and originate live and taped sports, news and
entertainment programing and broader and more flexible daily
employment rights.
   ``The new contract grants the company the relief we sought since
the negotiations began six months ago, while providing the union
with certain securities it sought,'' Jeffrey Ruthizer, the Cap
Cities-ABC chief negotiator, said in a statement Friday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
