<FIRST>u a AM-Carter-Ethiopia     08-25 0271</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Carter-Ethiopia,0279</SECOND>
<HEAD>Second Ethiopian Rebel Group Accepts Carter's Mediation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A second rebel group in Ethiopia has approved
former President Jimmy Carter as an observer for peace talks, but a
Carter Center official said Friday the group would not be included
in the discussions here.
   Representatives of Ethiopia and another rebel group, the Eritrean
People's Liberation Front, plan to meet at the Carter Center in
Atlanta beginning Sept. 7 with Carter acting as an observer.
   Earlier this week, the Tigre People's Liberation Front announced
in a clandestine radio broadcast that it was accepting Carter,
calling on the Ethiopian government to ``respond quickly'' to the
proposal.
   Dayle E. Powell, a Carter Center fellow who heads the
presidential library's conflict resolution programs, said the
Tigrean announcement was welcome news, but that their conflict with
the Ethiopian government is unrelated to that of the Eritreans.
   As a result, Ms. Powell said, talks between the Ethiopian
government and the Tigreans could not be included in the September
meeting. She added that Carter would get involved in the Tigrean
issue only if Ethiopia also agreed.
   The Tigrean rebels, based in Tigray province, took up arms 14
years ago to press for increased autonomy for their region.
   Early this year, they scored several major victories and forced
troops out of five towns, including the provincial capital of
Mekele, 470 miles northwest of Addis Ababa.
   The Eritreans, in Ethiopia's northernmost Eritrea province, have
been fighting for independence since 1961.
   Both rebel groups agreed to peace talks after President Mengistu
Haile Mariam's announcement in June that the government had no
preconditions and welcomed an independent observer.
</TEXT>
