<FIRST>r a AM-BRF--CarnegieAcoustics     08-25 0124</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-BRF--Carnegie Acoustics,0126</SECOND>
<HEAD>Carnegie Hall Adjusting Acoustics</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Carnegie Hall officials said Friday they are
continuing to adjust the hall's acoustics to restore the sonic glory
of the great hall that some critics said was lost in a 1986 interior
renovation.
   Officials hope to have the work done in time for the 1989-90
music season, said Executive Director Judith Arron.
   To introduce acoustical absorption within the mid- and
high-frequency ranges, workers are spraying a cellulose acoustical
material on the stage ceiling, and putting panels of 100 percent
wool felt on the stage's back wall.
   Second, sound-diffusing panels will be placed across the entire
rear wall to control the reflection of sound from the wall back to
the stage, Arron said.
</TEXT>
