<FIRST>u a AM-OperationIncubator     08-25 0401</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Operation Incubator,0412</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Former Clerk of Cook County Circuit Court Gets 10 Years ^By CLIFF
EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The former clerk of Cook County Circuit Court, the
nation's largest court system, was sentenced Friday to 10 years in
prison for corruption uncovered during the federal ``Operation
Incubator'' probe.
   Morgan Finley, 63, stood silently with his arms folded across his
chest as U.S. District Judge Ilana Rovner sentenced him for taking
bribes, threatening a witness and attempted extortion.
   Finley pleaded for leniency before the sentencing. ``I am sorry
that I involved myself in this mess, not only for myself, but mostly
for my wife and family,'' he said.
   Ms. Rovner ordered him to turn himself in to authorities on Oct.
23, pay $50,000 in fines and $25,000 in restitution for bribes he
took.
   ``You and you alone took yourself from the pinnacle of power ...
to stand here in a place you should only have visited in your
official capacity,'' she said.
   ``It is obvious that your representation of all that occurred can
only be characterized at best as skewed, and at worst as lies.''
   The judge also said evidence that Finley had threatened an FBI
agent twice during the trial weighed heavily in the sentencing
decision.
   Ms. Rovner and Assistant U.S. Attorney Ira Raphaelson said
videotapes showing Finley taking $7,500 in cash were the most
convincing evidence of his guilt.
   ``Morgan Finley sold the office of the clerk of the Circuit Court
of Cook County in no uncertain terms,'' Raphaelson said. ``Those
tapes show what Morgan Finley is about.''
   Finley's attorney, Louis Garippo, maintained his client was
enticed into taking the bribe. ``The money was there. It was shoved
at him and he took the money,'' Garippo said. ``He is a good man who
was drawn into something.''
   The videotape, viewed during the trial, showed FBI mole Michael
Raymond and former court investigator Michael Lambesis in Raymond's
apartment having lunch with Finley on Dec. 4, 1985.
   Raymond reaches beneath a kitchen apron to pull out a wad of
money, and a hand identified as Finley's extends into the frame of
the film to accept it for help in obtaining a lucrative city
contract.
   Operation Incubator targeted municipal corruption at Chicago's
City Hall. All 16 people indicted as a result of the 18-month
undercover federal investigation first disclosed in December 1985
have been convicted or pleaded guilty.
</TEXT>
