<FIRST>r a AM-RacialAttack 1stLd-Writethru a0690 08-25 0477</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Racial Attack, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0690,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Ward Says Slayers Mistook Blacks for Friends of White Girl</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 2nd, `Police Commissioner ..., to UPDATE
with comment from slain boy's father; picks up 3rd graf pvs, `The gang...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gang of white teen-agers, out to block
interracial dating in their neighborhood, shot and killed a black
youth who happened along with three friends hoping to buy a used
car, officials said Thursday.
   Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward said at least 10 and as many as
30 white youths, armed with baseball bats and at least one gun,
committed the killing.
   ``My son will never turn this corner again and it's only because
of this _ the pigment of his skin,'' Freddy Stewart, father of the
slain youth, said Thursday evening. ``This is what America has to
learn _ that we no longer are going to take this. ... All we want is
justice.''
   The gang had gathered to waylay blacks or Hispanics they believed
were headed for a birthday party for an 18-year-old girl, who
recently had rejected her white boyfriend and had been dating black
and Hispanic men, Ward said.
   The spurned boyfriend had threatened the girl and made racist
comments to her, said Deputy Commissioner Alice McGillion.
   The jilted youth was part of the gang that attacked the slain
teen-ager and his friends.
   The commissioner said the identity of the shooter was not known
and the former boyfriend, known so far only by a street name, was
being sought.
   Yusef Hawkins, 16, was killed Wednesday night in Bensonhurst, a
middle-class, largely Italian and Jewish residential neighborhood of
Brooklyn.
   Three white teen-agers had been taken into custody, but no
charges had been filed Thursday, said Chief of Detectives Robert
Colangelo.
   Hawkins and his friends entered the neighborhood to answer a
newspaper ad about a car for sale.
   Ward said the whites followed the blacks for about a block and a
half and that witnesses heard them say to each other: ``Are these
the ones? Is this them?''
   What they didn't know, according to McGillion, was that the girl
had told her new boyfriend not to come and called off her birthday
party.
   McGillion said the girl, whose identity was not divulged, saw the
killing from her window.
   ``She knew there was going to be trouble. There were rumblings in
he neighborhood. Her mother had looked out the window and saw the
boys with the bats,'' she said.
   When the white gang stopped and confronted the blacks, four shots
were heard. Hawkins was hit twice in the chest. One of his
companions suffered an arm injury and the other two were not hurt.
   The gang scattered after the shots.
   Police found four .32-caliber shells and a bat at the scene, but
no gun.
</TEXT>
