<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 0033EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r a AM-ShuttleContract     08-25 0210</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Shuttle Contract,0214</SECOND>
<HEAD>Martin Marietta Lands $1.8 Billion Shuttle Fuel Tank Contract</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Martin Marietta Corp. said its New Orleans
plant won a $1.797 billion contract Thursday to produce 60 more
external tanks to fuel the nation's space shuttle through mid-1997.
   The tanks, made of aluminum, steel alloys and titanium, are
produced by Martin Marietta's Manned Space Systems Co. at NASA's
Michoud Assembly Facility near New Orleans. The plant employs about
3,500 people.
   Each of the huge external tanks, 154 feet long and 28 feet in
diameter, supplies more than 500,000 gallons of liquid hydrogen fuel
and liquid oxygen oxidizer to the orbiter during lift-off and ascent.
   The super-cold propellants are fed to the orbiter's engines at a
rate of 1,035 gallons per second, emptying the tank in about 8{
minutes. When loaded the tanks weigh 1.676 million pounds; when
empty, 66,000 pounds.
   When loaded, the tank is the largest and heaviest part of the
shuttle and its only major, non-reusable element. It is comprised of
about 481,450 components.
   The first tank to be built under the new contract is to be
completed by late 1991 and the last by mid-1997, the company said.
Under previous contracts, Martin Marietta has produced 52 of 59
external tanks.
</TEXT>
