<FIRST>r a AM-DowntownFire     08-25 0378</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Downtown Fire,0391</SECOND>
<HEAD>Blaze Guts Three Businesses; Forces Hotel Evacuation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two explosions ripped apart a grocery store
that was recently the target of an arson fire, hurling debris nearly
a block, and the ensuing blaze gutted three other businesses early
Thursday, authorities said.
   The cause of the fire in the city's Old Town district had not
been determined, but arson investigators considered the blaze
suspicious, said Don Mayer, spokesman for the Portland Fire Bureau.
   ``Somebody wants them out of here and I guess they succeeded this
morning,'' Mayer said.
   Twenty-six people were evacuated from Ma's Community Inn, a
low-income hotel on the same block, Mayer said. The residents were
allowed to return about 9 a.m.
   Hotel manager Gary Cooper said the sound of the first explosion
awakened him. He was looking out his window when the second blast
went off.
   ``I saw all this material flying across the street and a big ball
of fire behind it,'' Cooper said.
   The explosion was centered at a grocery called Savmor Grub, also
the location on July 22 of an arson fire that was started at about
the same time in the morning. That fire caused $125,000 in damage,
Mayer said.
   He said agents from the U.S. Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and
Firearms in Seattle were called to assist in the investigation.
   Pieces of the damaged building were thrown at least half a block
away. ``If someone had been walking by, they'd probably had got
blown across the street,'' Mayer said.
   The three businesses destroyed by fire were Demetri's Grocery,
Henry's Resale and the Portland Tattoo Shop, Mayer said. No damage
estimate was immediately available.
   The three-alarm fire broke out at 4:26 a.m. but was under control
by 5:11 a.m., Mayer said.
   A fire bureau investigator said the Savmor Grub building was
owned by Martha Lutz, but her residence was not known. However,
business license records showed the grocery was licensed to Empyreal
Entertainment Inc., an Oregon corporation headed by Willis W. Rees
of Beaverton.
   Rees said by telephone late Thursday that he had sold Savmor Grub
to Sang Min Lee of Portland on March 29. ``Neither Mr. Lee nor I
have any types of enemies that I know of that would do this,'' Rees
said.
</TEXT>
