<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1655EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:ClichyDays Adv30   08-25 0842</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Clichy Days, Adv 30,0862</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv30</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Wed AMs, Aug 30, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Henry Miller Gets New Life on Screen</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TERRY LEONARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ROME (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Paris' most celebrated prostitute lay in her coffin
surrounded by flowers as faded as the era, and admired by two men as
jaded as the times.
   Manouche's wake in the plush red parlor of the bordello is the
beginning, not the end, of a friendship that introduces the
soon-to-be scandalous author Henry Miller to the hedonistic
pleasures of Paris in the 1930s.
   ``As you know it is a little my fault,'' chuckles renowned French
film director Claude Chabrol, puffing on a pipe as he surveyed his
gaudy vision of a prewar French cathouse.
   ``I wanted to make a film on sex for a long time. I didn't o it
because I had other projects.''
   Chabrol fulfills his fantasy in ``Clichy Days,'' a film adapted
from the baudy autobiographical novel ``Quiet Days in Clichy'' by
the author of ``Tropic of Cancer'' and ``Tropic of Capricorn.''
   The film is being shot on location in Paris, Florence and Rome
and in a studio at Cinecitta, the Italian Hollywood on the outskirts
of Rome. It is intended for release next summer.
   ``I must say it is interesting now to make a film about sex
because I think after the liberation of sexuality in the '70s it was
very, very childish. Now it seems to be a little more puritanical
than before. So I think now is a good moment to say that you can
speak of sex without it being a dirty thing,'' Chabrol said.
   ``Another thing that is very interesting is the period, the
1930s. It is in Europe at the beginning of Hitler, ... and I must
say the intellectuals in general and the American intellectuals in
Europe at that time didn't see anything. They weren't interested in
those things at all. I would like to show the character here who
tries to find his own freedom, his own lucidity and despite that he
doesn't see what happens beside him.''
   Chabrol cast 26-year-old Andrew McCarthy in the role of Miller,
who at 42 was discovering the bohemian lifestyle of prewar Paris,
indifferent to the sorrows of the Depression at home and to the
signs of impending war in Europe.
   ``Well, Henry Miller. You don't get a chance to be Henry Miller
very often,'' said McCarthy, who became a hero of the bubble-gum set
in such critical bombs as ``St. Elmo's Fire.''
   ``He is a notorious rogue. It is a lot of fun. I think it is fun
because of Chabrol.''
   ``I think he has an amazing knowledge of the cinema,'' added
Nigel Havers, the British actor who plays Alfred, the friend who
introduces Miller to his new life in Paris. ``He shoots exactly what
he wants and he knows exactly what he wants. It is a wonderful way
of working.''
   Chabrol's way of working has changed a lot since the young critic
for Cahiers du Cinema led the New Wave of French directors with his
first film, ``Le Beau Serge,'' in 1958. He gained international fame
over the next few years with ``Les Cousins'' in 1959 and ``Les
Bonnes Femmes'' in 1960.
   He suffered a string of commercially inspired critical failures
in the early 1960s, but later regained his reputation with such
films as ``Les Biches'' and ``La Femme Infidele.''
   ``You know, I have made too many films now, even too many bad
films. Now I'm almost an old man and I just do what I like. ...
That's all.
   ``I'm not sure all my films will be good now, but I am sure I
want to do them. It was not exactly the same thing in the past.
Sometimes I accepted things,'' said the 59-year-old filmmaker.
   Miller's ``Quiet Days in Clichy,'' he said, offered him the
chance to do at once the film on sex and several other projects he
had in mind.
   ``I had read it and remembered it as very well-written but really
almost a pornographic book. But I read it (again) and found exactly
the things I wanted to make,'' he said.
   ``Two years ago I had an idea to make a film about the American
intellectuals, especially those in the '30s. I had at the same time
another idea to make a film about a young girl of about 14.''
   The little girl is Colette, played by Stephania Cotta, the
15-year-old granddaughter of Manouche who ends up living with Miller
and Alfred.
   Chabrol and co-writer Ugo Leonzio used the book as the basis, but
not a script, for their screenplay.
   ``If your read Miller's book ... it is really trashy. He always
changes reality. He changes it to garbage. And it is not ... the
truth. I don't like that so I changed the reality, too.
   ``But on the other side,'' said Chabrol, ``that is why we have
big sets and too beautiful things. They are the other side of the
lie.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv</NOTE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890825-0193 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1655EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a a AM-WetlandsWars Adv29   08-25 0823</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Wetlands Wars, Adv 29,0842</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv29</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues AMs, Aug. 29, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Wetlands War May Reach a Negotiated Settlement</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PENN, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ray Horne cursed the smooth-as-glass water in a
35-acre pothole on his farm, even though he knew it made a rich
wildlife breeding area.
   ``That depression does no good for me except it might raise a
pair of ducks,'' he said. ``As a farmer, it's no good for me.''
   Horne won't be draining this wetland, even though he has all the
permits he needs. Instead, next winter, he'll haul dirt onto the
ice-covered pond so when spring arrives, mounds will sprout to
produce ideal nesting habitat for ducks.
   Horne's change of heart comes at a price. He and some neighbors
are negotiating an agreement with the U.S. Fish and Wildlife Service
that could pay them up to $40 an acre to raise ducks.
   Their willingness to negotiate, officials say, represents a real
breakthrough in relations that could end the wetlands war, North
Dakota's most controversial environmental issue.
   ``The signal, I think, is that Wildlife is able to sit down at
the table, not demanding that every wetland be preserved, and
agriculture is saying, `We don't want to drain and are willing to
save some,''' said Lloyd Jones, state game and fish commissioner and
former director of wetlands habitat for the Fish and Wildlife
Service. ``That is something that didn't happen in the history of
North Dakota and is happening now.''
   Unlike other states, North Dakota does not have serious problems
with dirty water and air. In fact, other than draining wetlands, the
biggest environmental concern looming for the state is how to get
rid of its garbage.
   The wetlands war has pitted landowners against wildlife
interests, but the ramifications move the issue closer to urban
consumers by affecting the quality of the wildlife habitat and water
available for outdoor recreation.
   Before settlers pushed onto the prairie, North Dakota had 5
million acres of wetlands, marshy land teeming with wildlife. Just 2
million acres remain, Jones said, and he is determined to preserve
them.
   ``We are seeing a lot of things go wrong with 2 million acres and
we can't get by with anything less,'' he said.
   Wetlands act as a natural filter, concentrating fertilizer and
other runoff, then releasing more polluted water into lakes and
streams. Draining the bowl-like indentations dotting the prairie in
eastern North Dakota has disrupted the area's hydrology and removed
natural storage tanks, increasing the chances of flooding, Jones
said. It also removed natural habitat for ducks and geese.
   The drainage was spurred by farmers' desire to plant on some of
their most fertile soil. The federal government even paid them at
one time to drain their sloughs. ``There was a strong public
attitude that wetlands were wastelands,'' Jones said. Through the
1970s, farmers drained about 20,000 acres a year.
   By 1987, the Legislature passed a law requiring that each acre
drained had to be replaced, the so-called no-net-loss policy, which
took effect July 1.
   ``I am real optimistic that the future for wetlands has never
been better in North Dakota,'' Jones said. ``People are getting
along a lot better now. People trust each other a lot more now.''
   Not everyone shares that optimism.
   ``I don't know if there is a final solution,'' said Ramsey County
Commissioner Lloyd Stromme. Landowners in his area remain unhappy
with the no-net-loss law and want it repealed; they are disgusted
that the federal government obtains land without paying full taxes
on it, he sid.
   State Rep. Gordon Berg _ whose critics call him ``Mr. Draino''
for his support of wetland drainage _ says landowners must be paid
for their potholes. ``If you don't have the cooperation of the
farmer, you've got nothing.''
   Mike McEnroe of the Fish and Wildlife Service has been
negotiating with Horne and 29 other landowners for preservation of
1,500 acres of wetlands in return for payments of $15 to $40 an
acre. The exact amounts are still being discussed, but an agreement
could be signed within two months, he said.
   ``Rather than fight with people, we figured we would be much
better off working toward the middle ground,'' McEnroe said. ``We
are going kind of slow on this one because we want to find out how
much it costs. If it will work up here on a draining project of this
size, I think it can work anywhere.''
   Horne, driving around his land northwest of Devils Lake, said the
roads and trees have disrupted wetlands as much as draining
potholes. His agreement with the government will let him drain some
of the smaller sloughs in return for preserving and enhancing the
larger, more valuable ones.
   ``I'll be your local in-house manager, and we will raise birds or
whatever,'' he said. ``But I want to get paid for it.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Tues AMs, Aug. 29</NOTE>
</DOC>
