<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 0152EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>s a BC-PersonalFile-Davis Adv27   08-25 1207</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Personal File-Davis, Adv 27,1244</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv27</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Aug. 27, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Oil, Hollywood and Deli Man Davis Has More Than UAL in Mind</HEAD>
<HEAD>With LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Also on financial circuits.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By E. SCOTT RECKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $6.2 billion offer for the parent of United
Airlines is the biggest takeover yet proposed by Marvin Davis, but
the Beverly Hills billionaire, ex-wildcatter and glitzy deli owner
has other deals cooking, too.
   Even as Davis awaited UAL Corp.'s response this past week, his
close-knit group searched for other undervalued companies and
eyeballed Europe as a possible hunting ground.
   Davis' son John, a Harvard MBA whose computer research backs up
his father's business instincts, said Davis is looking abroad now
that so many U.S. companies have been bought or dissected by the
1980s takeover frenzy.
   He suggested that Sir James Goldsmith's $21 billion offer for
Britain's BAT Industries PLC may set the agenda for Davis and other
investors.
   ``Europe now is where this country was in 1980,'' said John
Davis, 34.
   His father, 63, faces probable counteroffers for UAL by United's
pilots and the team of British Airways and the Morgan Stanley &amp; Co.
investment firm.
   He declined to be interviewed. But in written responses to
questions from the Associated Press, he said the greatest threat to
the U.S. economy ``is in our failing to recognize that we are,
today, in a truly global economy.''
   ``American companies will have to be intensely competitive to
succeed in the years to come,'' Davis said. ``They will have to be
managed by the best trained and motivated people, provided with a
steady flow of capital and operate without any illusion about the
fact that we are no longer the pre-eminent force in many
industries.''
   Neither father nor son will reveal exactly where they are looking
next, though John Davis said newspapers, magazines, television
stations, and hotel-casino outfits can't be ruled out.
   At 6-foot-5 and about 300 pounds, Marvin Davis is known as a
fierce dealmaker and one of the world's wealthiest businessmen,
estimated to be worth $1.7 billion by Fortune magazine.
   He seems unlikely to lose the fascination with glamour industries
he has shown since cashing out of the oil business in the early '80s
just before the industry slumped.
   Davis was Denver's ``Mr. Wildcatter'' in the 1970s, paying huge
commissions to top geologists while convincing other oil companies
to absorb much of the risk and cost for the drilling.
   He purchased 20th Century Fox Film Corp. for $720 million, most
of it borrowed, with a partner in 1981, then bought singer Kenny
Rogers' Beverly Hills estate, ``The Knoll,'' for more than $20
million.
   Fox faltered under his leadership, partly because of flops like
``Rhinestone'' (Dolly Parton teamed with Sylvester Stallone, who
played a singing New York cab driver). But when Davis sold to Rupert
Murdoch after four years, he netted $325 million.
   Davis has unsuccessfully pursued such high-profile companies as
CBS Inc., Lorimar Telepictures Corp. and, this year, Northwest
Airlines parent NWA Inc. He teamed with Prudential Insurance Co. to
snag Spectradyne Inc., a big provider of pay-per-view movies in
hotel rooms, for $635 million.
   He paid $136 million to the family of now-convicted speculator
Ivan Boesky in December 1986 to buy the Beverly Hills Hotel, the
pink landmark where he had honeymooned with his wife, Barbara.
Within a year, he sold the hotel to the Sultan of Brunei, the
world's wealthiest person, for a $65 million profit.
   Although Davis generally avoids the press, he seems to have a
hankering for Hollywood happenings and celebrity friends.
   When he opened his Beverly Hills version of New York's Carnegie
Deli in July, George Burns, Milton Berle, John Madden and Wayne
Gretzky watched as Carol Channing plopped a monster matzo ball into
a vat of chicken soup.
   John Davis acknowledges the family won't be looking much at
industries ``unless they are fun.''
   ``We probably won't buy a chemical company,'' he said.
   At any given time, Davis' group is analyzing two or three
industries where undervalued companies may be found, John Davis said.
   He said the airline industry was targeted because it had
stabilized after the trauma of deregulation. The Davis group
especially liked United and Northwest because of their strength in
the booming Pacific Rim region.
   More often than not, Davis has profited enormously by buying
stock in a company, making a buyout offer that raises the price,
then selling his stake to a higher bidder.
   For example, he initially offered $2.7 billion to buy NWA but
eventually was outbid by investor Alfred Checchi's $3.65 billion
deal in June. Davis made $30 million.
   But John Davis insists the Davises seriously want to buy when
they bid, and bid only after rigorous analysis.
   ``We've spent too much time and effort on the airlines industry _
2{ years of work and millions and millions and millions of dollars
worth of bank fees, consultant fees, investment banking fees, legal
fees,'' he said.
   ``You know we wouldn't have spent all this money if we were just
interested in putting a company in play and making a profit.''
   Likewise, Marvin Davis counters critics who say he and other
takeover strategists are motivated by greedy speculation rather than
long-term investment goals.
   ``We are businessmen and builders,'' Davis said. ``We started
with an industrial base, building and developing a major oil and gas
exploration company. The companies we have bought _ for example
Aspen Skiing Co. and the Pebble Beach Co. _ have been expanded and
enhanced under our ownership. ...
   ``Equally important, our companies are contributing citizens of
the communities in which they operate _ from a philanthropic, social
and economic point of view,'' he said.
   Davis' own philanthropy is extensive. He established the
Children's Diabetes Foundation in Denver and the lavish Carousel
Ball that supports it. His donations to the foundation, the Barbara
Davis Center for Childhood Diabetes, a geriatrics care facility in
Denver and a research center at Cedars-Sinai Medical Center in Los
Angeles total tens of millions of dollars.
   But if his generosity has made many friends, his sharp business
instincts have, perhaps inevitably, bred conflict.
   Former 20th Century Fox chairman Dennis Stanfill resigned soon
after Davis bought Fox, claiming interference. He filed a $40
million breach-of-contract suit, later settled out of court.
   A suit pending in Houston federal court alleges Davis cheated
investors out of $40 million by taking leftover drilling supplies
from their oil wells. In a fraud suit pending in Denver federal
court, Aetna Life &amp; Casualty Co. claims Davis misrepresented energy
properties in which Aetna had invested.
   Davis has called the suits ``fallacious and without merit.''
   Through it all, nothing seems to dampen the optimism that
motivated him in his wildcatter days. Friends say Davis and his wife
love Hollywood, where they remain on what's known as the social
``A-list.'' Linda Evans, Gregory Peck and Milton Berle attended
their Christmas party last year.
   ``I think he's really enjoying this new episode in his life,''
said former President Gerald Ford, a longtime family friend,
investor and golf partner.
   Ford noted that Davis' business instinct boils over onto the golf
links, where they compete for ``a couple of dollars here and there.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Aug. 27</NOTE>
