<FIRST>s a BC-SchoolSecurity-Rural Adv03   08-25 0418</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-School Security-Rural, Adv 03,0431</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv03</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Sunday, Sept. 3, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>In Some Rural Districts, School Violence Shatters Calm</HEAD>
<HEAD>With BC-School Security</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LEE MITGANG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Education Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The Greenwood, S.C., school district has spent $90,000 to install
intercoms and a fence around an elementary school where an intruder
last year shot and killed two third-graders and wounded seven other
students and two teachers.
   Weapons, drug-related violence, thefts and gang problems have
spread to small-town schools, leading authorities to try the same
high-tech security hardware inner-city schools rely on, a 50-state
Associated Press survey has found.
   ``We have to be conscious of security in small districts, a lot
more than we used to be,'' said superintendent Luis Montoya in
Clifton, Ariz., where a rash of break-ins forced the district to
triple its security outlays in the last five years.
   The effort is mainly to protect new VCRs, computers, tape
recorders and camera equipment. Another problem is siphoning of
gasoline from school buses.
   In central Michigan, the Mason school district spends about
$3,000 a year on motion detector equipment to protect computers at
the middle and high schools.
   ``Compared to five years ago, we didn't have that kind of
equipment. We didn't have that volume of computer equipment to
protect,'' said superintendent Glenn Doran.
   The 1,900-student Perryton Independent School District in the
Texas panhandle pays about $5,000 a year for drug-sniffing dogs and
$250 for security lighting. So far, those measures haven't turned up
much, spokesman Randy Barnes acknowledged.
   ``We found a pill once that looked pretty suspicious, but it
turned out to be a Contac capsule,'' he said.
   In Yankton, S.D., school authorities prefer a hard line on school
crime to security hardware.
   A 15-year-old boy convicted of making a false bomb threat wound
up serving time at the State Training School, and an 18-year-old was
sentenced to one year in the Yankton Detention Center for a similar
threat.
   Not every rural school is worried.
   Several years ago, in an incident that drew national attention,
an armed gunman took an entire school of children hostage in
Cokeville, Wyo. But state superintendent Lynn Simons said the
incident was an aberration and it didn't change his approach to
security.
   ``We can rest easy in Wyoming. We just don't have to worry about
those problems,'' said Simons.
   In Eatonville, Wash., high school principal Randy Dorn knows his
kids sometimes bring weapons to school _ but he says it's only
during hunting season.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, Sept. 3</NOTE>
