<FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights     08-25 0885</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Business Highlights,0923</SECOND>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dow Jones industrial average surged 56.53
points to a new closing high, shattering the record set almost
exactly two years earlier and symbolically marking a recovery from
the Black Monday crash.
   The index of 30 blue chip industrial stocks _ which to many
people symbolizes the stock market _ finished Thursday at 2,734.64,
topping the previous record close of 2,722.42 of Aug. 25, 1987.
   With Thursday's session, the Dow became the last of the widely
recognized market indicators to recover all the ground it lost in
the crash of 1987 that culminated with a record 508-point loss on
Oct. 19.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texas Air Corp. may consider selling part of its
Continental Airlines subsidiary, Chairman Frank Lorenzo said.
   The surprise announcement Thursday came a week after a Boston
investment firm disclosed that it owns 12 percent of Houston-based
Texas Air, the nation's largest airline company. Texas Air owns both
Continental and strikebound Eastern Airlines.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Reserve Board has voted to permit
bank holding companies to buy healthy thrift institutions, a
decision expected to accelerate the shrinkage of the savings
industry and the expansion of interstate banking.
   The 6-0 vote Thursday culminated a bitter, two-year struggle
among financial industry groups seeking to influence the central
bank's ruling.
   But it is also something of an anticlimax because S&amp;L bailout
legislation signed into law two weeks ago authorized the Fed to make
the decision and members of Congress clearly expected it would.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Holiday Corp. has announced the end of its
reign as ``America's Innkeeper'' with an agreement to sell its
Holiday Inn chain to British brewing giant Bass PLC for $2.23
billion.
   Holiday Corp. said Thursday it would form a new subsidiary to run
its profitable casino business and newer hotel chains, Embassy
Suites, Hampton Inn and Homewood Suites.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A target of the government investigation of New
York's futures markets was suspended from trading and he and his
firm were fined a total of $550,000 for violating trading rules at
the Commodity Exchange.
   The fines Thursday against Preston H. Semel and Semel &amp; Co., a
brokerage in gold, silver and other commodities, were believed to be
the largest in exchange history, officials said.
   Semel was cited for internal trading rules violations that also
are being examined in civil and criminal probes announced in May by
the Commodity Futures Trading Commission and Justice Department.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CAMDEN, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Campbell Soup Co. has announced a worldwide
restructuring that will include the loss of 2,800 jobs and the
closure of manufacturing plants in New Jersey, Maryland and
Tennessee.
   The restructuring, unveiled Thursday, is expected to produce a
one-time charge of about $344 million, or $2.01 a share, against
earnings for the 1989 fiscal year, the company said.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Electric Co. and Sweden's L.M. Ericsson
plan to form a joint venture in mobile communications that they
expect to have sales of $1 billion next year.
   The new company will be owned 60 percent by Ericsson and 40
percent by GE. It will produce cellular telephones and other kinds
of mobile radio equipment, including data communications systems. No
money will change hands in the deal, the companies said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Food and Drug Administration procedures
permitted preferential treatment to be given to some drug companies
over others in reviewing generic drugs, according to a federal
report.
   The report by the inspector general of the Department of Health
and Human Services is scheduled for release Monday. It was requested
by the commissioner of food and drugs, Dr. Frank Young, and Rep.
John D. Dingell, D-Mich., chairman of the House Energy and Commerce
subcommittee on oversight and investigations.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Implementation of A.H. Robins Co.'s
reorganization plan will be delayed until at least November while
claimants who challenged the plan appeal its approval to the U.S.
Supreme Court, claimants say.
   ``We're going to the Supreme Court,'' Rosemary Menard-Sanford,
one of thousands of women who claimed they were injured by the
Dalkon Shield birth-control device marketed by the company in the
early 1970s, said Thursday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America's elderly will live increasingly alone
and with greater health limitations in the 21st century, researchers
say in a report highlighting the need for alternative services to
help older people avoid nursing homes.
   The private Urban Institute, in a study projecting the
characteristics of older Americans into the next century, said at
least 30 million elderly people are expected to be living alone in
2030, compared with 8.4 million in 1984.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market surged ahead with renewed force Thursday,
breaking a record high for the Dow Jones industrial average that had
stood for two years. The average of 30 blue chips jumped 56.53
points to 2,734.64, surpassing its closing reading of 2,722.42 on
Aug. 25, 1987.
   The dollar finished mostly higher in quiet worldwide trading.
   Bond prices edged higher in quiet trading.
   Coffee futures prices fell sharply on news that Brazil will not
reintroduce its coffee retention program; copper was up sharply;
sugar prices plunged; grain and sopybean futures were mostly lower;
livestock and pork futures were down; and precious metals were mixed.
</TEXT>
