<FIRST>r f PM-IntegratedResources     08-25 0373</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Integrated Resources,0385</SECOND>
<HEAD>Integrated Sets Tentative Agreement For $310 Million Asset Sale</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Integrated Resources Inc., a struggling financial
services company, says it has reached a tentative agreement to sell
part of its holdings for $310 million to the family-owned Whitehall
Financial Group partnership.
   The price is about $20 million to $30 million below the low end
of the range that Integrated Resources executives had predicted to
creditors that the assets might fetch, Arthur Goldberg, Integrated's
co-chief executive, said Thursday in an interview.
   Nevertheless, Goldberg said he believed the announcement showed
that Integrated Resources was taking credible steps toward raising
money to make payments on its $1.75 billion in debt.
   Integrated has not paid any principle or interest to creditors
since June, when it declared a moratorium because of deepening
financial troubles.
   Integrated said last week it would try to sell its core financial
service companies for $450 million to $525 million, but Whitehall
was interested in only part of the holdings, Goldberg said.
   Since the offer came in below projections, Integrated said it
would continue to solicit bidders for them, but would pay Whitehall
a $4 million breakup fee if their deal was dropped. Goldberg said
other parties are interested in the parts of the business Whitehall
did not want, Goldberg said.
   Whitehall is half owned by members of the de Gunzburg branch of
the Bronfman family of Canada, heirs to the Seagram Ltd. distilling
fortune, and half by the Moross family of London, which has
extensive financial services interests. Whitehall has holdings in
life insurance and property and casualty brokerage.
   Whitehall would buy Integrated Resources Life Insurance Co.,
Integrated Resources Equity Corp., Integrated Resources Asset
Management Corp., Resources Trust Co., and Financial Clearing and
Services Corp.
   The sale price would be $297 million, plus a portion of tax
benefits received by the core companies after the sale that would
raise the total purchase price to $310 million.
   Whitehall would not buy Integrated's Capitol Life Insurance Co.,
its tax-sheltered annuity business, its ordinary life insurance
business or United Resources.
   After the spinoff of subsidiaries, Integrated's main business
would be management of existing public and private limited
partnerships and real estate investment trusts.
</TEXT>
