<FIRST>r f PM-MortgageRates     08-25 0130</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Mortgage Rates,0135</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fixed Rates Up From Lowest Level in Two-Plus Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fixed-rate mortgage rates rose to a national
average of 9.85 percent this month after dropping in July to their
lowest level in more than two years, according to a survey by the
Federal National Mortgage Association.
   Fannie Mae said Thursday the new average for 30-year, fixed-rate
mortgages rose from 9.73 last month, the lowest level since
fixed-rate morgages averaged 9.25 percent in March 1987.
   The rates for one-year adjustable mortgages, meanwhile, fell to
8.51 percent from 8.66 percent in July.
   Because of generally declining rates, homebuyers have flocked to
fixed-rate mortgages recently. In July, the percentage of adjustable
rate mortgage applications fell to 19 percent, the lowest level
since April 1987, Fannie Mae said.
</TEXT>
