<FIRST>r f PM-WallStreet-Reax     08-25 0417</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street-Reax,0433</SECOND>
<HEAD>On Wall Street, Dow Record Marks Just Another Session</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Wall Street Record, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two years ago today, the New York Stock Exchange
closed at an all-time high. Two months later, the market crashed.
   The resurgent Dow Jones industrials average on Thursday finally
cracked its 1987 record but few if any market professionals believe
that history will repeat itself.
   ``You didn't have the euphoric buying all summer long'' this
year, said Peter Blatchford, a 27-year-old market maker on the
options floor. ``It's based on sound economic news. The economy is
stronger than people thought.''
   In stark contrast with the go-go days of Summer 1987, this year's
rise to new record highs has been slow and steady.
   ``Everyone knows what the monster looks like and they're looking
over their shoulders to see him,'' said Robert W. Seijas, a partner
in a stock exchange member firm.
   Traders spilled out of the exchange at Wall and New streets after
the closing bell Thursday as on any other day. But this time the Dow
Jones industrials average had finished at a record 2,734.64,
surpassing its reading of 2,722.42 on Aug. 25, 1987.
   The rise in the closely watched measure 30 key industrial company
stocks is considered the final symbolic sign on Wall Street of the
steady recovery since the 1987 crash, which saw the Dow plunge 508
points on Oct. 19, 1987. Other key indexes shattered record highs
earlier this summer.
   The Dow flirted with the record several times earlier this month,
breaking through the top number but ending the day lower.
   A subdued cheer rose from the exchange floor after the close
Thursday.
   ``A day like every other day _ no big deal,'' said Peter Mancuso,
a specialist with Albert Fried &amp; Co. ``There was no question in
everybody's mind that the market would get back to these levels. It
just needed some time.''
   Market players said the difference between 1987 and 1989 lies in
the economy's strength, with inflation apparently under control and
interest rates gradually heading lower _ the non-recessionary ``soft
landing'' many economists have been predicting.
   They did say cracking the old record was significant because, on
Wall Street, psychological barriers are important. Thanks to the
economy's strength, optimism remains the vanguard on the Street.
   ``The market seems to want to go higher,'' said Alfred Smith, a
specialist with A.C. Partners. ``The further away you get from the
crash, the better it is.''
</TEXT>
