<FIRST>r f PM-Holiday-Bass Bjt   08-25 0557</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Holiday-Bass, Bjt,0574</SECOND>
<BYLINE>Bass Purchase of Holiday Inns Clears Path For Holiday's Other Chains</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The proposed $2.2 billion sale of Holiday
Inns Inc. would make Bass PLC of Great Britain the world's largest
hotel manager and clear the way for parent Holiday Corp. to
concentrate on its casinos and newer hotel chains, market observers
say.
   Holiday Corp. ``is poised for substantial growth in their new
form and with a much better balance sheet,'' said Marvin Roffman, a
market analyst with the Philadelphia brokerage Janney Montgomery
Scott Inc.
   Holiday, the Memphis-based parent of Holiday Inns, announced the
proposed sale Thursday, prompting the company's stock to jump $6 a
share to close at $83 on the New York Stock Exchange.
   ``The price received for the Holiday Inn brand was a very solid
valuation of about 13{ times pre-tax cashflow. That looks pretty
attractive considering it's a tax-free transaction to Holiday
Corp.,'' said John Lawrence, a market analyst with the brokerage
Morgan Keegan &amp; Co. of Memphis.
   The sale must be approved by shareholders of both companies.
Ralph Berry, a spokesman for Holiday Corp., said no dates have been
set for shareholder meetings to vote on the proposal.
   Holiday Corp. said it would form a new subsidiary to run its
profitable hotel-casino company, Harrah's, and its newer hotel
chains, Embassy Suites, Hampton Inn and Homewood Suites.
   ``It clearly focuses the company in the high-growth segments of
the hotel business,'' Roffman said.
   Holiday said its newer hotel brands have grown to the point that
they compete with Holiday Inn in the marketplace and for attention
within the corporation.
   Under the proposed sale agreement, Holiday stockholders would get
one-quarter share of Bass stock for each of their Holiday shares,
worth a total of about $125 million. They also would get a
$35-a-share dividend from the new Holiday subsidiary.
   In addition, they would get one share in the new subsidiary for
each of their Holiday shares, and Lawrence said that stock would be
worth $45 to $55 a share.
   The sale will allow Holiday Corp. to shed $2.1 billion in debt,
which will be assumed by Bass. Much of the debt stems from the
company's recapitalization in 1987, which allowed the company to pay
shareholders an extra dividend to ward of a takeover threat by New
York developer Donald J. Trump, Berry said.
   ``As a result of that, the new company when it's spun off will be
virtually debt-free. It will then borrow or finance new borrowing to
pay the dividend,'' he said.
   With the sale, Bass will acquire 55 owned or leased Holiday Inns
as well as franchise agreements, joint venture agreements and
management contracts covering about 1,400 other Holiday Inns in
North America.
   Last year, Bass bought the rights to franchise Holiday Inn hotels
outside North America and the company is a major franchisee in
Canada. Bass already owns 14 Holiday Inns in the southeast United
States.
   Bass has more than 7,300 pubs and other food and drink outlets in
the United Kingdom. The company also brews Bass, Carling Black Label
and other beers. It has annual sales approaching $6 billion.
   The British company is expected to keep Holiday Inn's North
American headquarters in Memphis, Berry said, and Holiday Corp.
employees now working for Holiday Inn will become Bass employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
