<DOCNO> AP890825-0217 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 0256EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f PM-CommoditiesProbe-NY Bjt   08-25 0641</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Commodities Probe-NY, Bjt,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Fines Against Trader, Firm Sign Of Increased Policing, Experts Say</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEFAN FATSIS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Fines totaling $550,000 against a top commodities
trader and his firm are a sign of increased internal policing in the
face of a federal investigation of New York's futures markets,
industry experts say.
   The Commodity Exchange on Thursday fined and suspended the
trader, Preston H. Semel, for violating trading rules. Semel is one
of the targets of the government's criminal and civil probes of New
York's commodity markets.
   ``It's a very large fine and it's probably making a statement
that what he did was bad and trying to tell the rest of Comex to be
careful,'' said Thomas Russo, a commodities lawyer and former
chairman of the federal Commodity Futures Trading Commission.
   The fines against Semel and Semel &amp; Co., a brokerage in gold,
silver and other commodities, were believed to be the largest in
exchange history, officials said.
   Semel was cited for internal trading rules violations that also
are being examined in civil and criminal probes at Comex and three
other exchanges announced in May by the CFTC and Justice Department.
   The probes are unrelated to a longstanding probe of Chicago's
commodity markets that recently yielded 46 indictments for
racketeering and fraud.
   A government official familiar with the New York investigations
confirmed Thursday that Semel is ``one of many'' traders whose
actions are being examined. The official, who asked not to be named,
said the probes include the same types of violations cited by Comex.
   More than 50 traders received subpoenas and federal authorities
are examining boxes of documents provided by the exchanges and
traders, defense lawyers said Thursday. No action in the federal
probe is expected for at least two months, lawyers said.
   The official familiar with the criminal probe said investigators
from the Manhattan U.S. attorney's office and the U.S. Postal
Service are examining documents subpoenaed by the CFTC.
   ``We've still got a while to go on the criminal case,'' the
official said.
   Comex spokesman Robert McGrath said Semel was fined $350,000 and
suspended for nine months from the exchange while Semel &amp; Co. was
fined $200,000.
   The violations by Semel involve improper cross-trading and
prohibited dual trading, two offenses that center on trading for
customers and personal accounts.
   Semel, 39, and his firm also were cited under exchange rules for
misconduct, disreputable or fraudulent conduct and conduct
detrimental to the exchange.
   Comex guidelines regarding the two stated trading violations bar
traders from taking the opposite side of an order received and from
trading for personal accounts while holding a customer's order for
the same commodity.
   Officials said the charges listed generally involve a practice
know as ``front-running'' _ getting an unfair advantage by trading
for personal accounts ahead of customer orders for the same
commodity. That pracice is under scrutiny in the federal probes.
   A person answering the telephone Thursday at Semel &amp; Co. said no
one would be available for comment.
   The CFTC probe reportedly examines violations including
pre-arranged trading, using advance knowledge of customer trades to
trade for personal accounts and conducting trades in order to skirt
tax obligations.
   The criminal probe reportedly includes examination of alleged
front-running at the exchanges and whether brokers and traders
illegally shared information with each other about customer orders.
   Comex issued a complaint against Semel _ a powerful figure on the
exchange floor _ in June 1988 for trading that took place before
then, McGrath said. He refused to release other details about the
internal probe.
   Semel was expected to appeal the penalty to the CFTC but
spokeswoman Kate Hathaway said he had not yet done so.
   In addition to the Comex, the government in May issued subpoenas
to the New York Mercantile Exchange, the Coffee, Sugar and Cocoa
Exchange, and the Cotton Exchange.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
