<FIRST>u f PM-Japan-Markets     08-25 0262</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Japan-Markets,0275</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar, Nikkei Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar edged down against the yen today, while
share prices on the Tokyo Stock Exchange closed lower.
   The dollar closed at 143.53 yen, down 0.07 yen from Thursday's
close of 143.60. The dollar started the day at 143.38 yen, and moved
in a range of 143.33-143.63 yen.
   On the stock market, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected
issues, a 106.73-point loser Thursday, lost 46.62 points today to
close marginally lower at 34,739.93.
   Currency dealers said trading was light and directionless.
``Japanese customers were staying on the sidelines,'' said Minori
Takeuchi, a trader at Chemical Bank.
   The resignation of Chief Cabinet Secretary Tokuo Yamashita today
did not have a major impact on currency markets, Takeuchi said.
   Yamashita announced he would resign after apologizing for an
extramarital affair with a bar hostess.
   ``Usually it would have an impact on the market, but the market
didn't move because many Japanese institutions had long dollar
positions and couldn't buy on the upside of the dollar,'' Takeuchi
said.
   On the stock market, prices were dampened by concerns about
interest rates, said a dealer at brokerage Kleinwort Benson who
spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Because domestic consumption and economic growth look like they
may be stronger this quarter than earlier expected, ``the market is
having to sit up and take notice of what's happening with interest
rates,'' he said.
   The effect of Yamashita's resignation was ``minimal,'' the dealer
said.
   Blue chips ``had a nice little run,'' he said, noting Sony closed
up 100 yen at 8,900 yen.
</TEXT>
