<FIRST>r f PM-FCC-Indecency     08-25 0880</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-FCC-Indecency,0910</SECOND>
<HEAD>FCC Looking Into Alleged Indecent Broadcasts</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: Contents in grafs 17-19 may be offensive to some readers; also
moved on general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAY ARNOLD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Communications Commission, in what
may indicate a new get-tough policy, is contemplating action against
three radio stations it says may have aired indecent broadcasts
during the day.
   The stations in Indianapolis, Chicago and San Jose, Calif., were
given 30 days to explain their actions or face sanctions ranging
from a warning to non-renewal of their licenses, FCC General Counsel
Diane Killory said Thursday.
   The action comes just two weeks after former Missouri broadcaster
Alfred Sikes was confirmed as FCC chairman.
   Sikes and two other new commissioners were questioned closely
during Senate confirmation hearings last month on what they planned
to do about indecent programming. Obscene programming is banned.
   The agency alleges that WLUP-AM in Chicago, KSJO-FM in San Jose,
Calif., and WFBQ-FM in Indianapolis may have violated laws
prohibiting indecent or obscene programming when children may be in
the audience.
   Lawyer John R. Price, president of Decency in Broadcasting Inc.,
said the Indianapolis-based watchdog group had taped WFBQ's ``Bob
and Tom Show'' continuously since July 1987 and submitted more than
5,000 transcripts to the FCC for review.
   ``In the last six months particularly, there's been a real
decline in the quality of material,'' he said Thursday. ``It was bad
before, but it's really bad now.''
   Price said he hoped the FCC action would be ``the first step in a
process that will improve broadcasting in our area.''
   Sen. Jesse Helms, R-N.C., an outspoken advocate of banning
indecent programming 24 hours a day, applauded the FCC action.
   ``The American people are fed up with this trash that corrupts
the minds of our children and erodes the values of our society,''
Helms said.
   However, Andrew Schwartzman, executive director of the
Washington-based free-speech advocacy group Media Access Project,
criticized the FCC.
   ``I'm disappointed that Chairman Sikes' top priority seems to be
suppressing speech rather than promoting it,'' Schwartzman said.
   The FCC said that based on ``review of complaints and extensive
supporting materials received from the public,'' it was considering
actions against:
   _Evergreen Media Corp. of Chicago AM, licensee of WLUP-AM,
regarding portions of the ``Steve and Gary Show,'' which airs at
2:30 p.m.
   _Narragansett Broadcasting Co. of California, licensee of
KSJO-FM, San Jose, regarding portions of the ``Perry Stone Show,''
which aired at 6 a.m.
   _Great American TV and Radio Co., licensee of WFBQ-FM,
Indianapolis, regarding portions of the ``Bob and Tom Show,'' which
airs at 6 a.m.
   On WLUP's ``Steve and Gary Show'' on March 30, 1989, and Aug. 19,
1987, there were alleged discussions of erections; descriptions of
magazine pictures of former Miss America Vanessa Williams and
another woman; and a song about a man filming ``Kiddie Porn'' at a
youth camp.
   Stone programs on Oct. 25, 27, 28 and 31, and Nov. 4, 1988,
allegedly included a segment in which Stone told a female caller he
wanted to lick food off her body; a later segment that featured a
ribald version of the theme from the ``Beverly Hillbillies'' TV
show; a segment on incest and one on classical music performed in
``fellatio.''
   On WFBQ, there allegedly was talk Oct. 16, 1987, and Sept. 14,
1987, of sex with candy bars, and a skit of Elvis discussing sex and
Richard Nixon.
   The latest these broadcasts occurred was at 5:10 p.m., Killory
said.
   Chris Wheat, general manager of WFBQ-FM, told the Indianapolis
Star that the station was ``fairly confident'' the FCC will find
that its rules were followed.
   ``The material doesn't have the innuendo attached to it that one
might read into the complaint,'' Wheat said about the ``Bob and Tom
Show'' complaints. ``Once the material is put into context, I'm sure
we will be cleared of doing anything wrong.''
   There was no answer to telephone calls to the Chicago and San
Jose stations Thursday evening.
   The FCC, based on Supreme Court rulings in the ``seven dirty
words'' case involving comedian George Carlin, defines indecency as
``language or material that, in context, depicts or describes, in
terms patently offensive as measured by contemporary community
standards for the broadcast medium, sexual or excretory activities
or organs. Such material may not be broadcast when there is a
reasonable risk that unsupervised children may be in the audience.''
   The commission has tried to establish a ``safe harbor'' for
indecent programming from midnight to 6 a.m., when children were
considered unlikely to be listening, but a court struck down that
rule last summer. The court said the commission could ban indecent
speech only during daytime hours.
   The FCC in June 1988 fined a Kansas City, Mo., station, KZKC-TV,
$2,000 for broadcasting the movie ``Private Lessons'' at 8 p.m. The
movie features explicit nudity in a story about a housekeeper
seducing a 15-year-old boy.
   Congress last year passed a law extending the ban on indecent
broadcast material to 24 hours, but the U.S. Court of Appeals in
Washington stayed implementation of the law in January pending an
appeal by broadcasters and First Amendment advocates.
   The FCC on Thursday also asked the court not to rule on the
24-hour ban challenge before the commission can study the issue
further, Killory said.
</TEXT>
