<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1030EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-SpongeDivingSqueeze Adv28   08-25 0880</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Sponge Diving Squeeze, Adv 28,0905</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday, Aug. 28</HEAD>
<HEAD>Fortune Hunters Clear Out as Sponge Prices Drop</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRIAN MURPHY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TARPON SPRINGS, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Kelly Garrett promised he was
through. He was going to sell his last load of ocean sponge and
leave this Gulf Coast fishing town, where he was lured 18 months ago
by record-high sponge prices.
   Maybe he'd take his wife and child to the Bahamas and try to make
some money salvaging old wrecks.
   ``This is it,'' he said, standing amid 700 sponges drying on the
deck of a weathered fishing boat. ``I'm getting out while I at least
have my diving equipment. But I can say it was real good there for a
while.''
   Garrett became the latest defection from the Tarpon Springs
sponge fleet as prices have fallen about 80 percent since February,
when a large sponge could bring in $16 and even inexperienced divers
could easily make $1,000 a week.
   Now, it's mostly just the few veteran spongers left to wonder
about the brief boom that clogged the docks with boats and left at
least four young divers dead from accidental drownings.
   Some of the old-time sponge merchants _ mostly Greek immigrants
and their descendants _ claim the prices were inflated by Japanese
investors who recently entered the shaky Mediterranean sponge market.
   Others, like sponge buyer Julio Arellano in Miami, say a
3-year-old blight affecting Mediterranean sponge beds was
responsible for a worldwide shortage.
   ``It was simple supply and demand,'' said the executive of
Arellano Brothers Inc., the main buyer of Tarpon Springs sponges as
prices soared. ``There are no good sponges coming out of the
Mediterranean and the value of the Tarpon Springs sponges went up.
It's not more complicated than that.''
   Arellano said prices have dropped to $3 or $4 each due to the
flood of sponges on the world market from Tarpon Springs, about 30
miles north of Tampa.
   Although sponges grow in many warm-water areas, the best species
come either from the eastern Mediterranean or the Gulf waters off
Tarpon Springs, where the nutrients and rock beds are ideal for
large and hardy sponges, said John Stevely, a sponge expert
affiliated with the University of Florida.
   The Mediterranean blight, suspected to be caused by a bacteria,
makes the sponges small and brittle. A similar disease in the Gulf
of Mexico and the Caribbean in the 1940s nearly wiped out the sponge
industry in Florida and Cuba, which is now a sponge supplier to East
Bloc nations.
   A sponge is acually the remains of a marine animal that lives in
the pores. Sun drying kills the living part of the natural sponge,
now mostly sold in the United Staates as a novelty bath item or as a
non-scratching alternative to synethetic sponges. But the demand for
natural sponge is still high in Europe and elsewhere.
   George Billiris, who began sponge diving in 1939, believes
Japanese sponge interests purchased the high-priced sponges earlier
this year in an attempt to corner the market and drive out smaller
competitors.
   ``Look, if a sponge cost $15 each it would cost the consumer $45
for a sponge. That didn't happen. I think they were just trying to
protect their investments in the Mediterranean,'' said Billiris.
   But James Cantonis, president of Acme Sponge and Chamois Co. in
Tarpon Springs, said it was mostly a panic among European buyers as
inventories of pre-blight Mediterranean sponges fell.
   He also noted that European sponge buyers, who usually make
purchases by the kilogram, were unfamiliar with the denser Tarpons
Springs wool sponges.
   ``Acually, the per-kilo price was not that crazy,'' said
Cantonis, also president of the New York-based Sponge and Chamois
Institute. ``But they were surprised by the wool sponges. You got
only about half as many per kilo.
   ``At one point, our sponges were selling at $3.50 an ounce.
Silver now sells about $5 an ounce. This is not gold or silver we
are taking about.''
   Cantonis said there are no records of natural sponge sales in the
United States or worldwide.
   Although experts are not sure how long the Mediterranean blight
may last, Acme has built a new sponge processing plant to meet
European demand.
   ``This portends well for Tarpon Springs,'' he said. ``What the
prices will do, I cannot say.''
   When the boom began, sponge diver Cary Barger said he predicted
prices would fall. He also was correct about his other preminition _
that untrained divers would die.
   In February, more than 200 people were diving for sponges. Now,
there's less than two dozen. The U.S. Coast Guard investigated the
deaths of at least four divers.
   Some of the victims were working alone and had problems with the
air compressors or tangled air hoses. Divers can spend up to nine
hours under 30 to 40 feet of water.
   ``This is serious business and people just thought you jump down
there and pick up sponges like you pick up money,'' said Barger, who
started diving two years ago. ``It was insane.''
   ``Everyone is looking for the next oil boom,'' said Cantonis.
``Everyone is looking to become a millionaire overnight. Well, I can
tell you, this is not the business they should be looking at.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday Aug. 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
