<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1112EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>a f BC-AsbestosFirm Adv28   08-25 0792</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Asbestos Firm, Adv 28,0818</SECOND>
<HEAD>$adv28</HEAD>
<HEAD>For release Monday Aug. 28</HEAD>
<HEAD>Entrepreneur Cleans Up on Asbestos Cleanup</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto LWRX4 of Aug. 23</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY STREFF BUZBEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LAWRENCE, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   When engineering graduate David Kimbrell
looked around in the mid-1980s and wondered how to make a living, he
found the answer buried in the walls.
   Along with colleague Frank Hall, Kimbrell founded one of the
first consulting firms that advise the best way to test for and
dispose of asbestos, the widely used building insulation that has
been found to cause cancer.
   Then Kimbrell had a hunch about schools.
   By the time Congress approved a 1986 law requiring control and
cleanup of asbestos in school buildings, Kimbrell already had a
national marketing campaign ready.
   Hall-Kimbrell's growth exploded, its revenues tripling over the
past three years from contracts with 15 percent of the nation's
school districts.
   ``I don't know if it's a sixth sense or what, but we kind of feel
things coming,'' said Kimbrell, 38. ``We try to watch for the
regulatory trends _ what's the research on what is toxic, what are
the liability issues _ and we felt that asbestos was going to be a
major problem.''
   Now Kimbrell is betting on his sixth sense again.
   ``We started watching Japan two or three years ago,'' he said.
``And we speculated that they were just at that stage of
industrialization where they're starting to address the issues of
asbestos and employee occupational exposure. So far, we've been
right.''
   Kimbrell bought out Hall's interest in the firm after the first
few months of business, although he's retained the Hall-Kimbrell
corporate name.
   His hunches have propelled Hall-Kimbrell's growth since he and
his wife drew up a five-year plan in 1983 for the company they'd
started in Mississippi the year before. They'd already made $120,000
from asbestos consulting and were trying to decide what to do.
   ``We wanted to be the best environmental engineering firm in the
nation,'' he said. ``We decided to take the specialty we knew,
asbestos, and form a national company on that. So we drew up a plan
to take literally every penny we made and put it back into growth.''
   The plague of lingering asbestos resurfaced this past week, when
federal prosecutors filed civil suits against several defendants
nationwide alleging improper handling of the material during
renovation and removal projects. The lawsuits underscored the
importance of the kind of services that Hall-Kimbrell and other
asbestos-cleansing consultants provide.
   Hall-Kimbrell has surveyed more than 1,300 school districts for
asbestos, in addition to 15 state governments, 200 colleges, ten
airports and thousands of commercial clients. Typically, its
engineers develop a plan to remove or contain asbestos, then monitor
another company that actually does the work.
   Its revenues grew from $248,000 in 1983 to $45 million last year
and a 34th place on Inc. magazine's list of the fastest-growing U.S.
companies.
   The firm now employs about 800 people in 26 offices.
Hall-Kimbrell moved to Lawrence, near Kansas City, to be in the
central part of the country and near a regional Environmental
Protection Agency office, but much of its work remains on the East
Coast.
   According to plan, Hall-Kimbrell also began diversifying in the
late 1980s, advising companies on environmental problems ranging
from hazardous wastes and groundwater contamination.
   Next year, it expects to start a hotline in connection with
grocery store chains, to let customers know how much pesticide is in
the produce they buy.
   The fast growth hasn't been problem free. The company laid off 39
workers earlier this summer in a move to cut costs.
   Earlier this year, Kimbrell had considered a $72.5 million buyout
offer from Law Companies Group, an Atlanta environmental firm. But
Kimbrell said he rejected the deal because of differences with Law
Companies over control.
   Nonetheless, many analysts think such deals are the industry's
future.
   Fast-growing, small to medium-sized companies such as
Hall-Kimbrell have dominated the asbestos-control business up to
now, but bigger environmental services companies are want a piece of
the market now estimated between $1 billion and $3 billion a year,
said Steven Bernard, a securities analyst with Edward D. Jones &amp; Co.
in St. Louis.
   Analysts foresee most of the industry's growth in the United
States, as more states approve even stricter asbestos guidelines for
private buildings.
   But that hasn't stopped Hall-Kimbrell from pressing ahead with
its overseas plans. Most of its business overseas currently involves
advising Japanese firms that own U.S. property, said John Carlin, a
former Kansas governor who sits on Hall-Kimbrell's board of
directors and has helped it get started in Japan.
   ``Given the context of how long it takes to set up business
there, they're doing extremely well,'' Carlin said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End adv for Monday Aug. 28</NOTE>
</DOC>
