<HEAD>Rain And Slack Export Demand Send Futures Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened lower in light
trading today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Prices were being pressured today by forecasts of rain in much of
the Plains and the Ohio Valley.
   But there was concern the severe weather forecast for parts of
the Plains could have an adverse impact on some crop areas, said
Joel Karlin, an analyst for Research Department Inc. in Chicago.
   Another drag on prices was the lack of action in the cash
markets. Analysts said few farmers are bringing their product to
market.
   With the exception of wheat, there was little export demand for
grain and beans, Karlin said.
   In early trading, wheat was { cent to 1 cent lower in all
contracts with the contract for delivery in September at $3.93} a
bushel; corn was 1 cent lower with September at $2.33\ a bushel;
oats were { cent lower to { cent higher with September at $1.37{ a
bushel; soybeans were 2{ cents lower to 1} cents higher with
September at $5.94{ cents a bushel.
   Livestock futures were lower and pork futures mixed in early
trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .07 cent lower to .03 cent higher with October
at 75.15 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .10 cent to .38 cent
lower with August at 83.85 cents a pound; live hogs were .02 cent to
.35 cent lower with October at 41.32 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .10 cent lower to .10 cent higher with February at
41.52 cents a pound.
   Livestock futures settled lower and pork futures were mixed in
Thursday's trading.
