<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1139EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-Eastern-Pilots     08-25 0434</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Eastern-Pilots,0449</SECOND>
<HEAD>Grassroots Movement For Pilot Work Stoppage Reported</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pilots from major competitors are volunteering to
stage a wildcat work stoppage Sept. 4 to support Eastern Airlines
strikers, a union official said Thursday.
   ``It's called Shut Down America,'' said Hank Weber, a spokesman
for the Eastern local of the Air Line Pilots Association. ``It's one
of those things. We've never had anything from the grassroots like
this before. All we can do is watch and see what happens.''
   Weber said the union wasn't organizing the effort and had no
details, but has been flooded with messages of support. He showed
messages from pilots for such airlines as United, Northwest, TWA and
Aloha Airlines.
   One message called for ``S.O.S. _ Suspension of Service; Sick-Out
in September ... Are you sick of what's happening to our Eastern
brothers?''
   ALPA's executive council, representing pilots at most of the
nation's major airlines, last week took no action on a request by
Eastern's pilots for a national work stoppage to show solidarity
with the strike that will be six months old on Sept. 4.
   However, Weber said that while unions can be fined or face other
sanctions for encouraging wildcat strikes, an unofficial sickout may
be forming as an alternative. Sept. 4 is Labor Day, a heavy travel
day.
   Weber said members of other unions, including some outside the
airline industry, also have offered to participate.
   Eastern's union leadership met in Washington on Thursday to plan
strategy. While some leaders two weeks ago discussed ending the
strike, their rank-and-file members have voted in local meetings to
continue.
   The pilots, who joined Eastern's Machinists and flight attendants
in a March 4 walkout, said they want action to dramatize that their
strike is continuing and that Eastern is rebuilding with
inexperienced, newly hired pilots who are jeopardizing safety.
   Eastern spokesman Robin Matell said the company wouldn't comment
on the reported work stoppage effort.
   Texas Air Corp. Chairman Frank Lorenzo, whose reputed
union-busting has been the focus of the strike, announced late
Thursday that he is considering selling a minority or controlling
stake in Eastern's sister carrier Continental Airlines.
   In Atlanta, meanwhile, the local chief of the Eastern pilots
union said Thursday he will resign in a disagreement over continuing
the strike.
   James B. Holder, the head of the Atlanta local of Eastern's
pilots union, said the 300 pilots who attended a Wednesday meeting
voted to continue the strike.
   He said he objected to the decision because by continuing to
strike, Eastern ``could hire enough replacement pilots and we could
be gone.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
