<FIRST>r f PM-CBOT-Capcom     08-25 0151</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-CBOT-Capcom,0160</SECOND>
<HEAD>Commodities Firm Banned By Board of Trade</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The commodities trading firm Capcom Financial
Services Ltd. has been expelled from the Chicago Board of Trade in
the wake of charges the firm engaged in a multimillion-dollar
drug-money laundering scheme.
   London-based Capcom agreed to the expulsion and to never reapply
for membership in the CBOT, according to an exchange statement
Thursday.
   The firm was suspended July 17 for violating exchange rules
requiring member firms to maintain and produce accurate records of
customer accounts.
   Capcom had been a member of the CBOT since 1985, officials said.
   Capcom and one of its officers, S.Z.A. Akbar, were indicted in
October following a two-year government sting operation in Tampa,
Fla. in which federal agents infiltrated a money-laundering
syndicate with ties to a Columbian drug cartel.
   Seventy-nime people and entities, including the Bank of Credit
and Commerce International of Luxembourg, were indicted.
</TEXT>
