   Stock prices were mixed today, struggling to
extend the yearlong rally that carried the market to record highs on
Thursday.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, up 56.53 points Thursday
to surpass the peak it reached two years ago, rose another 5.31 to
2,739.95 by noontime on Wall Street.
   But losers slightly outnumbered gainers in nationwide trading of
New York Stock Exchange-listed issues, with 646 up, 672 down and 551
unchanged.
   The market appeared to pause as some traders cashed in the
dramatic gains of stock prices lately.
   But prices generally held steady on the strength of the
enthusiasm generated by Thursday's record high and the widespread
public attention it received.
   Analysts say the market has been able to recoup the last of the
losses it suffered in the crash of 1987 with help from increasing
confidence that the Federal Reserve can restrain inflation without
causing a recession.
   They also note that corporate earnings have risen sharply in the
past two years, making the perceived risk in stocks less than it was
when the market peaked out two years ago today.
