<SECOND>BC-Board of Trade, Close,0227</SECOND>
<HEAD>Rains Continue to Cause Selloff</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures closed lower Friday in
quiet trading on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   The selloff was attributed to the forecasts for rain in the
plains states and the Ohio Valley over the weekend and expectation
of more precipitation next week, said Dale Gustafson, an analyst
with Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. in Chicago.
   As a result of the rain, traders are expecting improved corn and
soybean crop conditions next week, Gustafson said.
   Slack export sales and a drop in processor demand were also cited
as a cause of the selloff in soybeans and corn.
   ``There is not much working in terms of export sales, which is a
problem for the market,'' Gustafson said.
   The selloff in the corn and soybean pits spilled over into wheat
futures, where the lack of new export sales also hurt prices.
   At the close, wheat was 3} cents to 6\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.90{ a bushel; corn was 1\
cents to 1} cents lower with September at $2.33 a bushel; oats were
1 cent to 3\ cents lower with September at $1.34} a bushel; soybeans
were a \ cent to 14} cents lower with September at $5.81 a bushel.
