<DOCNO> AP890825-0243 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1517EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f PM-WallStreet-Record 3rdLd-Writethru   08-25 0598</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Wall Street-Record, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0617</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Jones Average Breaks High Set Two Years Ago Today</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 2 grafs to UPDATE with stocks lower; picks up 3rd
graf, On Thursday ....</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto NY9, LaserGraphic</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices retreated slightly in late trading
today, the second anniversary of the peak that preceded the crash of
1987.
   The Dow Jones industrial average of 30 stocks was down 3.61
points at 2,731.03 at 3 p.m. EDT.
   On Thursday _ one day short of the market peak's second
anniversary _ the market's most famous barometer soared 56.53 points
to surpass by 12 points its previous all-time high of Aug. 25, 1987.
   The 1987 peak was the start of a short but severe bear market
that culminated in the worst day in Wall Street history, the
508-point plunge in the Dow Jones industrials on Oct. 19, 1987.
   Market analysts said the risk of a financial meltdown was far
lower today than two years ago, and evidence of the 1987 debacle was
hard to find this week.
   ``The quote of the day is something like: What crash?'' Robert
Brusca, chief economist of Nikko Securities Co. International Inc.,
the New York arm of a Japanese brokerage firm, said Thursday.
   Supporting the stock market in 1989 are a healthy dollar,
relatively low interest rates and optimism that the economy will
manage to steer a middle course between recession and high inflation.
   Most of all, there is no speculative bubble ready to be popped.
Stock prices are far lower in relation to underlying company profits
than they were two years ago, said Lawrence Kudlow, chief economist
at Bear, Stearns &amp; Co.
   ``Fundamentally this is a great expression of confidence in the
whole U.S. economic outlook,'' Kudlow said. ``We keep throwing
negatives at the market and they don't stick.''
   Added David M. Jones, chief economist at the brokerage firm
Aubrey G. Lanston &amp; Co., ``Essentially the stock market is telling
us that a soft landing is in store for the economy, and that's
exactly the slowdown you need to keep inflation from accelerating,''
   While some other strategists are more skeptical about the
economy's health, a market rally can sometimes feed on itself
regardless of fundamental factors.
   ``The worst thing that can happen to an institutional money
manager is to sit there with a pile of cash and watch the market
take off without him. It's a buying panic,'' said Lawrence R.
Helfand, managing director for retail sales at the Chicago brokerage
Rodman &amp; Renshaw Inc.
   Thursday's gain was the second-biggest of the year, and it came
in the heaviest trading since mid-June, a good sign for the market.
Volume on the New York Stock Exchange totaled 225.52 million shares.
   A subdued cheer rose from the exchange floor after the close
Thursday.
   ``A day like every other day _ no big deal,'' said Peter Mancuso,
a specialist with Albert Fried &amp; Co. ``There was no question in
everybody's mind that the market would get back to these levels. It
just needed some time.''
   There was no economic news Thursday to account for the big jump.
Bonds were up slightly and the dollar edged higher.
   ``The market's going up just on its own. When you call around,
there's no reason. It just went up,'' Brusca said.
   From its low point at the close of Black Monday to its close
Thursday, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 57 percent.
   ``While nobody's paid much attention to it, it's two of the
strongest years, back to back, that we've had,'' Helfand said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP890825-0244 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1635EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>r f AM-WarnerBankruptcy     08-25 0525</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Warner Bankruptcy,0542</SECOND>
<HEAD>Hearing Scheduled on Motion to Rescind Liquidation Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RON WORD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSONVILLE, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A hearing has been scheduled next month
to determine whether former Ohio financier Marvin Warner will be
allowed to reorganize his financial affairs to stave off liquidation.
   U.S. Bankruptcy Judge George Proctor scheduled a hearing Sept. 7
on whether Warner's case should be converted back to a Chapter 11
reorganization, instead of the Chapter 7 liquidation decreed by the
court July 28.
   ``We hope at this hearing to present the true perspective of this
case and unmask the nature of the claimants,'' Warner said following
a hearing Friday.
   In his motion before the court, the former U.S. ambassador to
Switzerland, who is appealing a securities conviction in Ohio,
claimed he was not given proper advance notification of plans to
convert the case to Chapter 7, which allows the appointment of a
trustee and liquidation of a debtor's assets.
   Warner, target of a flood of lawsuits following the collapse of
his Cincinnati-based Home State Savings Bank in March 1985, said he
filed for protection under Chapter 11 of the U.S. Bankruptcy Code in
October 1987 in an attempt to consolidate the legal actions.
   ``I came to Chapter 11 not because I owed people money. I wanted
to consolidate in one forum these many lawsuits,'' Warner said
Friday.
   He contends a list of creditors, including the state of Ohio,
seeking $4.5 billion are merely claimants.
   ``I don't owe anybody anything,'' Warner said. ``The attorney
general of Ohio has stated that the losses in the closing of Home
State have substantially been recovered. ... How can the state of
Ohio justify having a claim of $275 million?''
   In March 1987, the creditors obtained a federal court order that
Warner pay back to Ohio $22 million needed to guarantee Home State
deposits.
   Warner, 70, was convicted on Ohio felony charges in Home State's
collapse but was acquitted of federal charges in a separate trial.
He is appealing the state conviction and a $22 million restitution
order.
   Home State collapsed four days after ESM Government Securities in
Fort Lauderdale was shut down by federal regulators for insolvency.
Home State had invested heavily with ESM through securities trade
and lost $144 million when ESM was closed.
   Several months after the Home State collapse, Warner and his wife
Jody moved from suburban Cincinnati to a 153-acre farm near Ocala,
where Warner breeds throughbred horses.
   Warner contends that more than 80 percent of his 1986 income was
derived from farming, and farmer's estates can't be converted to
Chapter 7 without the debtor's consent.
   Warner also claims $18 million of his estate is exempt from
bankruptcy under Florida's homestead law, which allows people to
protect their homes from bankruptcy proceedings. The law protects up
to one-half acre in urban areas and 160 acres in rural areas.
   Meanwhile, Warner's creditors and attorneys have been meeting in
an attempt to settle his bankruptcy case, but so far have not
reached any agreement.
   At a hearing Thursday, West Palm Beach attorney Daniel Bakst was
replaced as trustee of Warner's estate by Tallahassee attorney
Ronald Mowrey.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
