<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1627EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-CommoditiesProbe     08-25 0458</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodities Probe,0474</SECOND>
<HEAD>Two Bean Traders, Clerk, Plead Guilty; 12 Others Plead Innocent</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two soybean traders and a clerk pleaded guilty
Friday to charges of improper trading practices, while 12 others
pleaded innocent in the government's probe of alleged fraud at the
world's largest futures exchanges.
   All those who appeared before U.S. District Judge William Hart
were involved in soybean-trading activity at the Chicago Board of
Trade during a 2{-year undercover probe by FBI agents masquerading
as traders.
   The four remaining soybean traders charged are to be arraigned
Sept. 7.
   A total of 45 traders and the clerk were indicted earlier this
month after the investigation at the Board of Trade and the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange.
   The three who pleaded guilty Friday were freed on bond and have
agreed to cooperate with the government in the remaining cases. They
most likely will testify against co-defendants at upcoming trials,
said Assistant U.S. Attorney Sheila Finnegan.
   David Skrodski, 32, a soybean broker, admitted that he defrauded
customers by making prearranged trades in 1987 that he profited from
with others charged in the alleged scheme. He could be sentenced to
a maximum of six years in prison and fined up to $350,000.
   Craig LaCrosse, a 40-year-old father of four, admitted that he
accepted an illegal prearranged trade from an undercover FBI agent
posing as a trader in August 1988. He also admitted that he ``aided
and abetted'' defendant James Nowak, accused of doctoring a trade to
make it look as though LaCrosse had been involved in the deal, as a
way to pay back money Nowak owed LaCrosse.
   Nowak was among the 12 soybean traders who pleaded innocent.
   LaCrosse also could face a maximum six-year prison term and
$350,000 fine.
   Michael Weiser, a 21-year-old soybean clerk, said he helped
execute prearranged trades between Nowak and the undercover agent in
August 1988, between Nowak and Skrodksi, and between Nowak and
defendant John Vercillo, who pleaded innocent.
   Weiser also pleaded guilty to failing to file an income-tax
return reporting his 1987 income _ approximately $7,700. He could be
sentenced to a maximum four-year prison term and fined $400,000 on
all charges.
   But prosecutors ``agreed that if he continues to provide
substantial assistance'' in the probe, they likely will seek a
lighter sentence, Ms. Finnegan said after the hearing.
   No sentencing date was set for the three.
   Besides Nowak, 47, and Vercillo, 44, soybean traders entering
innocent pleas Friday were: Scott Anixter, 40; Bradley Ashman, 28;
William Barcal III, 35; Charles Bergstrom, 42; Edward Cox III, 28;
Martin Dempsey, 52; Joel Fetchenhier, 49; Thomas Kenney, 35; Bruce
Mittelstadt, 49; and Sheldon Schneider, 46.
   Hart set a Feb. 5 trial date for the 12 traders.
</TEXT>
