<FIRST>u f AM-OilPrices     08-25 0244</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Oil Prices,0253</SECOND>
<HEAD>Oil Prices Slip Further</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Crude oil prices slipped Friday as traders
assumed a cautious stance ahead of an OPEC committee meeting next
month.
   The October contract for West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark
grade of crude oil, lost 10 cents to close at $18.51 a barrel on the
New York Mercantile Exchange, adding to a 19-cent slide on Thursday.
   Refined products traded on the exchange also closed lower.
   The September contract for home heating oil fell 0.27 cent to
settle at 51.43 cents a gallon, adding to a 0.21-cent decline
Thursday. Wholesale unleaded gasoline for September delivery dropped
0.85 to 53.30 cents a gallon, reversing a 0.22-cent rise the
previous session.
   The Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries has scheduled a
Sept. 23 meeting of its price monitoring committee, and although the
session is a month away and the panel has no power to change prices,
traders are already cautious, said Andrew Lebow, a senior broker and
analyst with E.D.&amp;F. Man International Futures Inc.
   The committee, which will meet in Geneva, can make
recommendations on oil prices _ including possible suggestions to
raise the OPEC benchmark price of $18 a barrel _ to the full
13-nation cartel.
   Lebow said some traders have been reluctant to take speculative
positions in the market because of the uncertainty raised by the
meeting.
   Gasoline futures declined Friday as demand slackened, and there
was little interest in the heating oil market, Lebow said.
</TEXT>
