<FIRST>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     08-25 0475</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Dollar-Gold,0487</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dollar Finishes Higher At Home, Gold Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished higher Friday in domestic
dealings after declining overseas.
   Gold prices moved sharply lower. On the Commodity Exchange in New
York, gold bullion for current delivery fell $3.80 to close at
$360.70 troy ounce. Republic National Bank of New York quoted a late
bid for gold of $360.25 an ounce, down from $362.40 late Thursday.
   Trading was quiet, but U.S. currency dealers said the dollar
moved within a wide range before closing on the highs of the day.
   Profit-taking in London, where a three-day holiday weekend was
about to begin, helped push the dollar down overseas.
   But traders in the United States interpreted the lower dollar as
a bargain and began buying the currency at midday, driving the price
up.
   ``There was a failure of the dollar to follow through on the down
side,'' said Bob Morrissey, a senior trader at the Bank of Boston's
New York office.
   Others agreed that sentiment toward the U.S. currency remains
bullish.
   ``There's no risk per se in holding dollars,'' said Michael
McDonald, a trader at Chicago-based Harris Trust &amp; Savings Bank.
``Money is flowing into Wall Street, into the bond market, and
people just like the dollar.''
   Traders expect the market to liven up next week with the
government's release of revised second-quarter gross national
product figures on Tuesday and August employment figures on Friday.
   In Tokyo, the dollar closed lower at 143.53 Japanese yen, down
from 143.60 late Thursday. Later in London, the dollar traded lower
at 143.25 yen. In New York, however, the dollar closed at 143.90
yen, up from 143.21 yen on Thursday.
   In London, one British pound cost $1.5725 late Friday, more
expensive for buyers than Thursday's late $1.5698. But in New York,
one pound cost $1.5660, cheaper than $1.5720 on Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late Thursday
included: 1.9630 West German marks, up from 1.9565; 1.6918 Swiss
francs, up from 1.6870; 6.6115 French francs, up from 6.5955;
1,405.63 Italian lire, up from 1,402.50, and 1.1746 Canadian
dollars, down from 1.1748.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday
included: 1.9540 West German Marks, down from 1.9585; 1.6840 Swiss
francs, down from 1.6880; 6.5895 French francs, down from 6.6060;
2.2055 Dutch guilders, down from 2.2095; 1,405.05 Italian lire, down
from 1,406.75; 1.1732 Canadian dollars, down from 1.1765.
   Gold prices fell. In London gold finished at a bid $360.45, down
from $362.75 late Thursday. In Zurich gold fell to $360.25 bid, from
$362.00. Earlier in Hong Kong, gold closed at $361.55 bid, down from
$364.15.
   Silver prices also slipped. On New York's Comex, silver for
current delivery fell to $5.108 a troy ounce from $5.166 on
Thursday. In London the metal traded at a bid $5.13 a troy ounce,
down from $5.17.
</TEXT>
