<SECOND>AM-Stocks-Glance,0291</SECOND>
<HEAD>Dow Jones Industrials Dip One Day After Setting Record</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here is a brief look at the stock market at the
end of a record-setting week for the Dow Jones average:
   _WHAT HAPPENED: Stocks dipped slightly Friday after rocketing
Thursday to a record for the Dow Jones industrial average of
2,734.64. The close on Friday was 2,732.36, a drop of 2.28 points.
Friday marked the second anniversary of the average's last peak,
which preceded the crash of October 1987. Declining issues
outnumbered advances by about 8 to 7 on the New York Stock Exchange,
and volume receded.
   _WHY: The market's recent rally has built on itself. Bullish
analysts say the outlook for corporate profits is good and the
economy is likely to navigate successfully between inflation and
recession. A follow-through to Thursday's rally was cut short by
wary investors who chose to cash in their recent gains.
   _THE WINNERS: Airline stocks, buoyed by takeover speculation
rather than solid economic fundamentals, have helped carry the
market upward in recent months. Airline stocks lagged in Thursday's
rally but surged ahead again Friday. UAL gained another $10 a share
to $278.
   _THE LOSERS: Precious metals stocks don't usually do well in bull
markets because paper brings a better return than gold and silver.
Mining companies like ASA and Hecla Mining lost ground on Thursday
and were little changed Friday.
   _WHAT'S AHEAD: Stock analysts will be keeping an eye on the
outlook for inflation and economic growth. The coming week will
bring a slew of economic statistics, including a revision of the
second-quarter gross national product, July personal income and
factory orders, and August unemployment figures.
</TEXT>
