<FIRST>u f AM-CommodityRdp 1stLd-Writethru f0273 08-25 0745</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Commodity Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru, f0273,0770</SECOND>
<HEAD>Low Expectations on Cocoa Conference Send Prices Lower</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS 1 graf after 9th graf pvs, `Copper futures ...,' to
ADD copper prices. Picks up 10th graf pvs, `In addition ...'.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HERBERT G. McCANN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Cocoa futures prices plunged Friday on New York's Coffee, Sugar &amp;
Cocoa Exchange as traders looked ahead to next month's meeting of
the International Cocoa Organization with an expectation of failure.
   On other markets, copper prices reached new contract highs, grain
and soybean futures plunged, precious metals declined, oil futures
were down and livestock and meat futures were mixed.
   Cocoa settled $37 to $47 lower with the contract for delivery in
September at $1,066 a metric ton.
   The selloff in cocoa futures followed ICO's revision of its
forecast for the 1988-1989 world cocoa surplus, raising the figure
by 40,000 metric tons to 263,000 metric tons from its May forecast.
   Arthur Stevenson, an analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. in New York, said speculators led Friday's selloff.
   ``The market is looking forward to the International Cocoa
Organization meeting in London next month,'' Stevenson said.
``Perhaps the organization can come up with new price support
measures. But the principal players (in the market) are looking at
it as a likely failure.''
   The ICO meeting of cocoa producers and consumers is to take place
Sept. 11.
   Cocoa prices have been depressed in recent years by five
consecutive years of surplus crops. The surplus has hurt the
economies of major cocoa-producing nations such as the Ivory Coast.
   Copper futures hit new contract highs on New York's Commodity
Exchange as production problems around the world continue to push up
prices.
   Copper was up by 4.70 cents to 6.80 cents, with the August
contract at $1.373 a pound.
   In addition to a paralyzing strike in Peru, copper production is
hampered by a strike at the Highland Valley mines in British
Columbia, Canada; the bankruptcy of Mexico's Cananea mine, which is
expected to be closed for up to three months; and the shutdown of
the Bougainville mines in Papua New Guinea due to terrorist
activities by landowners.
   ``Current production problems are so severe the rally will have
to continue through early September,'' said William O'Neill, an
analyst with Elders Futues Inc. in New York.
   Grain and soybean futures were lower in quiet trading on the
Chicago Board of Trade due to forecasts for rain in the plains
states and the Ohio Valley over the weekend and expectations of more
precipitation next week.
   Slack export sales and a drop in processor demand also were cited
as a cause of the selloff in soybeans and corn.
   The selloff in the corn and soybean pits spilled over into wheat
futures, where the lack of new export sales also hurt prices.
   Wheat was 3\ cents to 6\ cents lower with September at $3.90{ a
bushel; corn was 1\ cents to 1{ cents lower with September at $2.32}
a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 3\ cents lower with September at
$1.34} a bushel; soybeans were 1\ cent to 16\ cents lower with
September at $5.79{ a bushel.
   Precious metal futures continued their retreat on the Comex, with
gold $3.70 to $3.90 lower with August at $360.70 a troy ounce;
silver was 6 cents to 7.4 cents lower with September at $5.115 a
troy ounce.
   Oil futures closed lower in listless trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange.
   ``The market is awaiting an injection of fresh news,'' said Jim
Ritterbusch, an analyst with Carson Petroleum Co., a Chicago-area
oil distributor.
   Analysts say the general market tone is negative because of
overproduction by some members of the Organization of Petroleum
Exporting Countries.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil was 11 cents lower to 10 cents
higher with September at $17.94 a barrel; heating oil was .27 cents
lower to .24 cent higher with September at 51.43 cents a gallon;
unleaded gasoline was .28 cent to .85 cent lower with September at
53.30 cents a gallon.
   Livestock and pork futures where mixed in light trading on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .20 cent lower to .15 cent higher with September
at 73.60 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .03 cent to .43 cent
lower with August at 83.67 cents a pound; hogs were .30 cent lower
to .5 cent higher with October at 41.32 cents a pound; pork bellies
were .65 cent lower to .40 cent higher with February at 41.62 cents
a pound.
</TEXT>
