<FIRST>r f BC-BankFailures     08-25 0259</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Bank Failures,0269</SECOND>
<HEAD>Four More Texas Banks Fall; Hibernia Arrives In Texas</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DALLAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Hibernia Corp., a Louisiana bank holding company,
made its first entry into Texas on Thursday, buying one of four
banks shut down by regulators.
   Texas Banking Commissioner Kenneth W. Littlefield on Thursday
shut down First State Bank of Pflugerville, blaming weak
underwriting standards for the bank's loan losses, writedowns of
other real estate and heavy volume of non-performing assets.
   Littlefield also closed Troup Bank &amp; Trust Co. of Troup and
Summit Bank of San Antonio, citing liberal lending practices and
other problems. Federal regulators shut Park Central Bank in Fort
Worth.
   All four banks were turned over the Federal Deposit Insurance
Corp. The closures brought to 108 the number of failed banks in
Texas this year; 113 failed in 1988.
   In all cases, branches of the failed banks will reopen Friday as
branches of new institutions.
   At Summit and Park Central, however, only insured deposits were
transferred, leaving holders of about $2.2 million in deposits to
await the sale of the banks' assets before they can recoup their
money.
   First State-Pflugerville had $32 million in assets. Hibernia paid
$26,000 for the 56-year-old bank's $32 million in deposits, plus
agreed to buy assets worth about $8.8 million.
   The FDIC will advance Hibernia National Bank in Texas $23.2
million in assistance, and retain a like amount of assets to try to
recoup its cost.
   Hibernia is the largest bank in Louisiana and 81st largest in the
nation.
</TEXT>
