<FILEID>AP-NR-08-25-89 1925EDT</FILEID>
<FIRST>u f AM-UAL     08-25 0407</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-UAL,0422</SECOND>
<HEAD>Davis Outlines Bid; Analysts Say it Should Appeal to All</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDSEY TANNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   California investor Marvin Davis on Friday
outlined his $6.19 billion bid to buy UAL Corp. with details that at
least one analyst said should please everyone involved.
   Davis said the financing package for the $275-a-share deal
includes $7 billion in bank financing and $1 billion in equity to
cover the acquisition of United Airlines' parent, refinance certain
debts, provide working capital and pay related expenses.
   ``In addition, Mr. Davis has stated his intention to pursue an
Employee Stock Ownership Plan, in which all employee and labor
groups would be invited to participate, thereby rewarding them for
their role in building UAL and providing them with an additional
opportunity to benefit from their continued efforts on behalf of the
company,'' a statement said.
   ``With this financing information, the UAL board should now be in
a position to take action on our proposal,'' Davis said.
   He said he has asked UAL to advise him of its decision by the
close of business on Aug. 31.
   ``The financing plan is entirely consistent with our goals for
UAL: it allows for the continued implementation of UAL's growth and
expansion plans, including new aircraft and capital equipment, but
does not contemplate the disposition of any UAL assets, nor any
`bust-up' of the company, in whole or in part,'' he said.
   Joe Hopkins, a spokesman for Chicago-based UAL, declined to
comment on the plan.
   Also Friday, Davis met in his Los Angeles office with members of
the International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers,
which represents the biggest share of United workers.
   Davis is seeking their support for his bid, and a spokesman said
the meeting was ``constructive.''
   ``The Machinists people made Mr. Davis aware of some of their
concerns with respect to labor, and he gave them some assurances
with respect to the future of the airline,'' said the Davis
spokesman, who asked not to be identified.
   He said both sides plan additional meetings to discuss Davis' bid.
   The unions representing United machinists and the carrier's
pilots are considered crucial to any sale.
   Davis' decision to outline his financing plans likely was aimed
in part at discouraging other potential bidders, said Louis
Marckesano, an analyst with Janney Montgomery Scott Inc. in
Philadelphia.
   ``I think by announcing the full financing available ... he's
showing he could'' go even higher, said Marckesano.
</TEXT>
