<FIRST>r f BC-SingerChairman     08-25 0192</FIRST>
<SECOND>BC-Singer Chairman,0201</SECOND>
<HEAD>Successor to Bilzerian Named by Singer Co.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former railroad and oil company executive
was named Friday as chairman of Singer Co. to succeed corporate
raider Paul A. Bilzerian, who was convicted of securities fraud
charges.
   The election of Walter A. Drexel was announced by the board of
the Tampa-based defense contractor.
   Drexel was most recently the vice chairman and chief executive
officer of Burlington Northern Railroad. Before that, Drexel was
with Atlantic Richfield Co. for 23 years.
   Bilzerian was convicted in June of securities fraud arising from
information spun off from the Ivan Boesky insider trader scandal.
   Bilzerian's case was also the first felony prosecution of stock
``parking,'' in which parties try to conceal the sale or transfer of
securities.
   The takeover specialist was found guilty on nine counts of
breaking securities and tax laws and making false statements in
connection with three failed takeovers and one other transactions in
1985 and 1986.
   Bilzerian no longer has any links to Singer, said company
spokeswoman Janet Rogan.
   Singer also announced Friday the resignation of Robert Kent
Scott, senior vice president, general counsel and secretary.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
